<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-01 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEHAMA, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The feature race at Mehama's summer fest
wasn't exactly a display of blazing speed, but they didn't call it
the Slug and Scotch Broom Festival for nothing.
   Humor helped make up for the lack of action in the race
Saturday, in which the first of the critters to ooze its way out of
a ring was declared winner.
   ``He was going pretty fast, wasn't he?'' said Daniel Urquhart,
8, of Aumsville, whose slug crept to the championship.
   Rick Urquhart, father of the winning slug trainer, said he found
the racer at a state park.
   ``We definitely searched high and low for this one. We didn't
take any backyard varieties,'' he said. ``We'll probably retire
this one for the year. Maybe we'll catch the same one next year.''
   The festival, the town's first in 30 years, was the brainchild
of businessmen Mike Boyles and Bill Mercer, who came up with the
idea over a drink at Mercer's Fish Hatchery Tavern.
   ``I was talking about how I was glad scotch broom season was
over, and he said something about how slugs oughta be banned, and
it just came together,'' said Boyles. Scotch broom is a bushlike
weed with small yellow flowers that grows along roadways.
   ``I guess we were kind of bored,'' Boyles said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 14 feet tall and 30 feet long,
Wilbir stands out from other peacocks.
   Of course, it's foliage, not plumage that Wilbir shows off, and
he can't strut around because he's a peat sculpture.
   With 2,000 begonias blooming on his chest, head and tail, he has
drawn some surprised looks at Michigan State University's new
Horticulture Demonstration Gardens.
   ``When I first saw it, I thought it was a dinosaur,'' said
Bobbie Haskell, who came for an evening walk in the gardens over
the weekend.
   ``We put in the peacock to get a little attention and show how
spectacular it's going to be,'' said Michigan State horticulture
Professor Will Carlson.
   Wilbir is short for ``Will's Bird,'' after Carlson, who is in
charge of the five-year project to construct the new garden.
   ``It will be a world-class garden. It will probably be one of
the finest in this country,'' he said.
   When finished in 1993, flowers will bloom over 7{ acres and
Wilbir will be the centerpiece of the garden's circular entrance
pavilion.
</TEXT>
