<FIRST>r i PM-SlainHostages     08-01 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slain Hostages,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Other Foreign Hostages Slain Since 1985</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before this week's report that Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins was hanged, at least eight other foreign kidnap
victims, including two Americans, had been killed by their
abductors in Lebanon.
   Here is a brief review:
   _William Buckley, 57, the CIA Beirut station chief, was
kidnapped March 16, 1984. The pro-Iranian Shiite group Islamic
Jihad claimed Oct. 4, 1985, it killed him, but no body was found.
On Jan. 20, 1987, Vice President George Bush confirmed that Buckley
had been killed. A bachelor from Medford, Mass., Buckley was
assigned to the U.S. Embassy in Beirut in 1983.
   _Peter Kilburn, 62, of San Francisco, a librarian at the
American University of Beirut, disappeared Dec. 3, 1984, and was
found shot to death with two British hostages April 17, 1986. A
nearby note said a group called Arab Revolutionary Cells killed
them in retaliation for the U.S. air attack on Libya two days
earlier.
   _Leigh Douglas, 34, a British professor at the American
University of Beirut, disappeared March 28, 1986, in west Beirut.
He was found shot dead with Kilburn.
   _Philip Padfield, 40, a British language teacher, disappeared at
the same time as Douglas. He also was found dead with Kilburn.
   _Nicolas Kluiters, a Dutch Roman Catholic priest, disappeared in
eastern Lebanon March 14, 1985. His body was found strangled in the
area April 1, 1985.
   _Denis Hill, a Briton who taught English at the American
University of Beirut, failed to show up for work May 27, 1985, and
was found shot to death May 29, 1985.
   _Arkady Katkov, 32, a cultural attache at the Soviet Embassy in
Beirut, was abducted Sept. 30, 1985, with three other Soviet
diplomats and was found murdered Oct. 2 in a west Beirut suburb.
The three other Soviets were freed.
   _Michel Seurat, a French academic researcher, was kidnapped May
22, 1985. On March 5, 1986, an Islamic Jihad statement claimed
Seurat, 39, had been ``executed.'' His wife later confirmed that
French officials told her he was dead.
   In addition, the British Foreign Office says it also seeks word
on Alec Collett, a New York-based British journalist on assignment
with a U.N. relief agency who was kidnapped March 25, 1985, in
south Lebanon. His Palestinian abductors claimed April 23, 1986,
that they had killed him, but his body was never found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
