<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages-Chronology     08-01 1190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Chronology,1247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Years of Abductions, Threats, Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the holding of American kidnap
victims in Lebanon:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   FEB. 10 _ Frank Regier, engineering professor at American
University in Beirut, abducted near west Beirut campus.
   FEB. 26 _ U.S. Marines withdraw from Beirut.
   MARCH 7 _ Jeremy Levin, Beirut chief for U.S. Cable News
Network, kidnapped as walks to work in west Beirut.
   MARCH 16 _ Gunmen abduct U.S. Embassy political officer William
Buckley outside home in west Beirut.
   APRIL 15 _ Regier and kidnapped Frenchman Christian Joubert gain
freedom from unidentified captors. Shiite Amal militia claims
credit for rescue.
   MAY 8 _ Kidnappers overpower American Presbyterian pastor
Benjamin Weir on west Beirut street and carry him off.
   MAY 9 _ Anonymous caller to French news agency claims Islamic
Jihad, shadowy anti-Western group of Shiite Moslems, holds Buckley,
Levin, Weir.
   SEPT. 20 _ Car-bomb at U.S. Embassy annex in east Beirut kills
at least 14 people, including two Americans.
   DEC. 3 _ American University librarian Peter Kilburn fails to
report to work. It is later claimed he was kidnapped by Islamic
Jihad.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 8 _ Rev. Lawrence Martin Jenco, Roman Catholic priest,
abducted from car by gunmen in Beirut. Anonymous caller later says
Jenco and four other missing Americans will be freed ``if all
Americans leave Lebanon.''
   FEB. 14 _ Levin gains freedom in Lebanon and is turned over to
U.S. authorities by Syria. He says he escaped; Islamic Jihad says
it freed him.
   MARCH 16 _ Terry Anderson, chief Mideast correspondent of The
Associated Press, abducted on Beirut street. Caller says Islamic
Jihad kidnapped Anderson.
   MAY 16 _ Islamic Jihad warns of ``catastrophic consequences''
for hostages if Kuwait does not free 17 Islamic Jihad comrades
jailed in Kuwait for December 1983 bombing of U.S. and French
embassies there.
   MAY 28 _ Gunmen kidnap David P. Jacobsen, American director of
American University Hospital, as he walks to work in west Beirut.
   MAY 30 _ Caller claiming to represent Islamic Jihad says group
killed Denis Hill, British teacher of English at American
University who disappeared May 27 and was later found shot in head,
and holds Jacobsen.
   JUNE 10 _ Gunmen on Beirut airport highway kidnap American
Thomas Sutherland, acting agriculture dean at American University.
   JUNE 30 _ Lebanese terrorists free last 39 hostages from TWA
jetliner they hijacked and forced to Beirut.
   SEPT. 9 _ President Reagan announces Weir has been freed after
16 months in captivity.
   OCT. 4 _ Islamic Jihad claims it has killed Buckley in
retaliation for Israeli air raid on PLO headquarters in Tunisia. It
later releases photographs it says show Buckley's body, and offers
to turn body over to United Nations if Israel releases 100
Palestinian prisoners.
   NOV. 8 _ In open letter, four captive Americans _ Anderson,
Jenco, Jacobsen and Sutherland _ call on Reagan to ``have mercy''
and negotiate with kidnappers.
   NOV. 13 _ Church of England official Terry Waite begins
mediation to try to gain hostages' release, shuttling among Beirut,
Washington and European capitals.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   APRIL 17 _ Kilburn and two other hostages, British educators
Leigh Douglas and Philip Padfield, found shot to death east of
Beirut. Note says Arab Revolutionary Cells killed them in
retaliation for April 15 U.S. air attack on Libya.
   APRIL 23 _ Revolutionary Organization of Socialist Moslems says
it has killed kidnapped British journalist Alec Collett in
retaliation for British complicity in U.S. attack on Libya.
Videotape purporting to show him hanged is made public. Collett, on
assignment with U.N. relief agency, was kidnapped March 25, 1985.
   JULY 26 _ Jenco freed. He later delivers confidential message to
Reagan from kidnappers.
   SEPT. 9 _ American educator Frank Herbert Reed kidnapped in west
Beirut.
   SEPT. 12 _ American University accountant Joseph Cicippio
abducted on west Beirut campus. Callers claim responsibility for
both Reed and Cicippio abductions in name of two groups _
Resurrection Cells, and Arab Revolutionary Cells-Omar Moukhtar
Forces. Later, Revolutionary Justice Organization claims
responsibility for kidnapping of Cicippio.
   OCT. 21 _ Revolutionary Justice Organization claims to have
kidnapped another American in Beirut, writer Edward Austin Tracy.
   NOV. 2 _ Jacobsen is released in Beirut. Islamic Jihad says U.S.
must continue pursuing ``current approaches'' to win freedom for
other hostages.
   NOV. 3 _ First reports surface that U.S., beginning in 1985,
arranged arms shipments to Iran in exchange for hostage releases.
   NOV. 28 _ Iran's Parliament speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, says
Tehran government will help free hostages if Washington returns
frozen Iranian assets in U.S. Talks on returning frozen U.S. assets
to Iran are later suspended.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 20 _ Vice President George Bush says hostage Buckley died
after torture. Anglican Church mediator Waite drops from sight in
Beirut. Unconfirmed reports say he is captive of extremists.
   JAN. 24 _ Three Americans _ Jesse Jonathan Turner, Alann Steen
and Robert Polhill _ and Indian Mithileshwar Singh, all faculty
members of Beirut University College, are kidnapped from the
campus. Group calling itself Islamic Jihad for Liberation of
Palestine claims responsibility.
   FEB. 9 _ Islamic Jihad for Liberation of Palestine, threatening
to kill Turner, Steen, Polhill and Singh unless Israel frees Arab
prisoners, ``postpones'' the act just before deadline.
   MARCH 26 _ Videotape released in which Turner says fellow
hostage Steen is ill and dying, and urging release of Arab
prisoners in Israel in exchange for hostages' freedom.
   JUNE 17 _ American journalist Charles Glass, on leave from his
job at ABC News, is kidnapped in west Beirut. He escapes two months
later.
   DEC. 24 _ Kidnappers issue videotape of Anderson in which he
appeals to President Reagan to win the hostages' release, saying,
``There is a limit for how long we can last.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   FEB. 17 _ U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, chief of
observer unit attached to U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon, is
seized by gunmen on southern Lebanese highway. The Organization of
Oppressed on Earth claims to hold him and demands release of
prisoners held by Israel.
   MAY 4 _ The last three French hostages in Lebanon are set free.
They say a fourth French hostage, Michel Seurat, died in captivity.
French Premier Michel Rocard later says France will re-establish
diplomatic relations with Iran.
   OCT. 3 _ Indian professor Mithileshwar Singh is freed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   MARCH 3 _ Lebanon's most influential Shiite Moslem cleric, Sheik
Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, says the foreign hostages should be
freed because ``abduction is wrong.''
   JUNE 8 _ Iran's Parliament speaker, Hashemi Rafsanjani, says
Iran will help free American hostages in Lebanon if the United
States tries to win freedom for Iranians held by Christian forces
in Lebanon.
   JULY 28 _ Israeli commandos abduct Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a
Shiite Moslem cleric and a leader of the Hezbollah, from his home
in south Lebanon.
   JULY 30 _ Organization of the Oppressed on Earth threatens to
kill Higgins if Obeid is not freed.
   JULY 31 _ Organization of the Oppressed on Earth says Higgins
has been killed, releases videotape purporting to show his hanged
body. Revolutionary Justice Organization threatens to kill Cicippio
if Shiite cleric is not freed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
