<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sylvester Stallone says he isn't trying to avoid
romantic commitments because of his failed marriage to Brigitte
Nielsen. He just hasn't found the right girl.
   ``I need something like Sister Mary Theresa and Madam Curie and,
uh ... Irma La Douce, a little bit of everything,'' the actor said
in an interview to be broadcast on ABC's ``Good Morning America''
this week.
   Stallone says he appreciates ``the fair sex'' because women
``have a vast understanding of the way I think.''
   ``They are, by chemical composition, more emotional, so they
tend to be a little bit more compassionate, very work-oriented,''
he said. ``I think women strive very hard to show that they
certainly can carry on any endeavor that a man can. So I only
benefit by being surrounded by these kinds of people.''
   Stallone says he has pretty much recovered from his divorce from
Nielsen and isn't attempting to avoid any new commitment ``if that
comes along. I mean 'cause what really, what else is there?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DODGE CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Charlie Daniels says many
working people have had their fill with the state of the nation.
   ``People in this country are fed up,'' Daniels said during a
weekend concert appearance at Dodge City. ``I know because I talk
to people. I'm on the road all the time. I'm talking to the people
out there.''
   ``They're sick and tired of child abuse. They're sick and tired
of drugs. They're sick and tired of murders. They're sick, sick,
sick of it.''
   His band's appearance included the first concert performance of
a new song, ``Simple Man,'' title track from an upcoming album.
   ``We appeal to the blue collar people out there,'' Daniels said.
``They're the ones who make this country run. I think I can play
for them because I am a working man. I come from a long line of
farmers and timbermen. That's where my heart is, with those people
who get up in the morning and go to work.''
   At 52, Daniels says he feels more creative than ever.
   ``I thank God every day of my life that I enjoy the business I'm
in so much,'' he said. ``I'm going to keep doing this as long as I
can.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch has joined the list of
Leona Helmsley's detractors, calling the hotel queen ``the wicked
witch of the West'' for behavior unbecoming a billionaire.
   For ``a billionaire to be so chintzy, distresses people,'' the
mayor said Monday.
   The mayor emphasized that his opinion had nothing to do with
whether she is guilty of tax evasion, for which she is being tried
in federal court.
   ``That's for a jury to decide,'' he said, adding: ``It's just
her chintziness. It's a case involving the wicked witch of the
West.''
   Koch also commented on the justice system. ``Rich people hire
the best lawyers and therefore, they have better defenses,'' he
said. ``So in that sense there is an inequity. But rich people go
to jail.''
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, heads a $5 billion real estate and hotel
empire with her 80-year-old husband, Harry. She is accused of
evading taxes by disguising millions of dollars of renovations at
their Connecticut estate and other personal items as business
expenses. Her husband was found mentally incompetent to stand trial.
