<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     08-01 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monthly Index Shows Prices Decline for July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department's monthly index
shows prices farmers received for raw products dropped 0.7 percent
in July from a month earlier, but were up 2.8 percent from a year
ago.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in its
preliminary report Monday that declining prices for oranges,
broilers, soybeans and corn were partially offset by higher prices
for potatoes, cotton, tomatoes and hogs.
   The July index of prices paid for commodities and services,
interest, taxes and farm wage rates was 178 percent of its 1977
average. The index was 0.6 percent above April and 3.5 percent
above July 1988.
   ``Higher prices during July for feeder cattle and calves,
gasoline and building materials were partially offset by lower feed
prices,'' the report said.
   Based on the preliminary figures, the price index for livestock
and livestock products as a group declined 0.6 percent from June to
July but still averaged 6.1 percent above last year's figure.
   Overall crop prices declined 2.9 percent from last month and 2.2
percent from July 1988.
   The all-fruit index was down 20 percent from last month and 19
percent from a year ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture says it's
working on a way to find out how much soil is blowing in the wind.
   By the mid-1990s, the department's scientists plan to have a
wind erosion computer system to help make daily estimates of soil
losses from wind erosion, says Lawrence J. Hagen, an agricultural
engineer with the USDA's agricultural research service.
   ``The system should also be helpful for managing rangelands and
croplands in humid as well as dry areas,'' he said.
   In the future, according to Hagen, the wind erosion system could
be linked to other computers to help compute the effects of dust on
the acid rain process, calculate economic costs of erosion and
assess management strategies for public lands.
   The USDA says semi-arid to humid croplands outside the Great
Plains often threatened by wind erosion include much of the
southeastern seaboard; sandy and organic soil areas of Michigan,
Wisconsin and Minnesota; lakebed soils of Ohio, Michigan, Minnesota
and North Dakota; the Palouse region of the Pacific Northwest and
several irrigated valleys of California.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rotating grain crops, such as corn with
alfalfa, is a key strategy for sustaining agriculture in the long
run, according to a new study by the U.S. Department of Agriculture
and Cornell University scientists.
   ``Crop rotation may be the answer to sustaining long-term
productivity of our land to provide billions of people with food,
fuel and other renewable resources,'' says Gary H. Heichel, a plant
physiologist with the USDA's agricultural research service.
   He says the study analyzes energy uses of various farming
systems, including continuous corn crops and various rotations of
grain and legume crops. Continuous corn can be highly productive
with the use of nitrogen fertilizer, he says, adding ``but is of
dubious sustainability because of high fossil fuel use and soil
erosion.''
   ``On the other hand,'' Heichel said, ``legumes are among the
most efficient crops grown in the United States, partly because
little fuel is required to grow them. Also more energy is embodied
in farming equipment needed to grow other crops such as corn.''
   More than 3 million calories of fossil fuel energy normally are
required to produce nitrogen fertilizer for an acre of corn grown
under a continuous cropping program, said David Pimentel, an
ecologist and entomologist at Cornell University. ``But a crop
rotation that alternates one crop of soybeans, which normally
requires no nitrogen fertilizer, with two crops of corn could
reduce fossil energy use by 26 percent.''
</TEXT>
