<FIRST>r w PM-Biden-Drugs     08-01 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Biden-Drugs,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biden: Bush Breeding Cynicism in War on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is breeding cynicism in the war
on drugs by calling for laws that already are on the books and
failing to seek full funding of drug legislation, says the chairman
of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   ``The war of words, what has it wrought?'' asked Sen. Joseph R.
Biden Jr., D-Del. ``What it has wrought so far is cynicism,
political opportunism, and some despair.''
   Bush ``is able to stand up at his inauguration and say, `This
scourge will end,' and then have no one `call' him when he refuses
to use the tools already available to him to fight the war on
drugs,'' Biden said Monday in a speech at the National Press Club.
   Bush sought to cut $10 million in funds for the Law Enforcement
Training Institute at Glynco, Ga., even as he traveled there to
praise the institute and call for new anti-crime legislation, Biden
said.
   Among the laws sought by Bush that Congress already has passed,
Biden contended, are longer sentences for drug dealers, the death
penalty for some drug dealers, minimum prison terms for weapons
offenders and preventive detention for people arrested with drugs.
   Congress passed such laws in 1984, 1986 and 1988, ``all by
bipartisan support, and neither party in Congress at the time tried
to take political advantage for them having been passed,'' Biden
said.
   Alixe Glen, a White House spokeswoman, said, ``The crime package
that the president sent to the Hill is a decisive, effective and
achievable package, and it is a very comprehensive program to
combat crime.
   ``Bush's plan doubles the mandatory penalty for the use of a
semiautomatic weapon, completely reforms plea-bargaining
practices,'' she said. ``The death penalty may be a law on the
books, but the procedures necessary to implement the death penalty
would be activated by Bush's plan.''
   In addition, she said, the package adds nearly 1,000 federal
agents to law enforcement agencies.
   Biden said the 1988 anti-drug legislation called for the
addition of almost 3,000 agents to federal law enforcement agencies
and for treatment beds for nearly 250,000 addicts.
   ``But in 1989, Mr. President ... you failed to put in your
budget the money need to make these tough laws work,'' Biden said.
``You didn't even ask for them to be funded after you praised them
in the election campaign.''
   Biden said $1.8 billion must be found in the current fiscal year
to fully fund the 1988 anti-drug bill, even if it means raising
taxes to pay for it. By contrast, he noted, the bailout plan for
the savings and loan industry will cost several billion dollars,
and each B-2 bomber sought by the administration costs $530 million.
   Larry Cirignano, a spokesman for William J. Bennett, director of
the Office of National Drug Control Policy, said after the speech
that he had no comment on the remarks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
