<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-FSX     08-01 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-FSX,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Effort to Override FSX Veto Becoming `Turf Battle': Byrd</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers are waging what appears to be a
futile effort to override President Bush's veto of legislation
putting conditions on joint production with Japan of the FSX jet
fighter.
   Bush vetoed the advanced fighter Monday, declaring that its
binding terms would ``tie my hands in the exercise of my
constitutional responsibilities.''
   The $6 billion FSX agreement, negotiated by the administration
earlier this year, calls for development by General Dynamics and
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of an advanced version of the F-16
fighter, intended to be deployed by Japan in the late 1990s.
   Opponents denounced the deal as a giveaway of critical U.S.
defense technology and predicted it would result in the eventual
loss of thousands of jobs in the U.S. aerospace industry.
   A House measure to restrict the agreement was passed in early
June on a 262-155 vote, far less than the two-thirds margin of 290
needed to override a veto in the 435-member chamber.
   An identical Senate resolution was adopted 72-27.
   Bush said the legislation would inject the General Accounting
Office, a legislative agency, into the administration of the FSX
program ``in a highly intrusive manner,'' trammeling the
constitutional powers of the president.
   ``I'm sorry this whole matter is being vetoed as a result of a
turf battle,'' said Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.
   Noting that Bush's ``most violent'' objections stem from fears
of congressional infringement into his authority to negotiate with
foreign powers, Byrd said the bill doesn't infringe on the
president's constitutional prerogatives.
   The Constitution, Byrd said, gives Congress the right to
regulate foreign commerce. The courts have held that power includes
the ability to ban or regulate specified foreign commerce, he said.
   ``This legislation actually strengthens the president's position
for future negotiations with the Japanese,'' Byrd said. ``Yet the
president has, ironically, chosen to veto essentially our support
and reinforcement of his own policy on this issue.''
   The legislation bars the transfer of certain engine technologies
to Japan and prohibits the sale or transfer of the FSX to third
nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
