<FIRST>r i PM-Hostage-List 1stLd-Writethru a0411 08-01 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostage-List, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0411,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>List of Foreigners Believed to be Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: ADDS Collett entry under British. ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreigners believed held by kidnappers in Lebanon:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>AMERICAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985. A Shiite Moslem group,
the pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, claims to hold
him.
   Thomas Sutherland, 58, Scottish-born acting dean of agriculture
at the American University of Beirut, June 9, 1985. Islamic Jihad
claims to hold him.
   Frank Herbert Reed, 58, director of the private Lebanon
International School in Beirut, kidnapped Sept. 9, 1986. A
pro-Libyan group called Arab Revolutionary Cells-Omar Moukhtar
Forces claimed responsibility.
   Joseph James Cicippio, 58, acting comptroller of the American
University of Beirut, kidnapped Sept. 12, 1986. The pro-Iranian
Revolutionary Justice Organization, a Shiite group, claimed
responsibility.
   Edward Austin Tracy, 58, author of children's books. Date of
kidnapping unclear, but the Revolutionary Justice Organization
claimed responsibility Oct. 21, 1986.
   Jesse Turner, 42, visiting professor of mathematics and computer
science at Beirut University College, kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987, from
university campus along with Robert Polhill, Alann Steen and
Mithileshwar Singh, by gunmen posing as policemen. Pro-Iranian
Shiite faction, Islamic Jihad for the Liberation of Palestine,
claimed responsibility.
   Alann Steen, 50, journalism professor at Beirut University
College, kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987.
   Robert Polhill, 55, assistant professor of business and lecturer
in accounting at Beirut University College, kidnapped Jan. 24, 1987
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BRITISH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Alec Collett, 67, New York-based journalist on assignment with
the United Nations Relief and Works Agency, kidnapped March 25,
1985. The Revolutionary Organization of Socialist Moslems, believed
to be linked to Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal, claimed on April
23, 1986 that he had been hanged in retaliation for the April 15
U.S. air raid on Libya. It released a videotape purportedly showing
Collett hanging from a scaffold, but his body was never found. His
family and Britain's Foreign Office believe he is dead.
   John McCarthy, 32, producer for London-based Worldwide
Television News agency, April 17, 1986. No group has claimed his
abduction.
   Terry Waite, 50, envoy of the Anglican Church who had been
seeking the release of foreign hostages, disappeared Jan. 20, 1987
after leaving his west Beirut hotel to negotiate with Islamic
Jihad. He is believed held by Islamic Jihad, though no group has
claimed responsibility for his abduction or made demands for his
release.
   Jack Mann, 75, missing in west Beirut since May 12, 1989. Cells
of Armed Struggle claimed same day it had kidnapped a Briton, but
did not name him.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>IRISH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Keenan, 32, an English language teacher at the American
University of Beirut, kidnapped April 11, 1986. No group has
claimed to hold him, but he was seen being seized by armed men in
Beirut. He comes from British-ruled Northern Ireland, but also
holds an Irish passport.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ITALIAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Alberto Molinari, age unknown, businessman who dealt with
insurance and import-export trade, kidnapped Sept. 11, 1985. No
claim of responsibility for his kidnapping.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WEST GERMAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   West German relief workers Heinrich Struebig, 48, and Thomas
Kemptner, 28, kidnapped with nurse Petra Schnitzler near Sidon May
16, 1989. Struebig and Schnitzler had been seized May 4 with
another German, but were freed May 5. In second abduction,
Schnitzler freed few hours later when militiamen stopped car in
which she was hidden in trunk. Kidnappings reportedly linked to
trial in West Germany of Mohammad Ali Hamadi on charges of
involvement in 1985 TWA hijack. He was sentenced to life
imprisonment May 17, 1989, one day after second kidnapping. No
group has claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
