<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-01 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar recovered slightly after opening sharply
lower against the Japanese yen in Tokyo Tuesday, while stock prices
dipped.
   The U.S. currency began the day at 135.95 yen, its lowest
opening level since the 135.40 yen registered on May 12, and 2.45
yen below its closing figure Monday. It then edged up in quiet
trading, ending the day at 136.65 yen for a loss of 1.75 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average
closed at 34,898.46, down 55.41 points from its record-high closing
on Monday.
   Traders said the dollar's plunge followed its similar downward
direction in overseas markets because of a drop in U.S. interest
rates.
   ``The major contributing factor to the dollar's sharp decline is
lowering U.S. interest rates,'' said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, who spoke anonymously.
   He said activity was light in the Tokyo market as some companies
began their summer vacations this week.
   Several major U.S. banks, including Chemical Bank and
Continental Bank, lowered their prime rate to 10.5 percent from
11.0 percent Monday.
   The prime rate is watched closely as bankers use it as a basis
for calculating loans to businesses and for determining many types
of fixed and adjustable-rate consumer loans.
</TEXT>
