<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--ZookeeperTrampled     08-01 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Zookeeper Trampled,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irritable Elephant Tramples Zookeeper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African elephant that was being treated for
eating too much dirt lost her patience and kicked a zookeeper,
breaking his right leg.
   But Henry Kacprzyk was philosophical about his injury.
   ``What really happened (is) she got fed up with the treatments.
She's smart,'' said Kacprzyk, 35.
   Pittsburgh Zoo officials said the 4,100 pound elephant Tribby
was suffering from ``sand impaction,'' which causes diarrhea.
   Kacprzyk and another zookeeper, Diane Hagey, were trying to
chain two of the elephant's legs Friday before giving her extra
water, oral medicine and a high-fiber diet when she used a hind leg
to kick Kacprzyk several times.
   ``Elephants are very powerful animals, very intelligent
animals,'' said zoo Director Charles Wikenhauser. ``This was a
reaction.''
   He said the elephant was feeling better this week.
   Kacprzyk was hospitalized and also suffered cuts and bruises.
</TEXT>
