<FIRST>r a PM-Governors-Notebook     08-01 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governors-Notebook,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor's Meeting is Reunion Time For Bush's Chief of Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Governors, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's quick trip to the governors
conference brought a reunion for the governors with their former
chairman, John Sununu.
   The former governor of New Hampshire, who a year ago was
presiding over the National Governors' Association, successfully
guided Bush's candidacy through the minefields of the New Hampshire
primary last year and after the election became White House chief
of staff.
   He took a seat at the governors' table next to Bush on Monday _
and came in for some pointed ribbing from his former colleagues.
   ``He is the same easy-going, soft-spoken, self-effacing man we
knew as governor of New Hampshire,'' said Virginia Gov. Gerald
Baliles, a Democrat. He he drew laughter from governors of both
parties, many of whose recollections of Sununu were more of a
prickly and short-tempered leader.
   Sununu merely grinned and raised his arms in a shrug.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush, who acknowledged that Sununu was ``not quiet and
retiring'' also had words for Virginia's Baliles, who was stepping
down after a year as chairman of the association.
   ``I studied Latin for four years,'' Bush said. ``Soon you will
be chairman emeritus. `E' in Latin means out; `meritus,' damn well
deserves to be.''
   Baliles will soon be a governor emeritus too. He leaves office
after the end of this year after a single four year term. He
mentioned several times during the governors' four-day conference
that it was Virginia's constitution, and not his choice, that ws
prompting his retirement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The president appeared a bit startled when he saw Ohio's
governor, Democrat Richard Celeste. And he wasn't the only one.
   Celeste returned from a fishing trip on Lake Erie three weeks
ago sporting a full salt-and-pepper beard.
   Calling on Celeste for a question after his speech, Bush said,
``I didn't recognize you.''
   Afterward, Bush walked around the row of tables arranged in a
square where the governors sat and shook hands with each. He
stopped briefly at Celeste and remarked again.
   ``He said, `I don't care what anyone else says, I like it,'''
Celeste reported.
   The Ohio Democrat, who under state law can not seek a third term
next year, said he intends to keep the beard for a while.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walking around the assembled governors, Bush also came face to
face with the man he defeated last November, Democrat Michael
Dukakis of Massachusetts.
   The two shook hands and exchanged nothing more than
pleasantries, Dukakis aide Mark Gearan said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>---</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, who is leaving office after two
terms at the end of this year, was greeted with effuse public
praise by his colleagues during the conference. Kean, a moderate
Republican, was praised no less by Democrats than Republicans.
   But New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, who enthusiastically joined in
the chorus, interrupted his own praise for Kean to add a bit of
explanation.
   ``It probably is a little easier to talk kindly about
Republicans when they're on their way out,'' Cuomo said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
