<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0459EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     08-01 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Jam Museum to View Uprising Exhibit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people jammed into a military museum
today to view a new exhibit devoted to the pro-democracy uprising,
while citizens generally ignored celebrating the anniversary of the
army.
   Nearly 6,000 people visited the Military Museum of the Chinese
People's Revolution in just three hours, compared with 3,000 to
4,000 visitors on an average day, museum employees said.
   Crowds gathered four or five deep in front of the displays of
the seven-week student movement, pointing at black-and-white photos
of marches that drew up to 1 million people.
   ``Look, that's Chai Ling,'' one young man said to a girl as he
pointed to a photo of one of the student leaders.
   The pro-democracy movement was crushed June 3-4 by the army,
which killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in clearing central
Beijing of protesters. The government has since portrayed the army
as having heroically ended an uprising organized by thugs.
   Those who managed to get close to the museum exhibits bent over
glass cases, carefully reading the petitions, handbills and posters
calling for greater freedoms.
   The exhibit, which occupies one wing of the museum's second
floor, included loudspeakers, a printing press, a computer, several
portable phones and weapons that allegedly were confiscated from
the students.
   It also showed rows of battered army helmets, mangled rifles
with broken butts and blood-soaked army uniforms.
   More than half of the exhibit was devoted to displays showing
the bravery and the patience of the army and the leadership of the
party since the crackdown. But few people lingered long in front of
those displays.
   The museum was one of the few places where crowds gathered on
Army Day, which marks the Aug. 1, 1927 founding of what later
became the People's Liberation Army.
   It has never been considered one of China's major holidays. But
this year, the hype was building for weeks as the government tried
to shore up the army's image and prestige in the wake of the
crackdown.
   The media has given prominent play to leaders' exhortations that
Army Day be especially festive this year, but in the streets of the
capital today there was little outward celebration.
   City officials had suggested that central Tiananmen Square would
be filled with soldiers taking part in grand Army Day celebrations,
but there was little activity in vast plaza that was the focus of
the pro-democracy protests.
   Several hundred soldiers attended an early morning awards
ceremony, but the event was brief and lackluster.
   Soldiers stood facing a single red banner as a tape-recording of
the national anthem played. A leader gave a speech as bicyclists
hurried past the square to work. Twenty minutes later, the square
was empty again.
   The biggest celebration of Army Day was in the nation's
newspapers, almost all of which carried front-page editorials
praising the army's patriotism and its heroic exploits in history
and during the recent turmoil, which the government calls a
``counter-revolutionary rebellion.''
   ``Officers and soldiers have stood up to all tests and used
their blood and lives to protect ... the party ... and the people's
power and safety,'' said a People's Daily editorial.
   The People's Daily and other newspapers stressed the need for
good relations between the army and the masses.
   ``The recent counter-revolutionary rebellion taught us that .. .
the army cannot be separated from the people ... that only with the
support of the people can the army surmount obstacles and complete
its mission,'' the People's Daily said.
</TEXT>
