<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0506EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-01 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dives, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today
on predictions of lower U.S. interest rates, traders said, while
prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined moderately.
   The U.S. currency opened at 135.95 yen, 2.45 yen below its close
of 138.40 yen on Monday. It was the dollar's lowest opening since
May 12, when it started trading at 135.40 yen. It closed at 136.65
yen after ranging between 135.80 and 136.96 yen.
   The dollar now has fallen 2.80 yen in two days.
   ``Many participants began the day selling the dollar because of
the impact from overseas markets, where it also was sold
overnight,'' said Nobuhiko Hibara of the Bank of Tokyo. ``But then
the dollar began edging up, and the general trend of the rest of
the day was recovery.''
   Traders said the dollar's losses were linked to reports of
falling interest rates in the United States, while its rebound was
due in part to profit-taking.
   ``The major contributing factor to the dollar's sharp decline
was lowering U.S. interest rates,'' said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said activity was light on the Tokyo market as some companies
began their summer vacations this week.
   Traders said the dollar appeared to have weathered an attempt to
test its lower limits, but many said they expect another attempt
this week.
   ``Whether or not there is another attempt at the low end is very
important to the trend from now on,'' said Michiko Kawai, chief
corporate trader at Security Pacific National Bank in Tokyo.
   ``There was a good chance that if the dollar had gone below
135.80 yen, we would have gone on down to 135 yen, but it didn't
work that way, at least on the first try,'' said another dealer,
also speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told a news conference
Tuesday that the dollar's recent decline accurately reflected the
``economic fundamentals'' between the United States and Japan, and
said the fall ``isn't too fast.''
   Murayama also attributed the dollar's decline in part to the
outlook for lower U.S. interest rates.
   On Monday, several major U.S. banks, including Chemical Bank and
Continental Bank, lowered their prime rates to 10.5 percent from
11.0 percent. The prime rate, the interest rate that banks charge
their best customers, has a wide effect on other interest rates.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dealers said political uncertainty
resulting from the governing Liberal Democratic Party's struggle to
find a successor for resigning Prime Minister Sousuke Uno
contributed to a decline.
   The 225-share Nikkei Stock Average closed at 34,898.46, down
55.41 points, or 0.16 percent, from its finish Monday, when it
climbed 248.24 points to a record high.
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 700
million shares, up from 500 million shares on Monday.
</TEXT>
