<FIRST>r a PM-Hormone-FreeBeef     08-01 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hormone-Free Beef,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Hormone-Free Beef Being Shipped to Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Nedlloyd in 7th graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranchers are set to cash in on what one official
called a ``modern day cattle drive'': the resumption of beef sales
to Europe following settlement of a dispute over hormones in
American cows.
   The first shipment of domestic and hormone-free beef to Europe
since a January embargo halted all U.S. beef exports to the
continent was to have left a Houston port today on its way to
England had Hurricane Chantal not intervened.
   ``From the onset, we at the Texas Department of Agriculture felt
that more was at stake than steak, and a whole lot more was at
stake than growth hormones,'' said Texas Agriculture Commissioner
Jim Hightower at a news conference Monday. ``This shipment is
pretty much the test case.''
   In May, the Bush administration and the 12-nation European
Community reached an interim agreement that allowed resumption of
sales of about 15 percent of the $100 million in U.S. beef exports
to Europe. However, a dispute over the other 85 percent remains to
be resolved.
   European countries said the import ban of hormone-treated beef
was made due to health concerns over the growth stimulant.
   American officials have maintained that the ban represented an
illegal trade barrier masquerading as a health measure. In
retaliation, the United States slapped tariffs on European goods
valued at about $100 million.
   Under the agreement, U.S. beef producers may export beef not
treated with growth hormones to Europe.
   The refrigerated container of 40,000 pounds of Texas
hormone-free beef was boarded onto the Nedlloyd Hudson Monday.
   Hightower said the shipment could signal an economic boon for
beef producers.
   ``This is the start of a modern day cattle drive that can put
millions of extra dollars into the pockets of enterprising Texas
ranchers, feedlot operators and meet packers,'' Hightower said.
   The shipment of beef, worth about $100,000, was processed by Cox
Packing Co. in Devine, near San Antonio, and being sent to TSW
Meats Ltd. of Liverpool. The company has an option with Cox Packing
to make an additional purchase of hormone-free beef valued at about
$1.5 million.
   Hightower said Texas ranchers normally don't give hormones to
their cattle. Feedlot operators, however, give the hormones to
increase the weight of the livestock, he said.
</TEXT>
