<FIRST>r a PM-IndianStandoff     08-01 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Standoff,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indians, State Reach Tentative Accord To Ease Reservation Tension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement to remove state police
roadblocks at the St. Regis Indian Reservation should help ease
tensions in a 10-day-old standoff there, Mohawk leaders and state
officials said.
   Five Mohawk leaders met in Albany Monday with state police,
members of Gov. Mario Cuomo's staff and a representative of the
federal Bureau of Indian Affairs to help resolve tensions on the
reservation along the St. Lawrence River in northern New York.
   More than 200 state troopers have been manning roadblocks to
keep outsiders out of the reservation's casinos, which police and
FBi agents raided July 20.
   ``We will be scaling down the checkpoints and allowing the
motoring public onto the reservation,'' said state trooper Richard
Garcia. ``We're hopeful this will ease the tension.''
   ``We have reached a tentative agreement which assures everyone's
safety,'' said Mohawk Chief Harold Tarbell. ``It was an effort to
reduce the tensions on the reservation.''
   State police were to erect informational barricades for an
indefinite time, Garcia said. Troopers at those barricades will
explain the situation on the reservation to motorists, giving them
the option to enter the Indian land or turn back, he said.
   The casinos will remain closed, Tarbell said. Mohawk leaders
have scheduled a vote for mid-August on whether reservation
residents want to legalize gambling.
   The gambling issue has divided the Mohawk community. The raid
prompted protests by the reservation's warrior faction, which
claims police have no jurisdiction on Mohawk land.
   About a dozen people were injured last week when a group of
Mohawks tried to prevent state police from arresting warrior leader
Art Montour on a federal charge of obstructing justice.
   Montour was accused of using a gun to keep police from searching
a casino during the raid.
   In Syracuse, U.S. Magistrate Gustave DiBianco on Monday set bail
for Montour at $50,000. Montour was released after posting $5,000.
He was to appear again in court Aug. 16.
</TEXT>
