<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0551EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-MurderInc     08-01 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Murder Inc,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Sentenced to Death For Killing Elderly People in Will Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer was sentenced to death today for
masterminding the murders of eight elderly people as part of a
sophisticated scheme to forge their wills and acquire their wealth.
   Christos Papadopoulos, who called his white-collar crime ring
``Murder Inc.'' and whose mother-in-law was among its victims,
laughed when his sentence was announced. He had been convicted of
murder on Monday.
   Despite the decision, Papadopoulos is not likely to be executed.
Greece is a member of the European Economic Community and the trade
group prohibits capital punishment.
   Although the death sentence remains on the books, it has in
practice been abolished and condemned prisoners remain in jail for
life. The last execution took place in 1972.
   Twenty other gang members were sentenced today by a three-member
judicial panel and a four-member jury. Gang member Nikos Peppas was
sentenced to life imprisonment and 19 others were given prison
terms ranging from two to 10 years. All were convicted.
   Authorities say Murder Inc.'s members included notary publics,
lawyers, a doctor and a police officer.
   Among the victims, all elderly, were a shipowner, a blind
lottery ticket salesman and Papadopoulos' mother-in-law.
   Authorities said that between 1979 and 1986, the gang members
forged wills worth at least $18.7 million.
   The 55-day trial began on May 17 with scores of witnesses
testifying how the gang won the confidence of lonely old people
before killing them.
   In several instances, the victims were forced to sign blank
pieces of paper before being suffocated or bludgeoned to death.
   In his closing argument Monday, Prosecutor Vassilis Markis
described Papadopoulos as ``a very clever individual, with great
capabilities. If his intelligence and his organizational skills had
been directed elsewhere things would have been very different.''
   Papadopoulos, testifying during the trial, cast himself as a
latter-day Robin Hood.
   ``I wanted to hand out social justice,'' Papadopoulos said,
claiming that he took from the rich and gave to the poor.
   `If there were 100 Murder Inc.'s the (social) situation today
would be very different,'' he said.
   When asked by the court to elaborate on his role in the murders,
Papadopoulos replied: ``Let's not go into that.''
   The wills drawn up by the gang aroused no suspicion until the
1986 death of 84-year-old shipowner Haralambos Typaldos. Relatives
contested the will, which listed 135 beneficiaries, of whom only
nine were known to the family.
</TEXT>
