<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FDA Asked Not to Let Promethazine Hydrochloride Go</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Over-the-Counter
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has been
asked by an advisory committee to reverse plans to allow
nonprescription sales of a cough-cold drug because of its possible
association with sudden infant death syndrome.
   The agency had planned to allow over-the-counter sales of the
drug, promethazine hydrochloride, in multi-ingredient cold products
for short-term use.
   But the FDA asked its Pulmonary Drugs Advisory Committee to
review the issue in light of a petition from the Public Citizen
Health Research Group and the University of Maryland Sudden Infant
Death Syndrome Institute.
   The groups said the drug, which has been sold in prescription
products since 1951, may contribute to some cases of the syndrome
known as SIDS. Though it is not recommended for use in young
children, doctors do prescribe it for them, for colic, the groups
said.
   The advisory committee voted 7-1 to recommend that the drug
remain a prescription ingredient, said Susan Cruzan, an FDA
spokeswoman.
   The drug is an active ingredient in products sold under the
trade name Phenergan, made by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories of
Philadelphia. Wyeth-Ayerst and other makers of prescription
products using the drug agreed to withhold nonprescription
marketing pending review by the advisory committee.
</TEXT>
