<FIRST>r a PM-Princeton-Newport     08-01 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convictions Could Spur More Wall Street Racketeering Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The racketeering convictions of five former
officials of a small securities firm and a former Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. trader could herald more racketeering cases against
Wall Street executives, law experts say.
   Monday's verdict came in the first case in which the federal
Racketeer Influenced Corrupt Organizations Act was used against
Wall Street professionals.
   The case overlapped the government's 98-count fraud and
racketeering indictment of former Drexel financier Michael Milken.
Much of the same evidence is expected to be introduced at Milken's
trial, scheduled to begin in March 1990.
   ``Until now the government has been using RICO effectively
against organized crime types,'' said Michael Goldsmith, a Brigham
Young University law professor and vice chairman of the American
Bar Association's racketeering law committee. ``This case reflects
a new effort to use it against white-collar folks. That is
appropriate.''
   Under the racketeering law, a person or business committing two
or more felonies can be charged with engaging in a pattern of
criminal activity.
   ``I think the government will use RICO more in these types of
cases,'' said Robert N. Kaplan, president of the National
Association of Securities and Commodities Law Attorneys.
   The law allows the government to seize many assets even if they
were not gained through the criminal activity. The jury in the case
is scheduled to return today to consider forfeiture.
   After 2{ days of deliberations, jurors found the six defendants
guilty of a total of 63 counts, including conspiracy, racketeering
and racketeering conspiracy and mail and wire fraud. The
racketeering counts carry a maximum sentence of 20 years in prison
and a $250,000 fine, in addition to possible forfeiture of assets.
   Convicted were former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg, former
Princeton-Newport Partners LP partners Charles M. Zarzecki, James
Sutton Regan, Jack Z. Rabinowitz and Paul A. Berkman, and the
firm's controller, Steven B. Smotrich.
   Newberg and Zarzecki were acquitted of one count of wire fraud.
   The case involved a series of pre-arranged stock transactions
between 1984 and 1986. The government alleged they were designed to
generate phony tax losses.
   ``It's an outrage,'' said Zarzecki's lawyer, Paul Grand. ``They
didn't bother to look at the evidence, or the lack of it.''
   Regan's attorney, Theodore Wells, said all the defendants
planned to appeal.
   Deborah Corley, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office,
said she could not comment on the verdict until after forfeiture
was decided.
   Princeton-Newport, a small securities firm with offices in
Princeton, N.J., and Newport Beach, Calif., went out of business
after the indictment was brought last August. Neither
Princeton-Newport nor Drexel was charged in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
