<FIRST>r a PM-PhotographFound     08-01 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Photograph Found,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mothers of Missing Youths Fly to Florida to See Mysterious Photograph</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two mothers of missing youths flew to
Florida to look at a photograph of two bound and gagged young
people shown on a national television program that they say may be
their children.
   Michael Henley Jr., 10, disappeared on a turkey hunt with his
father in April 1988 in the mountains south of their hometown of
Grants, about 60 miles west of Albuquerque. Tara Calico, then 19,
disappeared five months later while bicycling on a country road
near Belen, 30 miles south of here.
   The FBI, meanwhile, said it will join the investigation of the
youths' disappearances.
   The mothers were to meet with law enforcement officials today in
Port St. Joe, Fla. They had seen the photograph on the ``tabloid''
news show, ``A Current Affair.''
   Pat Doel, mother of Ms. Calico, and Marty Henley flew to Florida
to see firsthand the photograph they believe shows their children
bound and gagged in a van. A woman who found the photo June 15 in a
Port St. Joe parking lot said a white van had been parked over the
spot where she found the Polaroid snapshot.
   ``I can't give up on her,'' Mrs. Doel said Monday. ``I thought
it was her when I first saw her. But then when I saw the puffiness
around her eyes I didn't think it looked like her. But then I
looked at a photo of her when she first woke up and it looked like
her.''
   ``We've always thought we'd get Tara back some way somehow. This
is the first step,'' she said.
   She and Mrs. Henley boarded a plane together Monday afternoon.
   Mrs. Henley said in an interview Monday on ``A Current Affair''
that at first she didn't want to think the boy in the photo looked
like her son, Michael, ``but it looks like him. From the photo
you've shown us, we're as certain as we can be.''
   The nationally syndicated television show had first shown the
photo Friday, triggering the response from the Henleys and the
Doels.
   FBI spokesman Doug Beldon said Monday that the agency would
provide background information on the Henley disappearance and make
available its laboratory and identification division in Washington,
D.C.
   He said if it is determined that the photograph is of Henley or
Calico, a federal kidnapping investigation would follow. He said
such federal probes are predicated on abductions that cross state
lines.
</TEXT>
