<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     08-01 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repairs Started on Exxon Valdez</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A marine chemist collected air samples from the
cargo tanks of the Exxon Valdez to make sure it's safe for shipyard
workers to prepare the tanker for a nine-month repair job.
   The samples were collected Monday to ensure no dangerous gases
are present in the ship's holds when dry-dock welding begins, said
Al Lutter, senior vice president at National Steel and Shipbuilding
Co.
   Analysis of the samples is expected to be done by Wednesday, he
said.
   The sampling marked the start of a repair process that Exxon
Shipping Co. officials hope will allow the supertanker to return to
service. Repairs are estimated to cost $25 million.
   Once the ship's cargo tanks are certified as gas-free, workers
will begin welding to the hull approximately 24 brackets that will
help prop up the vessel when it goes into dry dock.
   About 30 percent of the ship's bottom either is gone or has been
weakened so badly in the aftermath of the March 24 grounding that
it can't be supported in dry dock without the brackets, Exxon and
National Steel officials said.
   Divers then will survey the ship's hull to determine the extent
of the damage on the 987-foot-long tanker, Lutter said.
   A piece of granite reef the size of a small van also must be
removed before the Valdez can be moved into the dry dock where the
ship was built in 1986.
   The tanker likely will be moved into the dock during a four-day
period of high tides that starts Aug. 14, said Lutter.
   The Valdez, which caused the nation's worst oil spill by dumping
about 11 million gallons of crude into Alaskan waters, is moored at
a National Steel pier following its discharge-free transit Sunday
through San Diego Bay.
   Its entrance was delayed three weeks by oil slicks that appeared
near the vessel off the Southern California coast. To enable the
Valdez to enter the harbor, divers also had to remove massive steel
slabs that dangled from the hull and extended as much as 70 feet
below the surface.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
