<HEAD>Dollar Stable, Gold Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was stable at lower levels today, but
dealers anticipated further drops reflecting declining U.S.
interest rates.
   Gold was slightly weaker in quiet trading.
   Several major U.S. banks cut their prime lending rates a half a
point Monday to 10.5 percent.
   ``We are constantly getting confirmation that the U.S. economy
is no longer in a boom phase, and that interest rates are
falling,'' said a dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   ``Once the yield advantage is gone, there is no more reason to
hold dollars.''
   The dollar dropped 2.45 yen on the Tokyo exchange, closing today
at 135.95 yen. Later in London, the dollar firmed to 136.70 yen.
   In London, the pound sterling cost $1.6580, compared to $1.6665
late Monday.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8665 West German marks, up from 1.8655
   _1.6097 Swiss francs, up from 1.6065
   _6.3215 French francs, up from 6.3155
   _2.1020 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1030
   _1,341.00 Italian lire, up from 1,340.03
   _1.1796 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1809
   Gold opened in London at $368.60, up from $368.25 a troy ounce
late Monday. At mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $369.95 an ounce.
   There was no trading today in Zurich, because of a national
holiday. Gold sold at $368.25 an ounce there late Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose the equivalent of $1.62 an ounce
to close today at $371.26.
   Silver was trading in London at $5.24 a troy ounce, up sharply
from Monday's $5.13.
