<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0709EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MarielAgent     08-01 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mariel Agent,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Cuban Agent Says He Masterminded Mariel Boatlift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader in the 1980 ``freedom
flotilla'' says he was actually a spy who had given Fidel Castro
the idea for the boatlift, which brought 125,000 Cubans, some of
them criminals, to the United States.
   Napoleon Vilaboa, 52, sailed his yacht to Mariel to pick up
Cubans and later spoke frequently on radio stations in Miami's
Little Havana in 1980, urging exiles to participate in the boatlift.
   After the boatlifts ferried Cubans to Key West, he disappeared
from the headlines and from Miami.
   Nine years later, Vilaboa has returned to Miami to say those who
suspected him after his disappearance were right _ he was a Cuban
government agent _ and that he had masterminded the boatlift, he
told The Miami Herald in a story published Monday.
   Vilaboa, who is living in Miami Beach, said that he eventually
became a lieutenant colonel in Cuban intelligence and worked to
export revolution through the Cuban Institute of Friendship with
Peoples.
   One former police official said he was not surprised by
Vilaboa's admission.
   ``We were looking for him everywhere,'' said Sergio Pinon,
formerly with the Florida Department of Law Enforcement. ``We knew
all along he was a Cuban agent. He was very dedicated to the
revolution. If he's coming out now, I think it's because he was
told to.''
   Pinon also said Vilaboa was suspected of stealing money from
exiles looking for help to free their families in Cuba. Vilaboa
denied stealing any money.
   Vilaboa said he met with Castro at the Havana Riviera Hotel in
April 1980, after 10,000 Cubans had stormed the Peruvian embassy
trying to get out the country.
   ``Fidel was violent, desperate,'' Vilaboa recounted. ``He said
`What do we think we should do with these embassy people?'''
   Vilaboa said he suggested something like the 1965 Camarioca
exodus, in which 5,000 people came to Florida through that Cuban
port.
   Days later, his contact told him Castro had agreed, and decided
the refugees should leave from Mariel.
   Castro used the boatlift to rid himself of thousands of
criminals and mentally ill people, as well as thousands of people
who for one reason or another were unhappy with conditions in Cuba.
   After the boatlift, Vilaboa moved to Costa Rica, where he said
he was a $3,000-a-month ``consultant to the Cuban government,
arranging exports and running a restaurant.''
   Vilaboa said he has come forward with his story because quiet
efforts to work with anti-Castro forces to change the government
had failed.
   He said his new mission would be to denounce other pro-Castro
infiltrators in the exile community.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
