<HEAD>Gunman Surrenders to Police After 18-Hour Standoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man surrendered to police after holding
officers at bay for almost 18 hours while shooting at them from his
home.
   Police arrested Joseph Smith, 50, who was armed with two rifles
and a handgun, on Monday afternoon, said Sgt. Christopher Buck.
Smith was to be hospitalized for a psychiatric evaluation, police
said.
   Police from the neighboring city of Highland Park had gone to
Smith's house Sunday evening to arrest him for assault with intent
to murder, officials said.
   ``He apparently was ejected from a theater, went outside and
fired shots at the theater,'' Detroit police Sgt. George Anthony
said.
   Smith opened fire on the Highland Park police, and later shot
into a Detroit police car that went to the scene. He also shot at a
police helicopter that hovered over his northeast Detroit home,
officials said.
   No injuries were reported at the theater or at the Smith's home,
Anthony said.
   Police sealed off the area and evacuated several dozen area
residents during the siege.
