<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Britain,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Says All Mideast Hostages Should Be Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Secretary John Major of Britain called
again today for release of all hostages in the Mideast.
   The archbishop of Canterbury also appealed for restraint after
the reported killing of a U.S. Marine hostage in Lebanon.
Archbishop Robert Runcie's personal envoy, Terry Waite, is one of
the Westerners held captive in that country.
   There were also threats to kill Waite today, but Runcie had no
comment. The Anglican envoy disappeared in January 1987 while
trying to free other captives.
   ``We are in touch with a number of countries in the region and
with the U.S. administration,'' Major said in a statement released
by the Foreign Office. ``I urge any country with influence to use
it to secure the safe return of all hostages.''
   Concern for the hostages was heightened Monday after the
purported hanging of Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins. His
captors said he was killed in retaliation for Israel's seizure of
Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a Moslem cleric linked to terrorism.
   Waite's brother, David, appealed again today for all sides to
release their hostages.
   John Waite, a cousin of the hostage, said in a television
interview that, ``We believe the Israelis should give up the sheik.
He is a hostage and he should be released along with all other
hostages.''
