<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0905EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     08-01 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Govt Employees Hold Day of Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of government employees
launched a nationwide protest today to demand higher pay. President
Corazon Aquino said the country cannot afford to pay better wages.
   About 12,000 striking workers rallied in front of the Senate
building to press their demand, police said, joining public school
teachers who walked off the job eight days ago over salary demands.
   Officials said the extent of the walkout was unclear. About 25
percent of the 1,350 employees at Ninoy Aquino International
Airport joined the walkout but operations there were unaffected,
according to airport manager Eduardo Carrascoso.
   Strike leaders claimed 75 percent of the airport staff joined
the walkout. Union leaders at the government-run Philippine General
Hospital said all sections there were affected by the strike except
the intensive care unit.
   Organizers said the walkout affected at least 28 government
agencies, including the University of the Philippines, the weather
service, the social security system, the Central Bank, the National
Food Authority, and the Department of Labor.
   Eric Torres, chairman of the militant Alliance of Concerned
Teachers, claimed 104,000 teachers nationwide joined the protest,
affecting 800 schools, colleges and universities.
   Government workers are asking for an increase in the minimum
monthly pay from $66.70 to $133. Public school teachers are seeking
an increase from $95 a month to $214.
   The government defines poverty as a family income of $185 per
month. Philippine salaries are among the lowest in non-communist
Southeast Asian countries.
   Mrs. Aquino acknowledged today that state salaries were well
below those of the private sector but said the government would not
bow to the strikers' demands.
   Budget Secretary Guillermo Carague said the government had
budgeted $285 million for salaries. But Patricia Santo Tomas,
chairman of the Civil Service Commission, said meeting teachers'
demands alone would cost the government $1.8 billion.
   Strike leaders have called for cuts in the budget for defense
and foreign debt service to make more money available for salaries.
</TEXT>
