<FIRST>r a PM-FairStabbing     08-01 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fair Stabbing,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mob Calls for Death of Psychiatric Patient Charged With Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GORDON FAIRCLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatric patient charged in the
fatal knifing of a 9-year-old girl encountered a mob screaming for
his death as he left court, headed for a hospital for the
criminally insane.
   Mental Health Commissioner Michael Hogan later Monday insisted
proper procedures had been followed at Connecticut Valley Hospital
before David Peterson wandered away.
   But he said the attack on Jessica Short, ``the most devastating
event in the hospital's 100-year history,'' shows a need for
tighter security.
   Peterson, 37, was ordered held on $750,000 bail Monday on murder
and weapons charges in the slaying of Jessica on Friday as she
attended a street fair. He was ordered to undergo psychiatric
evaluation.
   Peterson was whisked into the courthouse under heavy guard as
two police sharpshooters perched on a rooftop.
   After the arraignment, a mob of 35 to 40 people ran alongside
the squad car taking him to a Hartford jail, shouting obscenities
and ``Kill him, kill him.''
   ``I think they should kill him,'' said Stephanie Kamp, 18, who
said she saw the stabbing. ``There going to put him right back in
CVH and in a couple of years he'll be right back out.''
   Peterson was to be transferred to Whiting Forensic Institute in
Middletown, a state hospital for the criminally insane.
   Peterson had been ordered confined at sprawling, unfenced
Connecticut Valley Hospital for up to 15 years last year after
being found innocent by reason of insanity on assault and burglary
charges.
   Hogan said Peterson left his assigned building without
permission.
   ``The hospital is not a prison,'' he said, and the privileges
given to each patient are reviewed daily. ``This system has worked
well for thousands of patients over many years and is used in many
hospitals, but there is no question that it did not work in this
case to prevent a horrible occurrence.''
   ``The killing has had a traumatic effect on our patients and
staff,'' Hogan said. ``Many patients fear that they will be seen as
guilty by association.''
   As for the need to tighten security, he said, ``The specific
changes must be carefully considered.''
   According to family members, Peterson's first run-in with the
law came after he stabbed a fellow high school student in 1971.
After that he was in and out of mental hospitals, said his
sister-in-law, Ellen Peterson.
</TEXT>
