<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1054EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Options 2ndLd-Writethru a0531 08-01 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Options, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0531,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gropes to Find Ways to Retaliate Effectively</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs of detail on problems with military effort after
3rd graf, ``No one''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, pondering ways to retaliate
for the reported hanging of Lt. Col. William Higgins by Lebanese
kidnappers, faces the frustration his predecessors experienced in
deciding how to international terrorists, experts say.
   One administration source said today that a military response
was ``in the realm of the possible,'' but that Bush had not decided
on a course of action among the options before him.
   ``No one is tilted in that direction,'' the source, who declined
to be identified, said of some sort of armed intervention. ``It's
on the menu. No one's ordered it ... We're not leaning necessarily
toward anything. People are discussing the options. We are not at
the specific choosing stage.''
   A second official, who also demanded anonymity, said the problem
with a military strike is that some of the U.S. or foreign hostages
are likely being held ``at the sites you might strike'' to
retaliate against their terrorist captors.
   And he said of a possible rescue attempt, ``most people have
thought that's kind of ruled out'' in part because the hostages are
believed held at different sites by different groups.
   ``It's very clear the options are not attractive for the United
States,'' this official, adding that the diplomatic approach seems
the most viable.
   Private analysts note there are no easy answers to America's
latest terrorist challenge.
   ``Rhetoric is cheap, but decisive action is difficult. I don't
know if there is very much we can do in the short term,'' said
Geoffrey Kemp, a former Reagan administration official who works
for the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace.
   President Reagan pledged at the time of his inaugural more than
eight years ago to take ``swift and effective retribution'' against
terrorists but often backed away from bold action, worried that the
cure might be worse than the disease.
   He was concerned that the United States might strike at the
wrong target, kill innocent civilians and jeopardize the lives of
the remaining Americans held hostage in Lebanon. With the reported
death of Higgins, eight American hostages remain.
   According to Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., Bush told congressional
leaders Monday night that it's a ``98 percent probability'' that
Higgins was slain as his Shiite Moslem captors claimed.
   ``The options for retaliation are virtually non-existent,'' said
Noel Koch, a former Pentagon official and terrorism expert.
   L. Paul Bremer, who headed the State Department's
counter-terrorism office under Reagan, said Bush's problem has been
the absence of adequate intelligence from Beirut's shadowy
underworld, where the American hostages are believed held.
   He said the administration should not rule out the abduction of
terrorist ringleaders as punishment for Higgins' reported execution.
   Very little is known about the group that claimed to have killed
Higgins, the Organization of the Oppressed on Earth.
   James Blackwell, deputy director for political military studies
at Center for Strategic and International Studies, said, ``We are
really caught between a rock and a hard place.''
   ``The military option is there but it is a limited one,'' he
said, because the U.S. must avoid hurting innocent people and
doesn't want to harm the other hostages.
   Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman David Boren, D-Okla.,
said after the meeting with congressional leaders that Bush was
considering several options but he declined to identify them.
   ``I don't think anything has been ruled out at this point,''
Boren said.
   Complicating the quest for an appropriate response were doubts
about whether Higgins was killed Monday or months ago. Israeli
officials strongly suspect that Higgins's death may date as far
back as July or December 1988.
   Higgins' kidnappers maintained the purported execution was in
retaliation for the kidnapping by Israeli commandos of Sheik Abdul
Karim Obeid, a Lebanese Shiite leader who was seized at his home 72
hours before the announced hanging of Higgins.
   Shortly before Higgins' execution was reported, Israeli
officials said their government was offering to exchange its Shiite
Moslem captives from Lebanon for Israeli prisoners of war and all
foreign hostages held by Shiite groups.
   But after the meeting with Bush, Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, indicated that the president does not consider
negotiating with terrorists to be an appropriate option.
   Mitchell said Bush ``strongly reaffirmed his belief in the
appropriate policy of not negotiating with terrorists in any
circumstances.''
</TEXT>
