<FIRST>r p PM-Pepper'sSeat 1stLd-Writethru a0466 08-01 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepper's Seat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban-Americans Lead the Field for Pepper's Seat in Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with light turnout; PICKS UP graf
pvs, `On the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters today nominated candidates for the late
Claude Pepper's seat in a race that could send a Cuban-American to
Congress for the first time.
   Polls showed Cuban-Americans leading the crowded field among
Republicans and Democrats alike in the district, where Hispanics
have come to represent about half the voters some 30 years after an
influx of Cuban emigres began.
   Turnout had been projected at just 18 percent, meaning seven
Democrats were vying for 18,000 votes, while the four Republicans
battled for 14,000 votes, but the number of voters going to the
polls in a drizzle was even lighter than expected.
   ``You can count it on your fingertips,'' said veteran Miami
Beach political strategist Gerald Schwartz. ``You can almost
literally talk to everybody who's going to vote.''
   Each party will hold a runoff Aug. 15 if no candidate wins a
majority. The Democrat and Republican winners will meet in an Aug.
29 special election.
   Pepper, a Democrat, first won the seat in 1962 and held it until
his death on May 30 at 88.
   David Leahy, elections supervisor for Dade County, said his 18
percent turnout projection was a guess because there hasn't been a
special congressional election in recent history, and never in
August, a vacation month.
   Nearly half the voters will have only the House race on their
ballot, with a smaller portion of the district having a special
state Senate election and an even smaller section also having a
state House primary _ for the GOP only.
   Hispanic turnout is traditionally high, Leahy said, and there is
the added attraction of the chance to elect the first
Cuban-American to Congress. The district includes central Miami,
including the heavily Cuban Little Havana area.
   On the Democratic side, the lone Hispanic is Cuban-born former
city commissioner Rosario Kennedy, the leader in virtually all
polls. However, winning a majority ``against six other candidates
is nearly impossible,'' said Phil Hamersmith, a Kennedy strategist.
   Pepper's niece, Jo Ann Pepper, has been running second to Ms.
Kennedy in most polls and said her campaign lacked money for a late
TV blitz. Attorney Gerald Richman, third in most polls, put as much
as $180,000 into television.
   Ironically, neither Ms. Kennedy nor Ms. Pepper could vote today.
Although lenient congressional rules allowed them to qualify for
the race, they didn't meet local residency requirements.
   Far back in the polls were black professor Marvin Dunn, black
real estate agent Sonny Wright, businessman Bernard Anscher and
striking Eastern Airlines pilot John Paul Rosser.
   On the Republican side, state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen
concentrated on get-out-the-vote efforts Monday in hopes of winning
a majority against opponents led by fellow Cuban-American Carlos
Perez, a wealthy activist for conservative causes who was endorsed
by former National Security Council aide Oliver North.
   Also on the GOP ballot are insurance broker David Fleischer and
former North Miami Mayor John Stembridge.
   The elections office said there are 100,198 registered Democrats
in the district, with 16,028 Hispanics, 32,183 blacks and 51,987
non-Latin whites.
   There are 71,620 registered Republicans, with 46,738 Hispanics,
23,656 non-Latin whites, and 1,226 blacks.
   The figures for Hispanics include only those who were born in
Hispanic nations. Unofficial estimates that count second-generation
Hispanics suggest Hispanics make up about half the district's
registered voters.
</TEXT>
