<FIRST>r w PM-SocialSecurity-King     08-01 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security-King,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Sworn In as New Social Security Commissioner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gwendolyn S. King took office today as
commissioner of the Social Security Administration with a promise
to provide better service for the millions of Americans who receive
monthly benefits.
   Mrs. King, a former congressional, state and White House aide,
was sworn in by Health and Human Services Secretary Louis W.
Sullivan, who said the nation's retirement and disability benefits
system rests in ``capable, caring hands.''
   The new commissioner, who took the oath of office at Social
Security headquarters near Baltimore, said, ``I pledge to you that
SSA will serve only one special interest _ the public interest.''
   ``My goal is a fairer, more efficient and humane Social Security
system.''
   The SSA administers both the Social Security old age, survivors
and disability benefits program and the Supplemental Security
Income program for needy people who are aged, blind or disabled.
   More than 38 million Americans collect monthly Social Security
checks totaling about $230 billion each year and 4.1 million
recieve monthly Supplemental Security Income benefits totaling more
than $14 billion a year.
   During the Reagan years, the agency pared its workforce by about
20 percent to 65,000 employees as part of a program to streamline
and modernize operations. Critics, however, complain that the
remaining employees are overworked, morale is low and the quality
of service has declined.
   Mrs. King promised agency employees she would provide
``leadership which respects and trusts its employees; leadership
that will lead, but will also listen.''
   ``You are entitled to leadership that stands up for you,
especially when you think you may be left standing alone,'' she
said.
   Mrs. King succeeds Dorcas Hardy, who announced in June that she
would resign effective Monday.
</TEXT>
