<FIRST>r a PM-PhotographFound     08-01 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Photograph Found,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mothers of Missing Youths Fly to Florida to See Mysterious Photograph</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede ALBUQUERQUE, N.M</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with parents viewing photo, reax, details,
adds byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT ST. JOE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of two missing New Mexico
youths said today that a mysterious photograph of a bound boy and
girl appeared to show their loved ones.
   The snapshot, which a woman claimed to have found June 15 in a
parking lot near where a van had been parked, was shown Friday on
the syndicated TV program ``A Current Affair.''
   The parents of Michael Henley Jr. and Tara Calico flew to this
Florida Panhandle community Monday and visited police to view the
Polaroid snapshot.
   They emerged to tell reporters they are convinced the photo
shows their missing children, although they want experts to view it
as well.
   Michael Henley Jr., 10, disappeared on a turkey hunt with his
father in April 1988 in the mountains near their hometown of
Grants, N.M. Ms. Calico, then 19, disappeared five months later
while bicycling on a country road near her hometown of Belen, N.M.
   ``We hope it's a step closer to finding him,'' said Michael
Henley, father of the missing boy. Henley was accompanied by his
wife, Marty Henley.
   Pat Doel, mother of Ms. Calico, agreed the young woman shown
bound with her hands behind her back appeared to be her daughter.
She added that the two pictured appeared to be well-fed and in good
shape.
   On Monday, FBI spokesman Doug Beldon in Albuquerque, N.M., said
the agency would provide background information on the Henley
disappearance and make available its laboratory and identification
division in Washington.
   Before leaving for Port St. Joe, Mrs. Doel said the more she
looked at TV copies of the photo, the more convinced she was that
the young woman was her daughter.
   ``I can't give up on her,'' Mrs. Doel said. ``I thought it was
her when I first saw her. But then when I saw the puffiness around
her eyes I didn't think it looked like her. But then I looked at a
photo of her when she first woke up and it looked like her.''
   ``We've always thought we'd get Tara back some way somehow. This
is the first step,'' she said.
   Mrs. Henley said in an interview Monday on ``A Current Affair''
that at first she didn't want to think the boy in the photo looked
like her son, but she added, ``From the photo you've shown us,
we're as certain as we can be.''
</TEXT>
