<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Condoms-Jail     08-01 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Condoms-Jail,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condom Distribution Begins at County Jails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health educators have begun distributing
condoms to county jail inmates, despite questions about the
legality of the program.
   Although the program initiated Monday is part of the county's
4-year-old AIDS prevention project, prosecutors remain uncertain
whether participants could face charges of encouraging sex between
prisoners, a felony in California.
   Advocates argue the plan is targeted at preventing acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, not encouraging sex.
   Inmates must request condoms one at a time from health
educators, who will authorize distribution if deemed medically
appropriate, according to San Francisco Sheriff Mike Hennessey. He
has instructed jail deputies not to charge inmates with possession
of contraband for having a condom.
   ``We're not naive; we know it goes on here as well as every
other jail despite our efforts to prevent it,'' he said. ``But at
least now it will be safe sex.''
   According to an opinion by the district attorney's office,
public health workers who hand out the condoms could be found
criminally liable, but prosecutors will investigate only if a
complaint is made.
</TEXT>
