<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Hostages     08-01 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Hostages,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official: Captors of Two Germans Demanding Release of Hamadi Brothers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Lebanon-Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for federal
prosecutors said today the captors of two West Germans kidnapped in
Lebanon have demanded the release of convicted hijacker Mohammed
Ali Hamadi and his brother, Abbas.
   Hans-Juergen Foerster, spokesman for the Federal Prosecutor's
Office in Karlsruhe, said the kidnappers have also demanded
telephone contact with the two Hamadi brothers and that they be
placed in the same prison.
   Foerster told The Associated Press that the demands were relayed
to the West German Embassy in Beirut, but he did not indicate when
or how.
   Rainer Mueller, a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry in Bonn,
refused to comment on Foerster's remarks.
   Thomas Kemptner and Heinrich Struebig were kidnapped near Sidon,
Lebanon, on May 16. Both are employees of the West German relief
organization Asme-Humanitas.
   No one has claimed responsibility for kidnapping the 28-year-old
Kemptner and Struebig, 48. Asme-Humanitas officials said today they
had not been informed of any demands.
   Foerster said ``the kidnappers, who have not previously linked
the hostage-taking with demands, now through the West German
Embassy in Beirut have set as their conditions ... the release of
... Abbas Ali Hamadi and Mohammed Ali Hamadi.''
   There have been previous reports that the kidnappings were
linked to the Hamadi case.
   A day after the two relief workers disappeared, Mohammed Hamadi
was sentenced to life in prison on murder and air piracy charges by
a court in Frankfurt for the 1985 TWA hijacking in which a U.S.
Navy diver was killed.
   His brother, Abbas Hamadi, is serving a 13-year prison term for
an April 1988 conviction on charges he helped kidnap two West
German businessmen in a 1987 attempt to force the release of his
brother.
   The two businessmen were subsequently released.
</TEXT>
