<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--O'ConnorHome     08-01 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--O'Connor Home,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Buys Childhood Home Of Author Flannery O'Connor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A foundation has purchased the childhood
home of author Flannery O'Connor and hopes to convert it into a
museum dedicated to her memory.
   Miss O'Connor is considered one of the 20th century's leading
fiction writers. Her works include two novels, ``Wise Blood'' and
``The Violent Bear It Away,'' as well as collections of short
stories and essays.
   The Flannery O'Connor Home Foundation Inc. gave the previous
owner of the three-story house, Mary Runyon, a check for $132,000
on Monday.
   Miss O'Connor, who died Aug. 3, 1964, lived in the house from
1925 until 1938. Mrs. Runyon bought it from the author's mother,
Regina Cline O'Connor.
   Foundation treasurer Hugh Brown, a professor at Armstrong State
College, said the group hopes to have the museum open by spring
1990.
  
</TEXT>
