<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence     08-01 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Violence,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christians and Syrians Battle in Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners battled
across Beirut with howitzers and rockets, and police said one
person was killed and four were wounded.
   Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun today declared a
``popular liberation revolt'' against Syrian troops in Lebanon
after an Arab League mediation committee said Syria had blocked its
efforts to end the 14-year-old civil war.
   ``The era of the popular liberation revolt will not be far ...
It will be a sweeping river of resistance in every city, village,
street and house,'' Aoun said.
   The Maronite Catholic general's 20,000 predominantly Christian
forces have been locked in fierce shelling duels with Syria's
40,000 troops in Lebanon since March 8.
   The casualties in the overnight fighting raised the overall toll
to 511 killed and 2,162 wounded in the 20-week confrontation across
the ravaged capital and surrounding mountains.
   Syrian troops have been deployed in predominantly Moslem areas
under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the 22-nation Arab League.
   Aoun contends the Syrians have betrayed their mandate by siding
with the Moslems in the civil war and should leave.
   The current round of violence broke out after Aoun blockaded
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed Moslem militias south of Beirut
for denying the ailing state treasury about $100 million annually
in lost customs dues.
   In another development, Israeli-backed militiamen today killed
three heavily armed Palestinian guerrillas as they tried to
infiltrate across the Lebanese border, a security source in
Jerusalem said.
   The militiamen of the South Lebanon Army killed the gunmen near
the village of Houle, about a mile northwest of the Israeli border
in Israel's self-declared security zone, the security source said.
He said no militiamen were injured in the shootout.
   The source said the gunmen carried identification cards from the
Syrian-backed Palestine Liberation Front (PLF). He said the gunmen
were heavily armed and were likely on a mission to attack a
settlement in northern Israel.
</TEXT>
