<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ThirdWorldThreat     08-01 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Threat,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Report Says Third World Problems Threaten US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should put greater effort
into helping cool or avoid conflicts among developing nations, says
a congressional report that rates problems in Third World countries
as a greater threat to U.S. security than the Soviet military.
   ``The danger points can become turning points toward improving
life for all on this planet _ especially the poor and hungry _ if
we act now,'' Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, said Tuesday at a news
conference where he joined two other lawmakers in releasing the
report.
   It lists five major problems in developing nations _ economic
stagnation, environmental damage, the threat to democracy from the
military's political power, weapons proliferation and drug
trafficking.
   In one major recommendation, the report by Congress' Arms
Control and Foreign Policy Caucus calls for all nations to cut
their military budgets by 50 percent, providing money for urgent
civilian needs.
   The report also suggests that the United States press for
negotiated settlements to civil wars and urges a U.S. ban on
military aid to countries with dictatorships or to those ruled by
military forces that act independently of elected governments.
   The United States cannot concentrate alone on the ``outdated
East-West, Cold War mentality,'' according to the study.
   ``Today's security threats are problems like global warming and
international debt,'' said Rep. Matthew F. McHugh, D-N.Y., another
congressman involved with the report.
   ``They aren't American or Soviet problems alone, and they can't
be solved bilaterally _ they are transnational problems that
require transnational solutions.''
   Leland noted that wars have an economic as well as personal
cost, saying that last year ``the 23 wars in the developing world
not only killed hundreds of thousands of people and created
millions of refugees, they also reduced U.S. exports by billion of
dollars.''
   The report also recommended the appointment of a Cabinet-level
U.S. development representative _ similar to the U.S. trade
representative _ to concentrate on the problems of developing
nations. And it called for a summit between developed and
developing countries.
   Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., a member of the caucus, said the
``five global epidemics may not explode as fast as nuclear weapons,
but their net effect could be just the same: Destruction of our
society as we know it.''
   The report said the five major Third World problems it focused
on ``are emerging as a potentially greater long-term threat to U.S.
security than Soviet military power.''
   McHugh, Hatfield and Leland commissioned the report, ``The
Developing World: Danger Point for U.S. Security.''
   A review of recent polls, according to the report, showed that
Americans are more concerned with developing nations and problems
such as drugs and trade than fears about East-West conflicts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
