<DOCNO> AP890801-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ConstructionSpending     08-01 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Spending,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Slump Helps Push Construction Spending Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A persistent housing slump helped push
construction spending in June to the lowest level in eight months,
the government said Tuesday, but economists are expecting at least
a modest rebound as interest rates decline.
   The Commerce Department said residential, non-residential and
government construction activity fell 0.8 percent in June to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $414.7 billion, the lowest level
since October. The decline followed a 0.6 percent gain in May and a
0.8 percent drop in April.
   Construction of new housing units dropped 1.2 percent to an
annual rate of $136.6 billion, the lowest level in three years. It
was the fifth consecutive monthly decline.
   A year-long campaign by the Federal Reserve Board to fight
inflation with higher interest rates ended this spring. Starting in
early June, the central bank reversed course and has eased
short-term rates three times, once in June and twice last month.
   Long-term rates, over which the Fed has less influence, are also
down. Thirty-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 9.81 percent last
week, the lowest in two years, according to the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp.
   Economists expect rates to continue falling gradually and, as a
result, construction activity to pick up. But, softness in economic
growth overall will prevent a strong surge, they said.
   ``I don't see a big rebound. ... At least in the housing sector,
I think we have several more slow months to come while people wait
to see whether we're going to have a recession or not,'' said
economist James Christian of the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions.
   ``If you can't sell them, you shouldn't build them,'' he said.
   Activity for the first six months of the year was only 2.9
percent above the same period in 1988, an increase that doesn't
even make up for inflation in construction costs.
   The weakness in June included a 4.8 percent drop in public
construction, which accounts for about one-fifth of construction
activity, to an annual rate of $80.6 billion. The decline included
a 3.6 percent drop in spending for highways and streets, the
biggest government category.
   Spending on single-family homes fell 1.3 percent to an annual
rate of $113.6 billion, while multifamily construction was down 0.9
percent to $23 billion.
   Non-residential construction rose 2.8 percent to a rate of
$100.3 billion. That reflected strength in industrial projects, up
4.3 percent; hotels and motels, up 6.8 percent; office building, up
1.8 percent, and other commercial projects such as shopping
centers, up 2.5 percent.
   Economist John Savacool of the WEFA Group, a forecasting firm in
Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said activity is cooling in office and retail
building, but still strong in factory construction, which is
supported by manufacturers' success in selling more goods overseas.
   ``The one thing that is restraining additional investment in the
industrial sector is that everyone is looking over their shoulder
to see if there's a recession coming,'' he said. ``The people in
charge of investment are trying to be very cautious because they
realize we're going to get a rude surprise sooner or later.''
   He predicted a small increase in construction activity in the
second half of this year, ``but not enough to get excited about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
