<DOCNO> AP890801-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia 2ndLd-Writethru a0746 08-01 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0746,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Conference Agrees to Send Team to Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with ministerial meeting today ending
with agreement to send mission, set up structure to work for peace; CHANGES
byline; TRIMS, no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international peace conference on Cambodia today
agreed to dispatch an investigation team to that civil war-torn
country and set up a force to monitor a lasting peace there.
   ``This constitutes a great first step forward on the path which
should provide a return to peace for this country,'' said Foreign
Minister Roland Dumas of France.
   With Indonesia, France is co-chair of the monthlong conference
that began earlier this week. Parties at the meeting are seeking
formation of an interim government before Vietnam, which installed
Cambodia's communist regime, is scheduled to finish pulling its
troops out of the country by Sept. 27.
   A three-party resistance coalition headed by Prince Norodom
Sihanouk is fighting the government.
   Dumas said delegations from 19 nations and the United Nations
were stalled ``until the final moments'' of the ministerial
session, which ended at noon today. The foreign ministers are to
return to Paris to close the conference Aug. 28-30.
   The French foreign minister said the mission, under the aegis of
U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar, was to be
dispatched ``very quickly'' to Cambodia and other involved
countries, but he did not set a date.
   It is to gather technical information needed to set up an
international control mechanism to monitor a Vietnamese troop
pullout, an end to foreign interference, and a cease-fire among
warring parties.
   The three-party guerrilla alliance, which includes the communist
Khmer Rouge, have been fighting the government since shortly after
Vietnam invaded in 1978. The Khmer Rouge, who ruled Vietnam until
they were driven out by the Vietnamese, are the most powerful of
the guerrilla forces.
   The Cambodian government and the United States want to prevent
the Khmer Rouge from taking power in Cambodia after a Vietnamese
withdrawal. The Khmer Rouge are blamed for killing more than 1
million Cambodians in a nationwide purge during their 1975-1978
rule.
   Delegates to the Paris conference also agreed to set up four
working commissions on the monitoring unit, international
guarantees, refugees and reconstruction, and Cambodia's political
problems.
   ``I think I can say without exaggeration that this beginning
augurs well for the conference,'' said Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas, speaking at a joint news conference with Dumas.
   Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan had raised objections to the
investigation mission and other aspects of today's agreements.
   However, China, the guerrilla group's main backer, intervened
privately Monday night with the leaders of the resistance
coalition, said a conference source, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Also at the conference, Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co
Thach said only 26,000 Vietnamese troops remain in Cambodia. He
challenged anyone to prove charges by Sihanouk and the Khmer Rouge
that Hanoi was leaving behind tens of thousands of Vietnamese
soldiers disguised as Cambodians.
   Other estimates say there are 60,000 Vietnamese troops in
Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
