<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-01 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek Urges Change of Course, or Communism Will Fail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, the leader of
the failed 1968 ``Prague Spring'' reforms, has told
Czechoslovakia's leaders they should change course or risk losing
power, according to a letter made public Tuesday.
   ``Society is trembling in the clutches of hopelessness,'' Dubcek
wrote to the Communist Party's Politburo and policy-setting Central
Committee.
   ``Do not leave the removal of deformations of the past to either
justified pressure or chance,'' he added, urging Prague's
entrenched Communist leaders to talk to opposition groups and to
reinstate 500,000 party members expelled after the 1968 Warsaw Pact
invasion that crushed his reforms.
   The June 23 letter, released through Czechoslovak activists to
Western radio stations and the London-based emigre publishers
Palach Press, was the first from Dubcek to Czechoslovakia's leaders
to be made public abroad.
   In the nine-page letter, Dubcek defended his ``Action Program,''
a blueprint for reform adopted when he was Communist Party leader
in April 1968.
   Noting the similarity between his program and recent Soviet
reforms, Dubcek also warned Prague's leaders against attacking
change in Poland and Hungary.
   ``They did not show concern when the universities in Poland were
being closed, lecturers expelled and workers shot,'' Dubcek wrote,
alluding to the imposition of martial law in Poland in 1981.
   In a telephone conversation with The Associated Press from his
home in Bratislava, Dubcek confirmed writing the letter but
declined all comment on its contents.
   Activists in Prague said the letter apparently was made public
because Dubcek did not get a reply from the communist leaders.
   Dubcek, 67, was replaced as party leader in April 1969 by
current President Gustav Husak and expelled from the Communist
Party in June 1970.
   He has spoken out increasingly on Czechoslovak affairs since a
permanent police guard was lifted when Mikhail S. Gorbachev visited
Czechoslovakia in 1987. But the Soviet Union and fellow communist
reformers Hungary and Poland have yet to state officially that the
invasion crushing Dubcek's policies was a mistake.
   Human rights activists and reform communists are campaigning
increasingly actively for a revision of the 1968 invasion, which
they believe would encourage reformers in the party to adopt
genuine changes.
   The Aug. 21 anniversary of the invasion is expected to be a
focus of renewed anti-government protests in Czechoslovakia.
   Politburo member and Prague party boss Miroslav Stepan warned in
a speech Tuesday to police, security forces and communists that
authorities would not tolerate disruptions in August.
   He declined to specify what measures would be taken. Prague is
rife with rumors of a tough police crackdown to quell any street
demonstrations following protests in August and October 1988, and
in January and May of this year.
   Echoing articles in the state-run media, Stepan condemned a
current petition being circulated that demands democratic reforms.
More than 11,500 people have signed the petition, according to
human rights activists in Prague.
   Stepan branded it ``an anti-perestroika and therefore
counterrevolutionary program, aimed against socialist society,
against the party and against hard-won benefits.''
   ``These are appeals encouraging disorders and destabilization,''
he added. ``All we can do is respond strongly, using political and
administrative means and, if necessary, power.''
</TEXT>
