<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages-UN     08-01 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-UN,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Sends Peacekeeper to Recover Higgins' Body</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N.'s top peacekeeping official has
left for Beirut to try to recover the body of U.S. Marine Lt. Col.
William Higgins, the U.N. military observer killed by his captors.
   Marrack Goulding, the undersecretary-general in charge of
peacekeeping, will ``ascertain to the extent possible the facts
surrounding the fate of Lt. Col. Higgins,'' said U.N. spokeswoman
Nadia Younes.
   Pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists said they killed Higgins on
Monday because Israel did not release a Shiite cleric it abducted
last week in southern Lebanon.
   A group known as the Organization of the Oppressed on Earth
released a videotape that showed what it said was Higgins' body
dangling from a gallows.
   ``I was very sad when I saw the tape; it looks so much like him
that now I have little doubt that unfortunately he has been
killed,'' said U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``I think that the American government, as well, thinks that he
has been killed,'' he said.
   On Monday, Perez de Cuellar said President Bush asked him to
help with the return of Higgins' body. No body has been found yet.
   Goulding, who is expected to arrive in Lebanon on Wednesday,
will begin his investigation at the headquarters of the U.N.
Interim Force in Lebanon.
   Higgins was heading the 75-member U.N. Truce Supervision
Organization in Lebanon when he was abducted near Tyre on Feb. 17,
1988. His abductors claimed he was a spy for the CIA.
</TEXT>
