<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Cruise     08-01 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Cruise,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Air Force Removes Cruise Missiles from Greenham Common</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Air Force on Tuesday
began removing U.S. cruise missiles from Greenham Common, the first
NATO base to receive the intermediate-range nuclear missiles in
1983.
   A U.S. Air Force transport plane flew out the first of the 96
missiles at Greenham Common, 50 miles west of London, which are to
be destroyed at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in Arizona, the Air
Force said.
   Britain's domestic news agency Press Association said 16
missiles were flown out. The Air Force declined to give specifics.
   All the missiles are due to be removed by 1991 under the terms
of a superpower arms control treaty signed in 1987 to eliminate the
2,700 Soviet and U.S. land-based intermediate-range nuclear
missiles from Europe.
   The Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament said the 16 missiles'
nuclear warheads were flown to the United States on July 19 and
could be recycled for use.
   The site became a focal point of demonstrations after the
deployment, and a permanent ``peace camp'' was set up by the
Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament supporters at one of its seven
entrances.
   Hundreds of thousands of anti-nuclear demonstrators protested
the deployment of the missiles in five European countries, starting
with an airlift to Greenham Common on Nov. 14, 1983.
   The other U.S. cruise missile base in Britain at Molesworth, 70
miles north of London, was deactivated in January after its 16
missiles were removed.
</TEXT>
