<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--OldSnake     08-01 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Old Snake,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Methusaleh Found Dead in His Cage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILLSBORO, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prairie rattlesnake appropriately named
Methusaleh has died.
   Methusaleh, named by students at Tabor College where it had
lived in a cage since it was captured in 1960, was found dead
Saturday. It was 31 or 32, believed to be a record for prarie
rattlesnakes in captivity, said Max Terman, a biology professor at
the college.
   The previous record-setter was a 19-year-old prairie rattler at
the San Diego Zoo, Terman said Tuesday.
   ``There really is no official record. The only thing you have
access to is records from zoos, laboratories and things like
that,'' Terman said. ``We refer to these records as noteworthy
longevity records.''
   Prairie rattlesnakes live in the wild 10 to 15 years, he said.
   Methusaleh is being preserved in a freezer until a taxidermist
can ``put him into a lifelike pose,'' Terman said. The snake will
then be kept on display at the college.
   Methusaleh was a biblical character who lived 969 years.
</TEXT>
