<SECOND>AM-BRF--Piranha Caught,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lake Closed After Piranha Caught</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT HOREB, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular fishing and swimming spot was
closed after a man caught a piranha there, authorities said Tuesday.
   ``The first time I tossed a minnow, he hit it so hard there was
nothing left but gills and head,'' said Tom Grob, who snagged the
fish Sunday. ``I threw another minnow in the same spot and he hit
it and put up a terrific fight.''
   Stewart Lake is stocked with trout by the state Department of
Natural Resources.
   It was temporarily closed to swimmers in case other piranha are
present, said Ken LePine, assistant director of the Dane County
Parks Department. LePine said the DNR is trying to determine the
source of the piranha, a carnivorous South American fish that
normally eats other fish.
   Grob said he gave the fish to a tropical pet store.
