<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0482 08-01 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadcaster Assassinated, Schools Remain Closed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with govt blaming Sinhalese extremists,
details. Pick up 8th pvs, `The government...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six gunmen dragged a government radio
newscaster out of his house and killed him, military officials said
today, and the government postponed the re-opening of 10,000
schools because of continuing violence.
   A government communique blamed the slaying Monday night on
``subversives,'' the term it uses for Sinhalese radicals.
   The slaying came eight days after the assassination of the
chairman of the Sri Lanka Broadcasting Corp., who also was the
chief government censor. The government also blamed that killing on
Sinhalese extremists and placed radio and television stations under
military control to halt further violence.
   The Sinhalese extremists, angered by peace overtures made to the
Tamil minority and by the continuing presence of Indian
peacekeeping troops, have been revolting for two years against the
Sinhalese-dominated government and its supporters.
   Premakeerthi De Alwis, the latest victim, was a Sinhalese
newscaster on state radio and host of a children's television
program. De Alwis, 42, was shot to death in front of his home in
Homagama, 13 miles southeast of Colombo, the military officials
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Their report described the assailants as ``six unknown armed
persons.'' They did not speculate on a motive.
   Officials said Sinhalese extremists killed eight other civilians
and a soldier in a series of attacks in central and southern Sri
Lanka today and Monday night. In addition, security forces found
the bodies of five people and blamed Sinhalese extremists for the
deaths.
   More than 150 people described as ``suspected subversives'' were
detained by security forces for questioning, the government
communique said.
   The government also announced that today's scheduled re-opening
of schools had been postponed indefinitely ``because of the
security situation.''
   The 10,000 government-run schools, which have an enrollment of 4
million, were closed July 6 during worsening violence and a
transportation strike.
   The government has accused the People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese ultranationalist group, of about 4,000 killings since
July 29, 1987, when then-President Junius R. Jayewardene and Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India signed a peace accord designed to
give Tamils in northeastern Sri Lanka some autonomy.
   Indian peacekeeping troops arrived to supervise the accord's
implementation and a surrender of arms by Tamil rebels. But the
largest Tamil guerrilla group reneged and turned its guns on the
Indians.
   Jayewardene's successor, Ranasinghe Premadasa, took office in
January after pledging to bring about the withdrawal of Indian
troops.
   Indian and Sri Lankan delegations have been meeting in New Delhi
since Saturday to work out a timetable for the withdrawal of the
estimated 45,000 Indian soldiers.
   About 600 Indian soldiers left Saturday night, but so far no
further withdrawals have been announced.
   In New Delhi, a Foreign Ministry official said talks between the
two countries' delegations were continuing. The official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, gave no further details.
   The Sri lankan delegation was to return to Colombo later today.
   About 11,000 people have died in the Tamil insurrection since it
began in 1983.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
say they are discriminated against in jobs and education by the
Sinhalese.
   Sinhalese, who account for 75 percent of the population, control
the government and the military.
</TEXT>
