<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Rains 1stLd-Writethru a0480 08-01 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Rains, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landslides Kill Five, Including Three Rescuers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with death toll at five sted three;
17 injured; details of damage; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A night of torrential rain in the Tokyo area
touched off floods and landslides that killed five people,
including three rescuers, and left six others missing, police said
today.
   Seventeen people were also injured, said an official of the
National Police Agency, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said
the rains flooded 6,202 houses, caused 99 landslides, and blocked
24 roads.
   In Kawasaki, just southwest of Tokyo, 14 firefighters were
buried by a landslide while trying to rescue a family of three
trapped in their two-story house by an earlier landslide.
   The police official said three firefighters were found dead, and
the other 11 were injured.
   Other rescuers were later forced to suspend their search for the
family because of the danger of another landslide, the official
said.
   In Chiba, 20 miles southeast of Tokyo, a landslide swept a
station wagon with a family of five into a reservoir, the official
said. He said three children were rescued, but the parents were
killed.
   Local meteorologists today said nearly 10 inches of rain fell on
Tokyo and neighboring areas in the previous 24 hours.
