<FIRST>u w AM-NuclearDump     08-01 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Dump,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Experts Tell Energy Agency It Should Delay Sinking Experimental
Shafts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technical experts of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission told the Energy Department on Tuesday it should delay
sinking two experimental shafts at a proposed high-level nuclear
waste dump in Nevada until further study of problems including
possible earthquakes and volcanic eruptions.
   In comments on the department's site characterization plan for
the proposed Yucca Mountain repository, the NRC staff said the
department had erred by treating the shafts as though they were
merely test drilling and would not be part of the dump if it is
established.
   Robert Bernero, chief of waste disposal for the NRC, said the
shafts would be ``the first major holes to be dug into the Yucca
Mountain formation.''
   If the dump is established, he said, they would probably be used
either for ventilation or as an alternative form of access. The
main access route, through which radioactive waste would be brought
into the dump, would be a ramp.
   Congress has ordered the department to study whether the Yucca
Mountain location, about 100 miles northwest of Las Vegas, Nev.,
could safely store tons of radioactive nuclear waste for 10,000
years.
   Bernero said consideration of a possible license for the dump is
not expected until about 1995.
   The location is opposed on health and public safety grounds by
the state of Nevada, whose legislature has passed a law prohibiting
a high-level nuclear waste dump within its boundaries.
   In a briefing at the NRC's Rockville, Md., headquarters and in a
letter to Sam Rousso, acting director of civilian radioactive waste
management for the Energy Department, Bernero said study of seismic
and volcanic risks needed to be given high priority.
   ``If you stand on Yucca Mountain and look to the west across
Crater Flats, you can see a number of volcano cones 10 or 12 miles
away,'' he told reporters. ``They raise questions, obviously ...
that another volcano might go off, and it does go off, that it
might go off in or through the repository.''
   Bernero also said there is ``a body of data that suggests the
presence of a fault that would go right through where the shafts
are.''
   ``In our analysis, it is doubtful,'' he said. ``It's not
certainly there, or it's not certainly not there. It should be part
of the design process to determine whether there is faulting and,
if so, its significance.''
   Bernero said the latest plan submitted by the department, on
Dec. 28, contained ``substantial improvements'' over the original
one of Jan. 8, 1988.
   ``However, we do have a range of technical concerns.''
   ``We have asked DOE to give much greater care to the design
control process and the analysis for these experimental shafts,''
he said.
   He said NRC and department officials met July 6 and 7 and agreed
to work together this summer and fall ``so the issues can be
resolved before the shafts are sunk.''
   He said agreements were also reached to improve quality
assurance plans for auditing the performance of contractors.
   In his letter to Rousso, Bernero said, ``NRC has a broad
programmatic concern that the pressure to meet unrealistic schedule
milestones may leave DOE insufficient time to plan and to execute
proper technical information-gathering activities.''
   ``High priority should be given to conducting those
investigations which can lead to a determination of whether the
site is subject to an unacceptably high probability of disruption
as a result of volcanism, faulting, or seismicity,'' Bernero said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
