<NOTE>LaserPhoto CX6</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: A longer version moved on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PLATTEVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Maurice Douglass isn't playing
football in the Chicago Bears' defensive backfield, he is,
according to the team's press guide, an ecdysiast.
   Most people would say he's a stripper.
   Whatever his off-season activity is called, the 25-year-old
athlete says performing in a G-string is not really that different
from playing in football pads and helmet.
   ``They're both forms of entertainment, but football is a group
thing,'' he said in an interview at the Bears' summer training
camp. ``When you dance, it's just you by yourself _ you have to do
the best you can against this audience to make these people want to
give you their money.''
   He said he started dancing in college for the extra cash and
keeps doing it because it's fun.
   ``You get a chance to be around a lot of girls,'' he said.
   His girlfriend likes his dancing, within limits.
   ``She hates for me to kiss the ladies when I'm out there dancing
_ but that's just part of getting the money _ you've got to tease
'em a little bit,'' Douglass said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actors Lane Davies, who plays Mason Capwell
on NBC's daytime ``Santa Barbara,'' and Todd McKee, who plays his
little brother Ted, say they have left the show and plan a trip
around the world.
   ``It's not that I'm looking for another kind of challenge as far
as acting is concerned,'' Davies, 38, said while visiting his
family in Georgia last week. ``I'm just ready for a rest more than
a challenge. I've kind of `challenged' myself into an early grave.''
   The actors' characters have been absent from the program
recently, supposedly having left on a trip to Rome to save the
family business. After a brief stopover in Dalton, they left on the
first stage of their trip Saturday.
   ``I've been on the show for five years and I'm just restless,''
said McKee, 25. ``I've saved up some money and I thought this trip
would be a great idea. I sold a couple of homes that I had bought,
because it's nice to have some money in the bank.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Ford Vance, daughter of former President
Ford, has been married a second time after an unexpectedly short
engagement.
   She became engaged last month to lawyer Vaden Bales of Tulsa,
Okla., and they planned to wed before the end of the year.
   But they were wed July 25 while vacationing in Duck, N.C., The
Washington Post reported in Tuesday's editions.
   ``We decided there was no point in waiting,'' she said.
   In 1979, she married Chuck Vance, a former Secret Service agent
who was assigned to protect her father after he left the White
House. The couple, who have two daughters, were divorced in
December.
