<FIRST>u a PM-Hostages-Cicippio 4thLd-Writethru a0608 08-01 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Cicippio, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0608,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostage's Family Gets Word of Reprieve Two Hours After Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with family getting word of reprieve;
PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Earlier today ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORRISTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of hostage Joseph James
Cicippio today waited two hours after the deadline for his
execution had passed before learning his pro-Iranian captors had
given him a 48-hour reprieve.
   ``It's good news for all of us,'' said Thomas Cicippio as he
stood on the front lawn of his house, flanked by two of his
brother's sons, Joseph Jr. and David. He then went inside to talk
to other family members.
   The Revolutionary Justice Organization said Monday it would kill
Cicippio if Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a Moslem cleric seized by
Israeli commandos, was not released by 11 a.m. EDT. The group
announced the reprieve at 1:15 p.m. EDT.
   In between, family members anxiously awaited word of Cicippio's
fate.
   ``Now it becomes a waiting game,'' Thomas Cicippio said seven
minutes after the 11 a.m. deadline.
   Earlier today, Thomas Cicippio asked that Israel free Obeid and
that the United States and its allies refrain from military action,
while his sister-in-law, in Beirut, publicly asked the captors of
her 58-year-old husband to spare his life.
   Thomas Cicippio, standing on the front lawn of his house where
signs count the number of days his brother and other Americans have
been held hostage in Lebanon, asked of Israel: ``Please release
Sheik Obeid as quickly as possible. We must try to do everything we
possibly can to start peace movement once again.''
   ``Please don't execute him, please,'' Joseph Cicippio's wife,
Ilham, who works at the American Embassy in east Beirut, tearfully
pleaded today in Beirut.
   She read a message to her husband: ``Joe, I know the difficulty
of the situation in which we are, but all I ask you is to keep your
hopes high.''
   Obeid is a spiritual leader of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God, believed to be an umbrella group for kidnappers
holding Higgins and the 16 other Westerners missing in Lebanon.
Eight of the 16 are Americans.
   Cicippio was acting comptroller at the American University of
Beirut when he was kidnapped from the campus Sept. 12, 1986.
   ``The organization announces its quick resolve to execute the
death sentence against the American-Israeli spy Joseph Cicippio if
the struggling sheik is not released,'' his captors said in a
statement, adding the execution would be ``broadcast on all screens
in the world.''
   The statement, handwritten in Arabic, was delivered to the
independent Beirut newspaper An-Nahar with a photograph of Cicippio.
   Thomas Cicippio said that before the latest developments, he was
becoming more hopeful.
   ``We've been watching the elections in Iran and I put a lot of
hope in (Iran's Parliamentary Speaker Hashemi) Rafsanjani helping
the U.S. gain release of the hostages.''
   Rafsanjani, considered a pragmatist among Iran's religious
hierarchy, was elected president of Iran by a landslide majority
Saturday.
</TEXT>
