<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1443EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Victims'Statements Bjt   08-01 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Victims' Statements, Bjt,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Backers Say Letting Crime Victims Speak at Sentencing Proved Worthy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year-old state law allowing crime
victims to speak at sentencing hearings is bringing humanity into
the legal system, backers say.
   The law, patterned after similar measures in Michigan and
California, gives victims ``a maximum opportunity to participate,''
said Fran Sepler, executive director of the state Crime Victim and
Witness Advisory Council. The council pushed for what's known as
the right-to-allocution law.
   ``Allocution is sort of the Cadillac of victims' rights,'' said
Sepler, adding that other states are considering such laws.
   ``Everything I hear from people in the the criminal justice
process is that the law is working well and it's being handled in a
way that's not disruptive of the criminal justice system,'' said
state Sen. Richard Cohen, an author of the measure.
   ``It's allowed victims who are often given short shrift in the
process to have more of an opportunity to be a part of what's
taking place,'' said Cohen. ``They will have the satisfication of
the sentencing judge knowing exactly how they feel and what has
happened to them.''
   Since a guilty plea may leave a victim no opportunity to testify
at trial, ``this is the only absolute guarantee that the victim of
a crime has access to a judge in a case,'' he said.
   Sepler said she made a telephone check of 10 counties about six
months after the law took effect. Use of the right ranged from an
estimate of 40 percent to 60 percent in St. Louis County in
northeastern Minnesota to only seven or eight times in Hennepin
County, which has nearly 1 million residents and almost one-fourth
of the state's population.
   In California, where voters approved allocution in 1982, two
surveys released last year of judges and district attorneys
indicated that fewer than 5 percent of felony crime victims made
statements at sentencing hearings. The reasons cited were that
victims felt they could have little impact, they had already had
satisfactory involvement or they were afraid.
   In Michigan, ``very few take advantage of actually speaking,''
said Circuit Court Judge Michael Harrison.
   However, in at least half the crimes where there is an
identifiable victim, Harrison said they submit a statement that
state sentencing guidelines require judges to consider. Michigan's
crime victims' rights law has been in effect since July 1985.
   Sepler said Mothers Against Drunk Driving is advising members to
speak at sentencings.
   ``The feedback I get from judges is that they find these
statements very difficult to listen to, extremely painful; that it
injects an element of ... humanity into the courtroom that is
otherwise not there,'' she said.
   ``While there may not be substantial changes in sentencing ...
the victim impact statements are important considerations for them
as they determine things like mitigating and aggravating factors,''
said Sepler.
   The most publicized use of the new law came in May when more
than 300 people attended a hearing in suburban Inver Grove Heights
in the case of four teen-agers who vandalized a high school.
Resulting water damage and asbestos removal costs amounted to
millions of dollars.
   About 30 people testified during the orderly hearing in a
college auditorium. District Judge William Thuet, one of two judges
who gave students, faculty, staff and taxpayers standing as
victims, said the four teen-agers probably got more lenient
sentences _ none more than a year in jail _ because members of the
public ``were all asking that we be compassionate with these guys.''
   One measure of the success of the new law, said Sepler, is that
the dire consequences predicted by opponents haven't happened.
   Opponents felt that ``only those individuals who are articulate,
educated and well-off would use it and that it would be a step
backwards in jurisprudence,'' she said.
   ``And we would have irresponsible sentencing practices and
judges unable to dismiss irrelevant testimony and appeals based on
these statements,'' she added. ``That has not in any way, shape or
form come to be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
