<FIRST>u i PM-AfghanTalks     08-01 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan Talks,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Asks Soviet Help on Hostages; Afghan Talks End With No Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States asked the Soviet
Union today to use its influence with Iran for release of American
and other Western hostages in Lebanon.
   The request was part of a U.S.-Soviet meeting on Afghanistan in
which John Kelly, assistant U.S. secretary of state, met with
Nikolai Kozyrev a Soviet ambassador. No agreement on the issue was
reached.
   ``We asked the Soviet Union to use its good offices to influence
the Iranian government to bring about their safe and immediate
release,'' Kelly told reporters after the two-day meeting.
   Kidnappers on Monday said they killed a U.S. Marine, Lt. Col.
William R. Higgins. Eight other Americans, four Britons, one
Irishman, one Italian and two West Germans are believed to be held
captive in Lebanon by pro-Iranian kidnapers.
   It was the first superpower meeting on Afghanistan since the
Soviet Union finished withdrawing troops from the country in
mid-February.
   Kelly said there were still ``significant differences'' between
the parties on the Afghan issue and regretted that there had been
``no agreement at all.'' Kelly said there were still ``significant
differences'' between the parties on the Afghan issue and regretted
that there had been ``no agreement at all.'' The Soviets have
complained of U.S. aid to rebels trying to overthrow the
Moscow-backed Afghan government.
   Kozyrev said there would be further talks.
</TEXT>
