<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     08-01 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army to Reopen Schools for 70,000 More Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM RON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junior high schools in the occupied West Bank
will be reopened Wednesday, allowing about 70,000 more Palestinian
children to return to classes, the Israeli army announced Tuesday.
   The junior high schools would be reopened for the first time
since January, said West Bank commander Maj. Gen. Amiram Mitzna.
   Primary schools and classes for high school seniors reopened
July 22, and 200,000 students returned to classes.
   The West Bank's nearly 1,200 primary and secondary schools were
closed throughout most of the 19-month Palestinian uprising against
Israeli rule in the occupied territories.
   The Israeli government said the schools were hotbeds of violence
and rejected repeated appeals from the United States and
international human rights organizations against the closures.
   Palestinian leaders have called on students not to jeopardize
the resumption of classes by initiating anti-Israeli disturbances.
   Mitzna, speaking to Israeli legislators touring the West Bank
town of Ramallah, said the army was considering reopening classes
for high school sophomores and juniors in the near future, Israel
radio said.
   Mitzna added that Israel recently released 97 high school
students who were arrested for anti-Israeli protests to allow them
to resume their education.
   Elsewhere in the occupied lands, two Palestinians were shot and
wounded overnight in clashes between Israeli soldiers and about 200
protesters in the Tulkarem refugee camp. The army also fired tear
gas to disperse the crowd, which gathered to protest the death of a
Palestinian camp resident earlier in the week, Arab reports said.
   The army said three Palestinians were wounded in the Tulkaram
clashes.
   In other developments, Israel radio reported that leaflets
signed by Palestinian Liberation Organization chairman Yasser
Arafat's Fatah wing warned activists from the hard-line Marxist
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine that ``they bear
responsibility'' for their threats against Palestinian lawyer Jamil
Tarifi.
   Tarifi, a PLO supporter, disclosed last week he had met with
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir for discussions on
implementing Shamir's peace plan. Tarifi is the only Palestinian to
admit to such a meeting.
   Graffiti signed by the front later appeared on walls threatening
Tarifi with punishment for the meeting.
   Faisal Husseini, a prominent east Jerusalem Palestinian leader
and a PLO supporter, harshly criticized the threats and told the
Israeli news agency Itim that ``these warnings do not serve the
Palestinian cause.''
   The front, headed by George Habash, has opposed Arafat's offer
to compromise in negotiations with Israel.
</TEXT>
