<SECOND>AM-Fires-Glance,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Wildfires at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at wildfires burning Tuesday in the West:
   Idaho: Hundreds of lightning-caused fires have burned 76,000
acres, much of that on national forest land in the western and
central parts of the state. Flames were near three small mountain
towns Tuesday, and 5,000 firefighters were on the fire lines.
   Montana: A fire burning in grassland and scattered timber in the
Custer National Forest became the state's biggest fire of the
summer Tuesday when it surpassed 1,200 acres. About 140
firefighters were dispatched to fight the blaze in the southeast
corner of the state, and several smaller blazes burned elsewhere.
   Oregon: Fires east of the Cascade Mountains have burned 80,000
acres, and were being fought Tuesday by 5,000 people. The worst of
the blazes were around Baker, where ranchers were forced from their
remote homes over the weekend, but allowed to return Monday and
Tuesday.
   Washington: About 110 firefighters cut a containment line most
of the way around an 850-acre forest fire in the Pasayten
Wilderness near the Canadian border Tuesday. About 1,200 Army
troops at Fort Lewis began a crash course in firefighting and fire
safty techniques so they could join the battle against wildfires in
Oregon.
