<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     08-01 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Churches Endorse Defiance Campaign, Fear a Police Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders Tuesday
endorsed a campaign of mass defiance scheduled to start this week,
but they said they feared the government would respond with a harsh
crackdown.
   The South African Council of Churches, which includes almost all
leading Protestant denominations, said it backed a plan for ailing
blacks to seek treatment at ``whites only'' hospitals beginning
Wednesday.
   The civil disobedience campaign is expected to include other
tactics and to intensify in the days leading up to the segregated
parliamentary elections Sept. 6. South Africa's tricameral
Parliament has houses for whites, Asians and people of mixed-race,
but excludes the 28 million black majority.
   ``Elections in South Africa have become synonymous with the
perpetuation of apartheid and discrimination,'' said Frank Chikane,
general secretary of the council of churches.
   ``The only means that remain open to the voteless majority is to
embark on a program of peaceful, non-violent defiance that will
change these laws,'' Chikane said.
   His statement was endorsed by nine prominent church officials,
including Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, winner of the 1984
Nobel Peace Prize.
   ``We call on all participants ... to act with discipline and
restraint that such a campaign deserves in order to retain the
moral high ground,'' Chikane said.
   ``We are seriously concerned at the repressive action which (Law
and Order Minister Adriaan) Vlok has threatened to use,'' he said.
   Vlok has said the campaign is part of an attempt to disrupt the
elections with violence. Such actions, he said, must be stopped
``at all costs.''
   There have been several bombings in the past week, and police
said the three people who were killed had been planting the
explosives. On Monday night, gunmen opened fire and tossed a hand
grenade at a Johannesburg police station, but no one was injured.
   No one has claimed responsibility for the violence. Police blame
most such attacks on the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla group.
   The Mass Democratic Movement, a loose coalition of
anti-apartheid groups that organized the defiance campaign, said
anti-black leaflets that had been circulating in recent days
``could be the work of the government so as to instill a climate of
violence around a non-violent action.''
   One organizer, Cas Coovadia, said no more than 50 blacks were
expected to present themselves Wednesday at any one of the eight
white hospitals targeted by the movement. Government officials have
said blacks who arrive at ``whites only'' hospitals and are not in
need of emergency treatment will be referred to ``black'' hospitals.
   People entering hospitals without permission could face jail
terms of up to two years, according to a government directive
issued last week.
   The Mass Democratic Movement has no official structure or
acknowledged leader, but is made up of some of the same people who
headed the United Democratic Front until it was banned last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
