<FIRST>r a AM-Chantal-HighIsland     08-01 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chantal-High Island,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Take Shelter for Hurricane Chantal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chantal Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGH ISLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people fled and spent the night
in cars or in a shelter, and some stayed home and awoke to find
water in their homes when Hurricane Chantal swept ashore Tuesday
morning.
   ``I stepped out of my bed into standing water,'' said Helen
Church, who was taken from her beachfront home to a shelter set up
at the High Island High School. ``It was the first time that had
ever happened to me. I called in and asked if anybody was being
evacuated and they offered to come and get me.''
   Chantal, packing wind up to 80 mph, came ashore over High Island
about 8 a.m. Tuesday before weakening and being downgraded to a
tropical storm late in the morning.
   Doug Considine, with the Galveston County Sheriff's Department
Beach Patrol, said roads in the area were passable although debris
was scattered across several sections where water topped the
highway.
   John Richardson and Peggy Howard spent the night in his car
after fleeing from their Gilcrest home.
   ``I don't know if there's anything left there to get back to but
I'm sure ready to find out,'' Richardson said.
   Bucky Faggard, 48, knew from the hurricane's strength that it
would not be too threatening.
   ``You go through so many of them that you learn not to start
worrying too much with the winds like this. When they get up to
175, 200 (mph), that's when I start worrying about it,'' Faggard
said.
   Faggard said he stayed when Hurricane Carla blew through in 1961
and caused a great deal of damage.
   ``With Carla in '61, we were completed surrounded by water and
were isolated for about five days, but I don't expect anything like
that from this. We've been through a bunch of these and you don't
ever really know what's going to happen so we always prepare,'' he
said.
   George E. Kahla relaxed in an old easy chair inside his
self-proclaimed trading post, emblazoned with a sign ``We buy and
sell good junk.''
   ``I'm going to sit here and play it cool and not get too excited
about all this,'' he said.
   ``That's the beauty of this business. If it blows over, you just
pick it back up later. You can't tell much difference.''
</TEXT>
