<FIRST>r i AM-SeaRescue     08-01 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Rescue,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Said to Drink Own Urine While Stranded on Life Raft</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Contents of 5th graf, ``Dr. Goran ...'' may be offensive to
some readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who survived for two weeks in
the North Atlantic was so busy eating a fish that had jumped into
her life raft that she almost failed to see the vessel that rescued
her, a doctor said Tuesday.
   Janet Culver, a legal secretary from Passaic, N.J., was rescued
Sunday by a U.S. research vessel. Her ordeal began July 16 when she
was stranded on the open life raft with her boyfriend, Nicholas
Abbott, after their yacht sank two days into a trip from Bermuda to
Greenpoint, N.Y.
   Abbott, 50, jumped from the raft 10 days later, and he is
believed to have drowned, according to the U.S. Coast Guard.
   Ms. Culver, 48, was in stable condition Tuesday at Hamilton's
King Edward VII Memorial Hospital.
   Dr. Goran Akerberg said in an interview that Ms. Culver survived
by drinking her own urine for four or five days before being
rescued. He said he had been worried about the amount of salt she
had taken in through the urine.
   The doctor said Ms. Culver was calm and alert when she was
transferred to the Bermuda-bound Royal Viking Star cruise ship, a
Swedish vessel, on Sunday about 350 miles northwest of this British
colony.
   Akerberg, the Royal Viking's doctor who treated Ms. Culver, was
quoting by Bermuda's Royal Gazette newspaper as saying she is ``a
very strong-willed person who wanted to survive.''
   ``She told me she was very energetic right up until the last few
days, but then she was sleeping more and more,'' he said in the
newspaper interview.
   Ms. Culver earlier told officials she and Abbott were trapped on
the 3-foot-by-10-foot raft with only a flashlight, a flotation
device, an FM radio, some cold cuts, crackers, peanuts, and a half
gallon of water.
   Akerberg also said the couple later managed to collect a
half-gallon of water during a downpour.
   The doctor said that after a while, ``she noticed her
boyfriend's personality begin to change: he didn't want to go on.
He jumped over the side of the raft. She just thought he was
cooling off, but he swam away and disappeared.''
   Abbott, a delivery man for a Bogota, N.J., courier service,
lived on a boat during the summer in New York.
   The doctor was quoted as saying Ms. Culver had been dieting for
several weeks before the trip. ``That could have helped save her
life,'' he said. ``She was already eating less.''
   He said she was severely dehydrated, undernourished, and
suffering from exposure when she was rescued.
   The Coast Guard said they had abandoned ship after a leak
developed in packing material around the propeller shaft. They put
the engine in neutral to recharge batteries, but it slipped back
into gear and blew out the packing material, letting in water.
   At a news conference Tuesday, Dr. Ronald Lightbourne, the
medical director at the hospital, said Ms. Culver was progressing
well and had eaten ham and eggs for breakfast. He said she was
transferred to the Intensive Care Unit on Monday evening ``more to
protect her from the attention of the media than as a result of her
medical condition.''
   She will undergo minor surgery Wednesday to remove patches of
sunburned skin and will be hospitalized a few more days, he said.
</TEXT>
