<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-EEC 1stLd-Writethru   08-01 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-EEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0578,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nations Discuss Food, Economic Aid for Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. food offer, conference
ending, more details. Pickup 16th graf: The spokesmen said...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Tuesday pledged
$50 million in additional food aid to Poland to help ease shortages
caused by the government's moves toward a free-market economy.
   ``We're trying to help carry them through this period,'' Curtis
Kamman, deputy assistant U.S. secretary of state for European
affairs, said at the end of a 24-nation meeting on economic aid to
Poland and Hungary.
   Austria and Switzerland also promised food aid. The European
Economic Community, a 12-nation trading bloc, earlier agreed to
remove $120 million worth of meat, grains and other products from
warehouses to ship to Poland.
   Western nations want to speed up the push in Eastern Europe for
more open political and market-oriented economic systems.
   Poland on Tuesday ended price controls and meat rationing as
part of the government's drive toward a free-market economy. There
was concern the abrupt lifting of price controls might send the
country into turmoil.
   President Bush and other world leaders last month asked the
European Economic Community to set up an aid meeting to try to
encourage democratic change and economic reforms in Poland and
Hungary. The leaders, attending their annual economic summit in
Paris, also urged emergency food shipments to Poland.
   Shortly after Bush's trip to Poland last month, the United
States promised $9 million in food from surplus stocks.
   Kamman called Tuesday's conference ``very successful.''
Participants agreed to meet again in the early fall for more
discussions and decide then whether to schedule a high-level
conference on the aid program.
   Kamman told reporters it was the ``intention of the United
States'' to provide an additional $50 million in surplus food to
Poland beginning Oct. 1. Most will be free; some might be sold on
easy loan terms.
   ``It gives them the confidence to do their price reform, and it
may help them in the long-run to keep social discontent at a
manageable level,'' Kamman said.
   EEC spokesmen said the conference's agenda focused on food aid
to Poland and economic and trade cooperation between the West and
the Poland and Hungary..
   They said Polish President Wojciech Jaruzelski sent a letter
last month asking for 685,000 tons of beef, pork, powdered milk,
butter, oils, wheat, corn, rice and sugar in the next few months.
   He also said Poland needed at least 3.7 million tons of food
next year and again in 1991, roughly $1 billion worth in each year,
according to the EEC. Moreover, he asked for 250,000 tons of feed
for animals and $220 million to $250 million in pesticides and
similar products in 1990 and again in 1991.
   The spokesmen said there was interest in devising a plan to link
the free food to changes in the structure of the Polish economy,
particularly in the poorly working system for getting food from
farms to consumers' tables. Poland has accepted the idea in
principle, they said.
   One possibility, under discussion by the Common Market, would be
to allow the Poles to sell the food on the free market and use the
money to improve the distribution chain.
   The spokesmen said the quick shipments of food were necessary to
help Poland as it goes through the painful process of restructuring
its economy. Some at the conference urged that the food be
channeled into the economy so that it doesn't worsen the
already-high inflation rate or discourage domestic food production.
   Hungary has been in the forefront of economic reforms in the
East bloc since the 1960s. Still, it has a foreign debt of about
$18 billion, the highest per capita in Eastern Europe. Poland's
foreign debt stands at $39 billion.
   Nations at meeting include the Common Market members of Britain,
Ireland, Norway, Denmark, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg,
Germany, France, Spain, Italy and Portugal. Also present were the
United States, Canada, Australia, Turkey, New Zealand, Japan,
Sweden, Switzerland, Finland, Austria, Norway and Iceland.
</TEXT>
