<DOCNO> AP890801-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     08-01 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Celebrate Birthday of Red Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers frolicked in an amusement park Tuesday
to celebrate the 62nd birthday of China's army, and thousands of
civilians flocked to an exhibit about the pro-democracy student
movement that was crushed by troops.
   Despite weeks of buildup in the media, however, there was little
other public observation of Army Day, which marks its founding on
Aug. 1, 1927.
   Also Tuesday, China's official Xinhua News Agency criticized as
traitors fugitive Chinese dissidents who have formed groups in the
United States to work for democratic reform at home.
   It also criticized foreign news reports on the dissidents'
activities, especially those of the U.S. government-run Voice of
America.
   The nationally televised evening news reported only two brief
ceremonies at Tiananmen Square, which student protesters occupied
for seven weeks until the military crackdown June 3-4 that left
hundreds, perhaps thousands of people dead.
   The square has been closed to the general public since then, and
city officials had suggested it would be filled with soldiers
Tuesday.
   Instead, one of the few places that drew a crowd was the
Military Museum of the Chinese People's Revolution, which on Monday
formally opened an exhibit on the popular student movement.
   Nearly 6,000 people visited the museum in just three hours
Tuesday, compared to 3,000 to 4,000 visitors on an average day,
museum employees said. Many were there to see the exhibit which,
like all official accounts of what the government calls a
``counter-revolutionary rebellion,'' criticizes the students and
glorifies the army.
   Crowds gathered four or five deep in front of the displays about
the student movement, and those who managed to squeeze toward the
front bent over glass cases, poring over the students' petitions,
handbills and big-character posters calling for democracy, human
rights and more freedoms.
   The exhibit also showed rows of battered army helmets, mangled
rifles with broken butts, and blood-soaked army uniforms _ evidence
of the soldiers' patience and restraint, the signs said.
   But few people lingered long in front of the displays that
lauded the army and praised the party.
   For weeks, the leadership and the media have been exhorting the
masses to make this year's Army Day particularly memorable in a
show of love and respect for the army, but most of the holiday
activities were restricted to the troops.
   The Beijing evening TV news showed soldiers gleefully driving
bumper cars and sliding down water rides at an amusement park.
   At dawn in Tiananmen Square, a group of Young Pioneers, the
Communist Party's organization for youngsters, attended the daily
flag-raising. The nationally televised evening news said the
children were told ``to learn from their martial law
soldier-uncles.''
   A few hours later, several hundred soldiers attended an award
ceremony to honor those who acted bravely during the turmoil, but
the square was empty again after 20 minutes.
   The soldiers stood facing a single red banner while a band
played the national anthem. Some soldiers were shown receiving
medals.
   The biggest commemoration came in the nation's newspapers,
almost all of which carried front-page editorials praising the army.
   ``Officers and soldiers have stood up to all tests and used
their blood and lives to protect ... the party ... and the people's
power and safety,'' the People's Daily said.
   Xinhua called the Voice of America ``the most active and open
supporter of the fugitives in their attempt to overthrow the
Chinese government.''
   ``Not long ago VOA broadcast twice its long interview with Wu'er
Kaixi, continuing to spread the lie of the `bloodletting at
Tiananmen Square.'''
   Wu'er was one of the leaders of the seven-week student
pro-democracy movement that shook China in the spring. He vowed
after fleeing China to continue fighting to avenge the hundreds and
possibly thousands of people who died when the army attacked the
protesters June 3-4.
   He and other fugitive dissidents helped lead a gathering in
Chicago last week of Chinese studying in the United States, at
which participants voted to form an All-America Chinese Student
Union to press for reform in China.
   Xinhua accused the students of accepting financial help from the
rival Nationalist government on Taiwan.
</TEXT>
