<HEAD>Japan Donates $2.5 Million to Peacekeeping Trust Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan on Tuesday donated $2.5 million to a
new U.N. fund to pay for the start-up costs of peacekeeping
missions, officials said.
   U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes said the money would be put into a
trust fund to help pay for short-term financing to implement new
peacekeeping missions.
   The world body assesses its members for the cost of
peacekeeping, but often must dip into its operating funds to pay
for start-up costs until member-states pay their assessments.
