<FIRST>r a AM-SinkHole     08-01 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sink Hole,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Playground Endangered By Abandoned Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAILEYVILLE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinkholes from an abandoned coal mine
are threatening to gobble up a school playground, officials said.
   ``It's something really serious,'' said Pittsburg County
Conservation District Manager Kevin Smith. ``Something needs to be
done quickly.''
   School starts in two weeks.
   ``It makes you feel like the world's caving in on you,'' said
Haileyville Superintendent Gary Newberry.
   Maintenance worker Bobby Morrow found the new hole, 30 feet from
the children's swings, on Thursday.
   ``I was replacing a board on the merry-go-round. I walked
through a gate and almost fell in it,'' Morrow said.
   The hole is about five feet across and is four or five feet
deep, Newberry said. ``If a small child fell in the hole, they
wouldn't be able to get out.''
   Officials covered the hole with plywood and put a fence around
it.
   Another sinkhole on the school grounds is filled several times a
year, but continues to collapse, Newberry said.
   Officials also plan to test the school grounds to find out
whether there are more cavities under the surface. The ground has
collapsed into abandoned mines at several nearby locations in
recent months.
