<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     08-01 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Owners Put Up $4.7 Million While Negotiations Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owners of the tanker that ran aground
and spilled 300,000 gallons of oil in Rhode Island Sound have
agreed to put up $4.7 million while liability negotiations
continue, the attorney general said Tuesday.
   Representatives of Ballard Shipping Co. signed a letter of
undertaking, which agrees to make available $3.2 million to pay for
damages to Rhode Island's natural resources and more than $1
million for cleanup costs not covered by the federal government,
Attorney General James O'Neil said at a news conference.
   ``In lieu of arresting the vessel we have this bond established
that we can levy upon. That doesn't mean that we can't go beyond
that if we find that there are greater damages,'' he said. ``It's a
showing of good faith by the owners.''
   Ballard Shipping is ``not even agreeing that the environment has
been damaged to the tune of $3.2 million,'' O'Neil explained.
``They are simply agreeing to put it on the table.''
   The heating oil was spilled at the entrance to Narragansett Bay
on June 23 when the Greek-flagged World Prodigy struck a reef.
   The ship's captain, Iakovos Georgudis, 43, of Athens, has been
charged under state law with failing to have a harbor pilot on
board and with polluting the coastal waters. He faces a total
$20,000 in fines and 13 months in jail if convicted. He also faces
federal misdemeanor charges.
   Ballard Shipping also said it will make available $500,000 for
settlements with individuals who were financially hurt by the spill.
   ``We're confident that $4.7 million will adequately cover the
total of the claims,'' said Nick Long, chief of the attorney
general's civil division.
   The Coast Guard has estimated the clean up costs at almost $2
million, but O'Neil said the state costs had not been fully tallied.
   Approximately $2.6 million from the federal Clean Water Act Fund
is also available to pay for part of the clean up, said Long.
   O'Neil said the attorney general's office has received
complaints from about 300 fishermen who claim they suffered
financial losses as a result of the spill.
</TEXT>
