<FIRST>u w AM-FlagBurning 1stLd-Writethru a0644 08-01 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burning, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bork Returns to Judiciary Committee to Urge Constitutional Amendment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 2nd graf pvs, ``Every politician, to include
Bork appearance; SUBS 3rd graf pvs for transition; picks up 4th graf pvs,
The committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee, opening
hearings on measures to ban desecration of the flag, was urged
Tuesday to shun partisan politics and ``punish'' flag burners by
ignoring them.
   ``Every politician in the Congress should recognize that to be
ignored is the ultimate punishment society can inflict,'' said
former Sen. Charles McC. Mathias, a Maryland Republican.
   Robert H. Bork, returning to the committee that led the way in
blocking his confirmation to the Supreme Court, testified in favor
of amending the Constitution to prohibit flag desecration.
   Bork's schedule did not allow time for committee members to
question him. But he told reporters outside the hearing room, ``I
have no particular emotional response'' to returning to the
committee that questioned him for five days in 1987 before voting
against his nomination by then-President Ronald Reagan.
   The full Senate agreed, voting against him, 58-42.
   Bork agreed there was an irony in his appearance since the man
confirmed for the seat Bork had been up for _ Anthony M. Kennedy _
voted with the majority in the Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling that flag
burning is protected free speech. Bork has said if he were on the
court he would have voted to uphold a Texas law against flag
desecration.
   Asked whether he believed the judiciary committee is capable of
handling the issue properly, Bork said, ``You may record that I
grinned broadly.''
   Mathias, recalling a Longfellow poem, said the ``ship of state
sailing majestically through history'' should treat flag burners
with the same indifference as ``slugs and snails and slimy
creatures whose submarine activities do not cause the great ship to
deviate a degree from its course.''
   The committee is considering proposals to amend the Constitution
or enact legislation to reverse a Supreme Court ruling June 21 that
said burning or desecrating the flag as a form of political protest
is a constitutional right.
   Similar proposals are being weighed in the House. A
Democratic-sponsored bill could be voted on next month in the House
after Congress returns from a recess due to begin Friday.
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden, D-Del.,
said he plans to hold four hearings on anti-flag burning proposals.
   Biden is sponsoring legislation to make to it a crime to
desecrate the American flag, an alternative to a proposed
constitutional amendment backed by the Bush administration and many
Republicans.
   Opponents of both proposals said Tuesday that Congress and
President Bush are overreacting.
   ``We are caught up in a crass competition about who loves the
flag more,'' said Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio. ``We want to use
the flag against our opponent in the next election and we want to
be sure it is not used against us.''
   But Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., sponsor of a proposed
constitutional amendment, said, ``An overwhelming majority of
Americans are looking to the Congress to ... restore the proper
civil respect for our American flag.''
   He noted that after the high court ruling, the Senate voted 97-3
to express disapproval with the justices' decision. That action
carried no legal weight.
   Metzenbaum and Sens. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., were the three who opposed the resolution
condemning the court ruling.
   All three are Judiciary Committee members who urged their
colleagues Tuesday to withdraw plans to reverse the court's
decision.
   Humphrey produced a pair of bedroom slippers with an American
flag design. ``That seems to me to be desecration,'' he said.
</TEXT>
