<FIRST>r w AM-HouseEthics     08-01 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Ethics,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes More Money for Ethics Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House decided by voice vote Tuesday to
give the ethics committee an infusion of $500,000 to continue its
work this year.
   No further congressional action is needed. The committee spent
more than $1.5 million for the yearlong investigation of former
House Speaker Jim Wright, who resigned his seat in June after the
committee charged him with 69 rules violations.
   The panel could face other major investigations if it decides to
proceed with complaints filed against GOP Whip Newt Gingrich of
Georgia, Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill, and Rep. Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens,
R-Ohio.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., asked the panel to investigate
whether a controversial book deal arranged by Gingrich violated
campaign finance law, a House rule on outside income and a rule
prohibiting retention of gifts from those with a direct interest in
legislation.
   The committee has hired the Chicago law firm that investigated
Wright to recommend whether the panel should begin a preliminary
investigation of Gingrich.
   Three House members have asked the committee to investigate
allegations by a Peace Corps volunteer that Rep. Gus Savage,
D-Ill., sexually assaulted her while he was on an official trip to
Zaire.
   And the House Republican caucus has asked the panel to probe
Rep. Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens, R-Ohio, who was convicted of
contributing to the delinquency or unruliness of a minor. He is
appealing.
</TEXT>
