<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0650 08-01 0822</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Go Up; Walesa Urges Kiszczak to be Voted Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 22 grafs UPDATING with proposal that Solidarity and
Peasant Party form coalition with Solidarity prime minister. ADDS LaserPhoto
number. Pickup 18th graf: Food prices ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poles expressed shock Tuesday at soaring
food prices and Parliament dismissed the government of Prime
Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski. Legislators argued over Rakowski's
successor .
   Solidarity lawmakers heaped criticism on the outgoing
administration's economic policies. The union movement was reported
to be considering a proposal that could lead to a Solidarity prime
minister.
   Meat price increases on Tuesday were the highest in recent
memory. Food prices skyrocketed under the ``marketization'' program
put together by Rakowski's government. Across Poland there were
empty shelves and bewildered shoppers.
   ``Where is the meat? Where is the meat?'' cried out an old man
in a store without a scrap of meat.
   ``I am going to America,'' a woman shopper said in despair.
   Authorities say the increases are needed to prompt farmers to
deliver to market and stabilize the level of state subsidies to the
food industry.
   A vote on Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak as prime
minister, set for Tuesday, was postponed amid signs his candidacy
was in trouble in Poland's new pluralistic Parliament.
   Rakowski went to a hospital Tuesday after reportedly feeling
faint but returned to Parliament in the evening for urgent talks
within his communist coalition.
   According to several deputies involved, the caucus leader for
the communist-allied Peasant Party, Aleksander Bentkowski, proposed
that the Peasants and Solidarity form a government with a
Solidarity prime minister. The communists would be left only with
ministries controlling police and the army.
   Opposition sources said Solidarity was considering the proposal.
   One Peasant Party faction was in rebellion against the
communists and its own leadership, walking out when Rakowski came
to address the caucus.
   ``We have a general as president. Now they want a general as
premier. And we know they want a communist to be deputy premier,''
said one rebel, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   A member of the Solidarity delegation flew to Gdansk to review
the situation with union founder Lech Walesa. Walesa had urged
Solidarity followers to vote against Kiszczak, the candidate
advanced Monday by the Polish United Workers (Communist) Party.
   Rakowski, elected party first secretary four days ago, was
formally dismissed as prime minister by Parliament on Tuesday.
   Referring to Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula's claim that
the ``ship of the Polish economy is on the right course,''
Solidarity Deputy Ryszard Bugaj said, ``It seems to me that the
situation is the exact opposite. This ship is sinking.''
   Walesa did not explain his reasons for urging deputies to vote
against Kiszczak who, as interior minister, was in charge of the
police forces.
   The image of the top policeman as head of government has upset
many Poles, and Solidarity met dissent from followers when it
accepted Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's election as president July 19.
   ``I am against Gen. Kiszczak's candidacy for prime minister,''
Walesa said, without elaborating.
   Solidarity parliamentary leader Bronislaw Geremek said Monday he
expected Kiszczak to be elected even without support from
Solidarity lawmakers, who are outnumbered 299-161 by the communist
coalition in the Sejm. But the matter appeared uncertain Tuesday.
   The Peasant Party's 76 votes are needed to give the 173-strong
communist delegation a working majority.
   The parliament session began with criticism of the 9-month-old
Rakowski government that lasted nearly five hours, dwelling on high
inflation and the lack of goods in stores.
   Sekula defended the government, saying it lifted over 3,000
regulations and brought ``a different quality to our nation. ... We
acted in Poland's interest and in the interest of ... our society.''
   Food prices now will vary from store to store and region to
region, depending on supply and demand, officials said. According
to the state-controlled newspaper Zycie Warszawy, the new prices
included:
   _ Sugar, 60 cents for 2.2 pounds, up from 42 cents, a 43 percent
increase.
   _ Butter, 48 cents for about half a pound, up from 27 cents, a
73 percent increase.
   _ Flour, 12 cents for 2.2 pounds, up from 7 cents, a 56 percent
increase.
   Meat increases in state stores were steeper. Ham went from $1.92
for 2.2 pounds to about $7.22, a 275 percent increase, and pork
went from $1.08 for 2.2 pounds to about $4.21, a 288 percent
increase. The meat prices were still somewhat below those charged
at private farmer's markets.
   The average monthly income in Poland is $127.
   On Monday, parliament passed a key piece of legislation designed
to blunt the population's anger about inflation, now in triple
digits. The law, agreed to in principle in April by government and
Solidarity negotiators, calls for the incomes of workers, farmers
and pensioners to be compensated automatically for 80 percent of
the rise in the cost of living.
</TEXT>
