<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0677 08-01 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0677,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Swap Offer Stands; Contacts on Hostages Advanced</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to include possible Red Cross visits; picks
up 4th pvs `Israel insisted'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Tuesday his
government was making contacts in an effort to free hostages in
Lebanon, and sources said direct approaches were made to Lebanese
Shiite Moslems for a prisoner swap.
   Israeli officials said it remained willing to exchange a Moslem
cleric kidnapped by Israel, and other Lebanese Shiite prisoners,
for Israeli soldiers and Western hostages. The radical Shiite group
Hezbollah, or Party of God, issued a statement spurning the deal.
   Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner, called the offer humanitarian
and fair, and added: ``We believe it is not Hezbollah's last word.''
   Israel television said the army would let the International
Committee of the Red Cross visit the kidnapped Lebanese clergymen
and his two abducted assistants if Shiite groups allowed a Red
Cross visit to three Israeli soldiers believed to be held captive
in south Lebanon.
   A Defense Ministry spokesman confirmed the report but would not
give details.
   Israel insisted it would not free Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid
despite threats by Shiite kidnappers to kill Western hostages in
Lebanon.
   When asked by the national news agency Itim whether Obeid might
be turned over to U.S. authorities, Shamir replied he could not say
what might be done.
   The Israelis say Obeid planned guerrilla attacks on Israel and
directed the kidnapping in February 1988 of Lt. Col. William R.
Higgins, a U.S. Marine officer on U.N. duty in south Lebanon.
   On Monday, Higgins' captors said they had hanged him and
released a poor-quality videotape showing a man on a gallows. The
kidnappers said he was hanged in retaliation for Obeid's abduction,
but there have been reports Higgins was killed several months ago.
   Shamir said Tuesday night that Higgins was ``apparently dead,''
and added: ``We express our deep sorrow to his family and the
American people.''
   During a factory tour earlier, Shamir said there was ``a common
interest and a common goal'' between Israel and the United States
on freeing hostages, but noted the reason for capturing Obeid was
to free the three Israeli soldiers held in south Lebanon.
   ``The only purpose of our operation was to free our captured
soldiers,'' he said. ``If, at the same time, we manage to set free
other hostages, we will be happy.''
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens told reporters in Jerusalem that
Israel viewed the new death threats as ``disinformation.''
   ``We do not have much faith in the truthfulness of the
announcements that come from these organizations,'' he said. ``It
would probably not be very wise to take any action based on that
information.''
   Itim, the Israeli news agency, reported Tuesday that Shamir was
making contacts to free Western captives, and he said on his
factory tour: ``There are permanent contacts with various factors
about the release of the hostages.''
   Pazner said the contacts were indirect, through the United
States and international organizations.
   Some Israeli sources, speaking privately, said talks were being
held directly with Lebanese Shiites about the proposed
prisoner-hostage trade.
   Security sources said Israel is believed to hold 50-60 Lebanese
Shiite Moslems in Israel and, through its surrogate South Lebanon
Army militia, about 300 in southern Lebanon.
   Israel made the offer to free Shiite prisoners in exchange for
its soldiers and foreign hostages on Monday, before the
announcement that Higgins had been killed.
   Shamir defended the abduction of Obeid as ``a strong, energetic
effort'' to help free the captured soldiers.
   ``If need be we will take stronger steps,'' he told a ceremony
in Jerusalem marking the 49th anniversary of the death of Israeli
pioneer Zeev Jabotinsky.
</TEXT>
