<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     08-01 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Town officials unamused by a car
dealer's latest advertising gimmicks want him to stop the monkey
business and send out the clown.
   ``People here like to see advertising that is in keeping with
their vision of what the town represents _ quiet, not like the
city, tasteful and somewhat quaint,'' said Town Councilwoman Gaytha
A. Langlois.
   The 6-foot-tall electric gorilla and the mechanical clown at the
Paul Bailey Used Cars dealership just don't quite make it, she said.
   Town Manager Stephen A. Alfred said recently the town can't
order the dealership to get rid of the gorilla and the clown, but
officials have asked the manager, Keith Bailey, to voluntarily pull
the plug on the displays.
   Bailey said he would consider removing the advertisements.
   ``I thought it was a pretty good idea, but I do maybe feel that
there could be a traffic hazard in some instances,'' he said.
</TEXT>
