<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Prices     08-01 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Prices,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Stunned By Stiff Price Increases and Empty Shops</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customers gaped in disbelief Tuesday at
freshly lettered signs announcing the highest meat price increases
in recent memory. The cost of other key food items also skyrocketed.
   ``Where is the meat?'' cried out an old man in a store without
meat.
   ``There is no meat, just the price list,'' a woman complained.
   There were empty shelves and bewildered shoppers at meat stores
and markets throughout Poland as official price increases took
effect.
   Authorities said the increases are needed to prompt farmers to
deliver their meat and produce to market and stabilize the level of
state subsidies to the food industry.
   Price increases occur regularly in Poland, but the scale of the
latest boost drove many customers to despair. Lifting of the ration
system after seven years caused no joy since meat was so scarce.
   ``I am going to America! Of course, I am going to America!,''
shouted one woman after taking a look at the newest list of meat
prices in the Supersam supermarket.
   The price of pork roast, an expensive and popular cut, rose from
980 zlotys ($1.18) to 3,850 zlotys ($4.64) a kilogram (2.2 pounds).
Regular sausage rose from 52 cents to $1.80 a kilogram.
   The average monthly income in Poland is $127.
   Private farmers standing outside a state market in central
Warsaw demanded even higher prices. One farmer wanted $7.23 a
kilogram for ham and $4.82 a kilo for beef that was covered with
flies.
   Inside the Hala Mirowska market supplies of state-supplied meat
were all sold up by 2 p.m.
   Customers at other shops were less fortunate. A large meat store
near parliament closed Tuesday for a monthlong vacation. The
usually well-stocked Supersam was down to scrawny chickens and
cheap cuts of pork by midafternoon.
   A sign in the empty meat shop on Krakowskie Przedmiescie street
said the store had frozen duck and goose available and a sales
clerk said she hoped chickens would be delivered later in the day.
   ``How much will the chickens cost?'' asked one customer. ``I
don't know, dear, I don't know,'' replied the sales clerk.
   Until now, meat prices in state stores have been the same
throughout country. As of Tuesday, however, prices will be
determined by the supplier and may vary from store to store.
   Among other items that cost more Tuesday were sugar, which went
up from 42 cents to 60 cents a kilogram, but was unavailable in
many shops. Butter was up from 27 cents for a quarter kilogram to
48 cents. Flour increased from 7 cents a kilogram to 12 cents.
   In one food store some items available were unfit for
consumption. Stacks of moldy bread were piled in a corner. Bottles
of milk with flies inside were on the shelves.
   ``Why bother to stand in line for stuff like this,'' said a
woman as she picked through the available items.
   Even the normally well-supplied restaurant in the parliament
where deputies met to debate the formation of a new government felt
the pinch of the new prices.
   Bean soup and tripe were the main items as the restaurant was
out of one of the lawmakers' favorite breakfast dishes _ hot dogs
wrapped in bacon. ``We don't have any and we don't know how much
we'll have to charge when we get them,'' a waitress told a
Solidarity deputy.
   The food price increases are part of a government
``marketization'' program aimed to prompt farmers to produce more
by introducing free-market concepts.
   Some Solidarity lawmakers claimed marketization was only a way
of disguising price increases. Over the weekend the government said
reduction of subsidies would diminish ``eventually.''
   Parliament on Monday passed by a 335-29 vote legislation
designed to cushion consumers from the impact of price increases
and inflation now rising at an estimated 160 percent rate annually.
   The law on indexing _ agreed to in principle in April by
government and Solidarity negotiators _ calls for incomes of
workers, farmers and pensioners, to be automatically conmpensated
by 80 percent of the rise in the cost of living.
   Lawmakers hope indexing will reduce the chance of strikes and
overall wage increases from outpacing price rises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
