<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-MilitaryOptions     08-01 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Military Options,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Options `Dusted Off'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``All options are open'' to President Bush if
he intends to retaliate for the apparent murder of Lt. Col. William
R. Higgins, a Pentagon spokesman said Tuesday, but he refused to
define them or say whether any action had been taken to ready U.S.
forces in the Mideast.
   Spokesman Pete Williams said the aircraft carrier Coral Sea,
which is on duty in the Mediterranean, left the Egyptian port of
Alexandria ``a little early'' Tuesday, but he declined to give its
destination or say why it had put out to sea earlier than planned.
   ``We don't discuss future deployments. ... We don't discuss
alert status,'' Williams said when asked about the ship's movement.
   Queried about the list of miliary options that Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney delivered Monday evening to the White House, Williams
replied, ``All options are open,'' and refused to discuss them
further.
   Navy sources said the Coral Sea, on duty with the 6th Fleet in
the Mediterranean, left ``a few hours'' ahead of its scheduled
departure.
   The carrier is accompanied by its battle group, which included
the nuclear cruiser Virginia and the Aegis cruiser San Jacinto,
said the sources, who spoke on the condition they not be identified.
   Also on hand is a 2,400-member Marine contingent known as the
Amphibious Readiness Group, which is aboard three ships designed to
aid any landing assault they are ordered to carry out, the sources
said.
   Overall, there are some 24 U.S. ships in the Mediterranean at
this time, with approximately 20 others in the Persian Gulf and
Indian Ocean region, the sources added.
   The battleship Iowa, which is not allowed to use its 16-inch
guns pending the outcome of a Navy inquiry into the April explosion
in one of its three turrets, is on a port call in Marseilles,
France, the sources said. The ship is equipped with a variety of
weapons, including cruise missiles, that could be used if
necessary, sources said.
   A Pentagon official familiar with the options presented to the
president confirmed that they included such possibilities as the
bombing or shelling of certain areas, a surgical strike against
specific terrorist camps, or even a simple ``show-of-the-flag'' of
the U.S. forces on duty in the region.
   ``A lot of these options have been around for some time,'' said
the official, who noted that crises in the Middle East have
bedeviled more than one recent president.
   The Joint Chiefs' staff draws up such options for consideration
by the president and National Security Council, and includes the
pros and cons of each step.
   ``This isn't a situation where they had to come up with a lot of
original thinking. Some of these options have been on the shelf for
some time. In many cases, they dusted 'em off and evaluated them in
light of the current situation,'' said the official.
   He cautioned, however, that there is little indication that any
high-level planning for a full-blown military strike is underway.
For example, the Joint Chiefs of Staff have not met, he noted.
   And the pattern of the Pentagon in recent history has been to
use military force as only the last resort, the source said.
   ``These guys have been on the cautious side,'' he said.
   Each option must be assessed for the kind of target it presents,
the type of weaponry eeded, the type of forces that may be deployed
against U.S. forces and the kind of ``collateral damage,'' or
number of civilians that might be killed in any action, the source
said.
   But, as in many past cases dealing with the U.S. hostages, such
considerations are not viewed from a strictly limited military
point of view, the Pentagon officials noted.
   As one Army source said, ``With the power of the 6th Fleet, we
could blow Beirut off the map. But what good would that do?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
