<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Uprising     08-01 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Uprising,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Marks Anniversary of Doomed Uprising Against Nazis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR51</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's communist president and Roman
Catholic prelate dedicated a monument Tuesday to the fighters in
Warsaw's doomed 1944 uprising against the Nazis in which more than
200,000 Poles perished.
   Sirens wailed throughout the city at 5 p.m. _ the hour when the
uprising began 45 years ago.
   In the evening, after the official ceremony attended by
President Wojciech Jaruzelski and Cardinal Jozef Glemp, the
opposition movement held its own observance attended by Solidarity
lawmakers. They went by bus from parliament to a different, newly
dedicated monument in Powazki Cemetery. That monument is dedicated
to the leaders of the underground resistance during World Wasr II.
   The Waraw uprising and its brutal aftermath remain controversial
in Poland because most of the underground leaders were loyal to the
wartime government-in-exile in London, which was not recognized by
Soviet dictator Josef Stalin.
   Many Poles believe Stalin deliberately withheld help for the
Warsaw fighters, allowing the Nazis to wipe them out while the Red
Army stalled its advance on the eastern side of the Vistula River
that runs through Warsaw.
   Stalin also refused British requests to let relief planes land
behind Red Army lines to supply the 63-day uprising.
   When the Red Army arrived in Warsaw in January 1945, after the
Nazis had systematically destroyed the city no significant force
remained to resist the communist takeover of the country.
   In the years immediately after World War II, the anniversary of
the uprising was not observed and soldiers of the resistance Home
Army who remained in Poland often were imprisoned and deported to
Siberia or executed.
   Jaruzelski referred indirectly to those events in his speech at
the new monument near the city's Old Town section.
   ``This epoch included injustice, human harm and concealment,''
he said. ``This book has already been closed.''
   ``The atmosphere is different today,'' said Jan Kostrzewski, who
served as a doctor in the uprising and who headed the committee
that erected the monument. ``After more than 40 years, efforts are
made to repair the wrongs. .... But it is not easy to remove from
our hearts the bitter sediment.''
   Glemp later consecrated the monument with holy water as
Jaruzelski, in full military uniform looked on, the first time in
memory that a Polish leader took part in such a religious ceremony.
   The communist government normalized relations with the Polish
church this year and established diplomatic relations with the
Vatican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
