<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala-Killing     08-01 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala-Killing,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guatemalan Gunmen Kill Ruling Party Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five gunmen dragged a leader of
Guatemala's ruling Christian Democratic Party out of his home
Tuesday and shot him dead, witnesses and officials said.
   Police said no group claimed responsibility for kiling Danilo
Barillas Rodriguez and the motive was not clear. President Vinicio
Cerezo, who went to the scene called his friend ``a victim of
democracy.''
   ``I am deeply concerned. This is deplorable,'' Cerezo told
reporters.
   Cerezo took office in January 1986 for a five-year term as the
first elected civilian president after 16 years of rightist
military rule.
   Leftist guerrillas have fought the government for four decades
and right-wing death squads also have operated in Guatemala.
   Barillas had been chairman of a Guatemala city council
commission in charge of urban planning and development since 1987.
He previously served as Guatemala's ambassador to Spain, general
secretary of the Christian Democratic Party and member of the
Chamber of Deputies.
   Cerezo blamed ``extremist groups'' for the slaying and promised
the killers would be found.
   Witnesses said five armed men barged into Barillas' home and
dragged him out. They said the five opened fire after he managed to
slip away and started running, wounding him.
   Barillas then tried to dive under a parked car, and one of the
gunmen shot him dead. The gunmen then fled on foot, one of the
witnesses said.
   A police examiner at the scene said Barillas' body had at least
30 bullet wounds.
   As Guatemala's ambassador to Madrid, Barillas participated in
talks between leaders of the Revolutionary Nationalist Unity, a
coalition of the four guerrilla groups, and a government delegation.
   The talks were to establish grounds for peace negotiations but
did not progress, principally because the military insisted on
complete surrender by the rebels.
   Barillas' death comes amid mounting labor unrest and terrorist
attacks. One person was killed and several were injured in half a
dozen bomb explosions in the capital over the past two weeks.
   About 50,000 public school teachers and government employees
have been on strike for almost two months, demanding higher pay.
They have snarled traffic in Guatemala City with almost daily
street marches and demonstrations.
</TEXT>
