<FIRST>r a AM-TunnelDeaths     08-01 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tunnel Deaths,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>OSHA Recommends Company Be Prosecuted in Fatal Tunnel Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency recommended Tuesday that two
companies involved in a sewer tunnel explosion that killed three
workers be prosecuted on criminal charges.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration sent the
recommendation to the U.S. attorney's office, which will review the
Nov. 10 accident to see if charges are warranted.
   The workers were killed when methane gas collected and exploded
in a Milwaukee Metropolitan Sewerage District tunnel that was under
construction.
   The victims had entered the tunnel to check levels of the
naturally occurring gas. Earlier in the day the methane had reached
a dangerous level and forced an evacuation.
   OSHA had already filed numerous civil charges against the S.A.
Healy Co. of McCook, Ill., the tunnel contractor, and CH2M Hill of
Corvallis, Ore., an engineering firm that supervised the work. The
agency also recommended $1.15 million in fines.
   OSHA now wants the civil cases postponed so the case can be
reviewed for possible criminal violations, U.S. Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole said in a statement Tuesday.
   ``We are determined to do whatever is necessary to prevent the
tragic recurrence of such accidents in our nation's ever growing
number of tunnel projects,'' Dole said.
   Both firms have contested the civil citations.
   Healy president George Malina said he did nt know how any
criminal wrongdoing could be found in the accident, which developed
out of unanticipated conditions, not out of any willful acts.
   Wyatt McCauley, spokesman for CH2M Hill, did not immediately
return a phone call to his office in Denver.
   Under the civil proceedings, the companies face fines for
alleged violations of the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Criminal prosecution would carry fines plus possible imprisonment
of up to six months.
   Healy was cited in May for 68 alleged willful violations of
health and safety regulations, and CH2M Hill was cited for 47
willful violations.
</TEXT>
