<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-01 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says It Seized 100 Rockets, Arrested 50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army seized 100 rockets and
arrested about 50 people in raids aimed at ending devastating
rocket attacks on Kabul by Moslem guerrillas, the government said
Tuesday.
   No rockets fell on the city Tuesday, but 14 fired Monday killed
24 people and wounded 58.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said the military
was given urgent instructions Monday to take whatever action
necessary to stop the attacks, which have occurred almost daily
since late June.
   U.N. sources say 281 people have been killed and 745 wounded
since June 25 in rocket attacks and a car bombing. Virtually all
the victims were civilians.
   A major search operation started late Monday and continued into
Tuesday in the city and environs, Amani said, and government forces
confiscated many documents and weapons and made about 50 arrests.
   No group claimed responsibility for the rocket attacks. The
Soviet-sponsored government blames the U.S.-backed guerrillas, who
began fighting after a communist coup in April 1978.
   Amani also reported new fighting between rival fundamentalist
guerrilla groups, Hezb-e-Islami and the Jamiat-e-Islami, in Herat
province near the Iranian border.
   He said 12 members of Jamiat-e-Islami were killed and six
wounded, and six supporters of Hezb-e-Islami were wounded. He gave
no date for the fighting.
   Guerrillas sources have said Hezb-e-Islami supporters attacked a
Jamiat group July 9 in northern Afghanistan, killing 30 people,
including several field commanders.
   Fighting among guerrilla groups has been mentioned as one reason
they have failed to oust the government since the Red Army withdrew
in February after nine years of involvement in the civil war.
   In Stockholm, Sweden, on Tuesday, the United States and Soviet
Union held their first meeting on Afghanistan since the Soviet
withdawal.
   After his meeting with Soviet Ambassador Nikolai Kozyrev, John
Kelly, assistant U.S. secretary of state, said there was a ``frank
exchange of views'' and ``significant differences'' remained.
   The Soviets complain of U.S. aid to the insurgents and
Washington says the Kremlin has increased arms shipments to the
Kabul government.
   Western diplomats in neighboring Pakistan reported an attempt in
Kabul to overthrow President Najib and said a house-to-house search
for suspected conspirators had increased tensions within the ruling
Communist Party.
   One said the hint of a coup attempt emerged about two weeks ago.
   ``There is no indication of how close to being launched the
reported plot was when it was discovered,'' the diplomat said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Multiple sources have
reported a sudden upsurge in tension within'' the ruling party.
   A leftist Pakistan newspaper, The Frontier Post, said Defense
Minister Shah Nawaz Tanai was under house arrest for alleged
involvement in the attempt against Najib, who uses only one name.
   It quoted the pro-guerrilla Afghan Media Resource Center. The
diplomats said the claim could not be substantiated.
</TEXT>
