<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Soviets     08-01 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Soviets,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Offers to Mediate Deadlocked Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze announced Tuesday that Moscow was willing to mediate
deadlocked peace talks between Iran and Iraq, Tehran radio reported.
   Shevardnadze, who left Tehran Tuesday after a two-day visit,
also was quoted as telling Iran's President-elect Hashemi
Rafsanjani that Iraq should withdraw from any Iranian territory it
still holds.
   ``We deeply regret that a group of Iranian and Iraqi people are
held captives, but their release would be impossible before Iraq's
withdrawal from Iranian soil,'' the broadcast, monitored in
Nicosia, quoted Shevardnadze as saying. He referred to more than
100,000 prisoners of war held by both sides.
   In a meeting with Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati,
Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union was willing to exploit good
relations with both Persian Gulf war foes in an effort to further
the talks, according to the broadcast.
   Iran-Iraq peace talks started five days after a U.N.-mediated
cease-fire halted the 8-year war last Aug. 20, but they deadlocked
immediately.
   Further negotiations faltered over Tehran's demand that Iraq
withdraw its troops from 380 square miles of Iranian territory and
Baghdad's insistence that the Shatt Al-Arab waterway should belong
to Iraq. Iran argues that sovereignty over the waterway should be
shared.
   Referring to recently improved bilateral ties, Shevardnadze
said:``Our two countries have opened a new chapter in relations.''
   The radio said Velayati welcomed Shevardnadze's offer to
intercede in the peace talks.
   The Soviets, Iraq's main arms suppliers in the gulf war, are
thought to have leverage with Baghdad.
   Shevardnadze also met Tuesday with Iranian Premier Hussein
Musavi, the radio said.
   During a June trip to Moscow, Rafsanjani signed agreements worth
$6 billion, including an arms agreement.
   Details of the arms deal were not released, but Iran is known to
seeking new weaponry to rebuild its armed forces after the
Iran-Iraq war.
   The Soviets also will help Iran rebuild several key industrial
complexes damaged in the war, construct new power stations and
assist in off-shore oil exploration.
   The deals are to be partly financed through annual exports of
Iranian natural gas to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
