<FIRST>r a AM-FairShooting     08-01 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fair Shooting,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>9-Year-Old Victim of Random Stabbing Buried</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners packed a church Tuesday to
bid farewell to a 9-year-old girl allegedly stabbed to death by an
escaped mental patient in an act of ``undiluted evil.''
   About 300 people filled the Yalesville United Methodist Church
for Jessica Short's funeral. Among the mourners was the ambulance
crew who tried to save Jessica after she was attacked in front of
her mother and dozens of other witnesses at a crowded street fair.
   ``There is grief and there are tears, but there is also horror
and burning anger at the circumstances of her death,'' the Rev.
Richard Simmons told the mourners. ``What can we do, we all ask?''
   Perhaps God's grace, Simmons said, will ``bring some good things
out of a crime that seems to us like undiluted evil.''
   David Peterson, 37, a mental patient at Connecticut Valley
Hospital in Middletown, was charged with murder. Police, hospital
officials, and state mental health officials have begun
investigations into the circumstances of Peterson's release.
   Police said he picked Jessica at random out of hundreds of
people at a street fair in Middletown on Friday.
   ``I don't think there are any good answers why,'' said Virginia
Towle of Wallingford, a family friend. ``My only answer would be
that this man was terribly sick.''
   Jessica's uncle, Andrew Reynolds, read a short remembrance
written by Jessica's grandmother that described her as a family
peacemaker who was sensitive beyond her years.
   Jessica also was looking forward to her role as an angel in a
summer ballet, the grandmother wrote.
   Outside the church, police officers formed an honor guard, and a
police escort led the procession to In Memoriam Cemetery.
</TEXT>
