<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-01 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remnants Of Chantal Drench Southeast Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Southeast Texas was hit with a deluge of rain _ 8{ inches at one
spot _ from the remnants of Hurricane Chantal and thunderstorms
swept through the lower Mississippi Valley to the southern Atlantic
Coast on Tuesday.
   Chantal hit southeast Texas on Tuesday morning and weakened to a
tropical storm. At 3 p.m. EDT, the center of the storm was 25 miles
north of Houston and moving northwest at 12 mph.
   Maximum sustained winds decreased to 55 mph, with higher gusts
in squalls mainly over the Gulf of Mexico to the south of the
center. The storm was expected to weaken as it moved further inland.
   In addition to strong winds, torrential rains were reported
across southeast Texas. More than 7 inches of rain fell at
Friendswood and Houston Tuesday morning, with 4 inches dumped in
one hour. Clear Lake City was drenched by 8{ inches of rain, while
Galveston received 6\ inches.
   Widespread street flooding was reported throughout Brazoria,
Fort Bend, Galveston and southern Harris Counties in southeast
Texas. Access roads and underpasses on Interstate 45, near
Dickinson, were flooded and several roads were closed. Highway 6
was flooded near Arcola and Sugarland and widespread street
flooding was reported at Rosenburg.
   Flash flood watches were in effect for southeast Texas and the
upper Texas coast, as well as southwest central and southeast
sections of Louisiana. Ten to 15 inches of rain were possible
across parts of eastern Texas, with 3 to 5 inches possible over
parts of central and southern Louisiana.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered Tuesday afternoon from
the southern Plains across the lower Mississippi Valley to the
southern half of the Atlantic Coast. Showers and thunderstorms were
also scattered over western Montana, with showers along the Oregon
Coast.
   A flash-flood watch was posted for the northwest mountains of
Wyoming because of possible heavy rains and flooding of creeks and
streams.
   In southwest Virginia, thunderstorms brought heavy rain through
Christiansburg and Shawsville.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included nearly 7\ inches at Houston, and 4} inches at Ellington
Air Force Base and Galveston, Texas.
   In the northern Plains, however, sunny and hot weather
prevailed. Readings were in the 90s over extreme eastern Montana,
North Dakota and much of South Dakota.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Astoria, Ore., to 106 degrees at Needles, Calif.
Tuesday's low in the Lower 48 states was 33 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstorms
through central and eastern Texas and southeast Oklahoma; scattered
showers and thunderstorms through west Texas, the rest of Oklahoma,
and from the lower Mississippi Valley across Alabama to the south
Atlantic coastal states; scattered showers and thunderstorms from
the northern Pacific Coast to Montana, from central Nebraska across
eastern South Dakota and northwest Iowa to Minnesota, and from
northern New York to western New England; and thunderstorms
scattered from North Dakota to Wyoming.
   Temperatures were forecast in the 70s through northern New
England, the Pacific Northwest and along the California Coast;
between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and
90s throughout the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
