<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls     08-01 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dole Hints at Parliamentary Maneuver on S&amp;L Bailout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas on
Tuesday threatened a parliamentary maneuver that could help force
passage of President Bush's savings and loan bailout before
Congress goes on vacation by attaching it to essential legislation.
   A Democratic-controlled House-Senate conference committee last
week voted to send landmark S&amp;L legislation to the full House and
Senate for final action this week.
   But, Bush and congressional Democrats are feuding over the
Democrat-backed financing plan in the package. Bush proposes an
accounting maneuver to exclude $50 billion in S&amp;L spending from the
official budget deficit, while the Democratic plan would send the
deficit soaring over the next three years but not count the S&amp;L
portion against official deficit limits.
   The two sides are deadlocked, with each claiming to have enough
votes to block the plan in the Senate. Under that chamber's rules,
60 of 100 senators must vote to approve either financing plan.
   In a letter to Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
and House Speaker Thomas Foley, D-Wash., Dole said he may move to
attach the S&amp;L legislation, with the Republican financing plan, to
another piece of legislation that must be passed for the government
to continue operating.
   Dole said he may attempt to package the S&amp;L bill with another
bill raising the nation's debt limit above $2.8 trillion. The
administration says unless the debt limit is increased, the
government is in danger of running out of borrowing authority in
mid-August, while Congress is scheduled to leave town on Friday of
this week.
   If the government can't legally borrow money, theoretically it
would be forced to shut down.
   A bill passed by the House and sent to the Senate on Tuesday
would raise the debt limit by $70 billion, enough to keep the
government operating through October.
   Dole said he was responding to a threat by the House to pass the
S&amp;L bill, with the Democratic financing plan, and then recess for a
month. That would leave the Senate with no choice but to accept the
Democratic plan or put off passage of S&amp;L legislation until after
Labor Day.
   ``I strongly object to such a take-it-or-leave-it approach since
this action may delay final passage of the S&amp;L legislation until
September,'' Dole wrote. ``In my view, neither house of Congress
should adjourn until the S&amp;L legislation is completed.''
   On Wednesday, the House Rules Committee is expected to schedule
a House vote on Thursday. The Senate vote would follow on Friday,
the day Congress expects to recess.
   In other S&amp;L news, federal regulators said late Tuesday they
took control of a thrift institution in Lubbock, Texas, bringing
the number under government control to 254 in 33 states.
   The institution, Caprock Savings and Loan Association, had
assets of $457 million and deposits of $414 million in 12,733
accounts. The takeover, by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.,
will not affect depositors.
   The FDIC has been taking over the sickest of the nation's failed
S&amp;Ls since February. The goal is to minimize losses and supervise
operations until Congress approves the funding needed to close or
merge the institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890801-0167 </DOCNO>
