<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1937EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BrooklinevsDukakis     08-01 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brookline vs Dukakis,0678</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Dukakis' Hometown to Sue Him in Local Aid Dispute ^By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Add one more lump to the list of hard
knocks Gov. Michael S. Dukakis has endured this year: His own
hometown planned Tuesday to sue his administration over how local
aid is doled out to cities and towns.
   Brookline, an affluent town just outside of Boston, has
faithfully backed Dukakis since his political career began as a
state representative in 1962. But at 9 a.m. Wednesday, attorneys
for the town planned to file a lawsuit in Suffolk Superior Court
essentially accusing Dukakis of being unfair to his home town and
scores of others.
   Selectman Chairman Jeffrey Allen, a long-time supporter of
Dukakis, called the move ``painful (and) emotional'' but necessary.
The administration responded icily by saying that the concerns of
all communities would be considered, regardless of who lived there.
   ``It's a very difficult decision for those of us in Brookline to
take,'' Allen said Tuesday.
   ``To get to the point of where we're actually suing the state or
the governor over his actions is a very painful, emotional step for
me to come to but I think he was wrong and I don't think his
actions in changing the local aid formula are legally defensible.''
   The issue of state financial aid to cities and towns for
schools, police and fire protection has been a particularly hot
topic this year. The state's budget troubles _ which many blame on
Dukakis _ have led to sharp reductions in local aid.
   Brookline argues that Dukakis has violated state law by using
one formula to distribute local aid and another to cut it. In
Brookline's case the use of two formulas means that instead of
facing a local aid reduction of $1.1 million, the actual reduction
will be $1.9 million.
   ``We've benefited in good years and if we have to suffer in lean
years we'll do that. What we won't do is suffer disproportionately
with other communities,'' Allen said.
   Dukakis was at a national governor's conference in Chicago
Tuesday and unavailable for comment.
   John Hanson, a fiscal aide to the governor, defended the use of
a different local aid formula designed to favor poorer communities
in cutting grants to cities and towns.
   But he added that the governor has not made a final decision on
whether the controversial formula will even be used. Dukakis has
until Thursday morning to make that decision _ that's when local
aid figures are slated to go out to communities.
   ``The concerns that cities and towns are expressing certainly
weigh into consideration,'' Hanson said. ``I don't think the
concerns of one particular town, whether it's the governor's home
town or not, is particularly relevant at this point.''
   Dukakis last month reduced local aid by $210 million. The use of
a second formula came to light when it was revealed that $100
million of those cuts would be made on a per capita basis instead
of a complicated ``needs basis'' formula by which aid is
distributed.
   Hanson defended the per capita formula, which he said would hurt
the poorest communities least because it avoids cutting local aid
under the same formula as it was given out. That method distributed
most of the money to the neediest communities.
   To cut local aid under the original formula, Hanson said,
``undoes what we've been trying to do for the last six years.''
   When the Legislature overrode the $100 million cut, Dukakis
announced he would withhold the money anyway, using his power to
impound funds. But his fiscal aides said this week he is not bound
to the controversial per capita formula.
   Brookline Town Administrator Richard T. Leary said the town
planned to sue before Dukakis made his decision on the formula
because that's the only way an allegedly unfair distribution of
funds can be prevented. Were the town to wait, he said, the checks,
figuratively, would already be in the mail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
