<HEAD>Career Foreign Service Officer Nominated Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Tuesday he will nominate
career foreign service officer James Richard Cheek as ambassador to
the Sudan.
   Cheek, 53, is a former chief of mission and charge d'affaires in
Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. He has been diplomat in residence at Howard
University since 1988.
   Bush also said he will nominate:
   _Jonathan Moore, 56, to be alternate representative to the
United Nations for special political affairs with the rank of
ambassador. He has been the State Department's refugee coordinator
and is a former Harvard politics professor.
   _Ronald J. Sorini for the rank of ambassador during his tenure
as U.S. negotiator on textile matters. Sorini, 34, has been
involved with textile negotiations for the U.S. Trade
Representative since 1983.
   The president also said William P. Albrecht will remain a
commissioner of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. Albrecht,
54, is a former University of Iowa professor of economics and dean
who has been on the CFTC since last year.
