<DOCNO> AP890801-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     08-01 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Tells Legislators that Foreign, Domestic Policies Linked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Tuesday his
foreign policy is inextricably linked with his domestic economic
and political reforms.
   His speech was labeled as the first of planned regular reports
to the Supreme Soviet, or legislature.
   Gorbachev reported on such successes as arms control and his
tumultous welcome in West Germany. The Western public, he said,
views Soviet reform with enthusiasm. He implied that without
continuing reform, foreign relations could chill.
   ``Of course, you will agree that there is an unbreakable
connection between the new foreign policy and the internal
perestroika (reconstruction) of the country,'' Gorbachev said.
``All our activities in the international arena are built on this.''
   Gorbachev also praised the United States, saying it has not
increased its military budget for three years. U.S.-made Pershing
missiles in West Germany have been destroyed, he said, and a
moratorium has been imposed on the production of weapons-grade
plutonium and tritium.
   ``It would be wrong to ignore the fact that the West is meeting
us halfway on disarmament problems,'' Gorbachev said.
</TEXT>
