<DOCNO> AP890801-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Docks     08-01 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Docks,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Calls Off Dock Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leaders on Tuesday called off a 3-week-old
national dock strike that had faltered because more longshoremen
were back on the job than were out on strike.
   About 1,000 returned to work Monday after employers threatened
to fire anyone who stayed out. On Tuesday, employers said 3,727 men
were working, 2,682 remained on strike and 43 of the 60 affected
ports were operating normally.
   The Transport and General Workers' Union called the strike after
the government abolished a guaranteed lifetime employment
arrangement at the 60 ports.
   Members of the union's executive committee voted 18-12 to end
the strike, four days after longshore leaders voted overwhelmingly
to continue and intensify it.
   Ron Todd, secretary-general of the union, said ending the strike
was ``a question of recognizing the realities that are going on
around us.''
   The union said it would continue pressing for reinstatement of
longshoremen who were fired for striking and would bargain for
local agreements to replace the national guaranteed-employment plan.
   Nicholas Finney, director of the National Association of Port
Employers, said: ``This is a profoundly sensible decision which
will save the TGWU's members any further heartache. The industry
can now get on with the task of building a prosperous and
successful industry in partnership, not conflict.''
   Michael Meacher of the opposition Labor Party called the outcome
``proof positive that it is becoming impossible, even with
overwhelming right on your side, to hold a legal strike in
Britain.''
   Curbing the power of unions has been a priority of Margaret
Thatcher, the Conservative Party prime minister.
</TEXT>
