<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-QuayleResidence     08-01 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle Residence,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Moving Toward Remodeling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee on Tuesday approved a
bill omitting federal funds for a refurbishing of Vice President
Quayle's official residence, but panel members said the money could
still be put back.
   Four days ago, the House provided $200,000 to remodel the third
floor of the 1894 Victorian mansion. Since shortly after last
fall's election, the Quayles have said the third floor would have
to be renovated to accomodate the family's three children, but they
have repeatedly said the work would be financed privately.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., chairman of the Appropriations
treasury and postal subcommittee, said his panel omitted the money
from a spending bill because he had not received justification for
the work from the administration.
   ``We will surely take care of their needs,'' DeConcini said.
``Just give us a little plan, even on the back of a napkin or
something.''
   The ranking Republican on the subcommittee, Sen. Pete Domenici
of New Mexico, said he had been told by an aide to Quayle that the
failure to request the funds was an oversight.
   ``That's such a different group of occupants than we've had in
the past,'' Domenici said of the Quayle family.
   The lawmakers indicated they expected the money to be approved
either by the full Appropriations Committee or by the Senate,
perhaps later this week.
   The funds would be part of the $18.4 billion measure for the
Treasury Department, postal programs and related purposes for the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 that the subcommittee approved Tuesday.
   Like the House version, the Senate bill contained a one-year
delay in implementation of Section 89, a portion of the tax code
designed to encourage companies to provide health plans to low-paid
employees. Businesses have complained that complying with the
measure is time-consuming and expensive.
   The three-story mansion at the Naval Observatory grounds on the
``Embassy Row'' section of Massachusetts Avenue in Washington has
been used as official residence for vice presidents since 1975.
When George Bush was vice president, the third floor was used for
storage, Barbara Bush's office, and a maid's bedroom.
   Friends of the Quayles have raised about $200,000 in donations
for the work, according to Denise Balzano, chief of staff to the
vice president's wife, Marilyn.
   Earlier this year, Mrs. Quayle invited members of the House
Appropriations treasury and postal subcommittee to examine the
mansion. Balzano said the invitation was made to keep Congress
informed of the planned work.
   A subcommittee aide visited the mansion and agreed that the work
was needed. The treasury and postal bill approved Friday by the
House included $200,000 for the job.
   ``We didn't plan to put it into this budget,'' Rep. Edward
Roybal, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee, said in an
interview on Monday. ``She called our attention to it.''
   None of the work has been done. Balzano said plans call for the
construction of four bedrooms, a family room, an office for Mrs.
Quayle, three bathrooms and a room for a washer and dryer.
   The first floor of the mansion is used for entertaining, while
the second floor has a master bedroom and a guest room.
   The Quayles' children are Tucker, 15, Benjamin, 12, and Corinne,
10. Currently they sleep elsewhere in the house.
</TEXT>
