<FIRST>r p AM-Barry-Mayor     08-01 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Mayor,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry, Planning Re-Election Bid, Encouraged by Finance Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr. reaffirmed on Tuesday
he plans to run for re-election in 1990, urged potential
contributors not to give money to his rivals, and discounted any
impact Jesse Jackson might have on the race.
   Barry said he was encouraged by recently released campaign
finance reports which he claimed indicated his opponents have not
been raising as much money as they might.
   ``I'm putting everybody on notice: Those who want to give money
to other candidates, don't give it, because they have to save their
money for me,'' said Barry. ``I would have thought with all the
Barry-bashing, they would have more money. That demonstrates they
are waiting for me.''
   Barry scoffed at suggestions contributors may be waiting to give
to Jackson, who is moving here and has refused to rule out a bid
for mayor.
   As for the impact Jackson might have, Barry said: ``Jesse
Jackson's position on the mayor's race is not relevant to my
plans.''
   Jackson had said previously that he would never oppose Barry,
but refused to reaffirm that statement after Barry said he would
run again.
   John Ray, a member of the District of Columbia Council, reported
raising $218,592 from January to July in his bid for the Democratic
nomination, according to records filed with the city's office of
campaign finance. Former Pepco executive Sharon Pratt Dixon has
raised $100,261, while council Chairman David Clarke registered
$48,875.
   Barry said he would file a campaign finance report in January
but offered no other clues on when he will formally create the
fund-raising arm of his campaign, a first step toward officially
entering the race.
   The mayor also said he felt confident that he could raise the
$1.5 million he estimated it will take to win re-election. He said
he already has commitments in excess of $400,000.
