<HEAD>Divers Stand By To Search Capsized Rig; Coast Guard Ends Rescue Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with divers returning to scene; DELETES
outdated material. No pick up.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chantal, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers returned to a capsized oil rig Tuesday
to search for 10 missing crewmen despite 10-foot seas and 43 mph
winds left behind by Hurricane Chantal.
   ``It is not an ideal situation. The seas are still rough.
Visibility is only fair and when those scattered thunderstorms move
through it's very limited,'' said Coast Guard spokesman Lt. Pat
Philbin.
   The self-propelled rig Avco 5 was headed to shore with 14 people
aboard early Monday when it capsized about 20 miles off the
Louisiana coast, near Morgan City, Lifa said.
   The rig, leased from Avis Bourg Co. of Folsom, had left a
Chevron worksite because of the threat of Chantal.
   Three survivors were taken aboard the fishing vessel Spar
Royale, and a fourth was taken by helicopter to Grand Isle.
   Officials had hoped to find survivors who might have found air
pockets in the rig's sealed compartments, but 12-foot seas, 70 mph
wind and heavy rain prevented divers from searching.
   Chantal hit land on the east Texas coast Tuesday morning. It
weakened as it headed inland and was downgraded to a tropical storm
before noon.
   The Coast Guard, which had said it would not resume its search
for the missing men, reconsidered Tuesday and dispatched a plane to
conduct a surface search and a ship to accompany the dive boat, the
Sea Level 21, Philbin said.
   A second drilling rig began listing Monday but all five workers
aboard were removed without injury. That rig, owned by Atlantic &amp;
Pacific Marine Inc. of Houston, was located about 15 miles east of
Grand Isle.
