<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-Fires     08-01 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Fires,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brush Fires Kill Three in Northern Sardinia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLBIA, Sardinia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brush fires raged across northern
Sardinia Tuesday, killing at least three people and forcing the
evacuation of more than a thousand residents of this Italian
island, authorities said.
   Hundreds of firefighters and a dozen helicopters and aircraft
battled the flames that threatened more than 2,500 acres of land in
Sassari province.
   Two charred bodies were found near the village of Bassacutena
and a 12-year-old boy was burned to death in Porto San Paolo, a
seaside resort just south of Olbia.
   Five people were hospitalized in Olbia for burns, including a
42-year-old French woman identified as Anne Richard. She and
another woman were airlifted to Rome for treatment at a burn center.
   Several villages were evacuated, including all 1,200 residents
of the town of Loiri.
   Brush and forest fires are common in the summer in Sardinia,
which has had a severe drought this year. The origin of Tuesday's
fires was not immediately clear, but officials said arson was
suspected.
   Meanwhile, civil defense officials in Rome said six forest fires
were reported in other regions of Italy on Tuesday. No casualties
were reported in those fires.
</TEXT>
