<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARKERSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury deliberated for only
three hours Tuesday before finding four people guilty of plotting
to kill six federal witnesses.
   The U.S. District Court jury also found three of the defendants
guilty of plotting an escape from the Cabell County Jail.
   John P. McCoy, 43, of Slaters Branch, Ky., and Robert Nance, 42,
and Vondia Clary, 35, both of Huntington, were found guilty of one
count of conspiracy to kill a federal witness, four counts of
attempting to kill witnesses, one count of conspiracy to escape
from federal custody, among other charges.
   McCoy's son, Kennis ``Kip'' McCoy, 22, of Pike County, Ky., was
found guilty of all the charges except the escape charge and one of
the attempted murder charges.
   ``We're just glad we're finished with all the prosecutions of
John P. McCoy,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Ben Bryant.
   ``What the evidence in these various prosecutions has
demonstrated, and what's remarkable, is the way John P. McCoy
managed to use other people and recruit them into his criminal
schemes, and how many other people have become involved and
subsequently prosecuted and convicted, including his young son.''
   At the time of the plots in March, April and May, John McCoy
faced federal bank robbery, counterfeiting and murder charges.
Nance and Clary had been charged with distributing cocaine.
   Attorneys for three of the defendants declined to comment after
the verdict.
   Joseph Martorella, attorney for Kip McCoy, said he would file a
complaint alleging prosecutorial misconduct. Martorella said
prosecutors brought a witness in at the last minute without
informing him.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Haden II revoked bond for Clary and
Kip McCoy after their convictions. Nance and John McCoy already
were being held without bond.
   In closing arguments earlier Tuesday, defense attorneys ripped
prosecutors' use of a career criminal as star witness. Bryant,
however, called the defendants ``cutthroats'' who would do anything
to escape prosecution.
   ``These are desperate people, each and every one of them,''
Bryant said. ``They were in a desperate situation and they took
desperate actions.''
   In their closing arguments, all four defense attorneys ridiculed
the prosecution's chief witness, Willie Cremeans of Huntington.
   Cremeans, allegedly the triggerman in the would-be killings,
cooperated with authorities and secretly tape recorded several
telephone and personal conversations with the defendants. In
return, prosecutors promised to help Cremeans on a robbery charge.
   ``Willie Cremeans is going to make up any story that will keep
him out of jail,'' said Wright.
   ``Willie Cremeans was a puppet,'' said Flora. ``Willie Cremeans
is the one constant factor here. Willie Cremeans don't want to go
back to prison.''
   Bryant said that if Cremeans had not cooperated with
authorities, several people would be dead.
   ``Thank heavens for Willie Cremeans,'' Bryant said. ``As much as
they've dumped on him in this case, he did the right thing for the
first time in his life.''
   The McCoys contended that they had asked Cremeans to help
investigate the charges against John McCoy. Nance said he plotted
with Cremeans to rob several people, not to kill them. Clary said
she sold an AR-15 semiautomatic assault rifle to Cremeans but
didn't know what he planned to do with it.
   Bryant called the defenses crazy.
   ``If ever in modern times there is a set of more clear facts,
colder facts presented to a jury in this state, I hope I don't hear
it,'' said Bryant's co-prosecutor, Paul Billups.
   Sentencing for Nance, Clary and Kip McCoy was scheduled for Oct.
10 in Huntington. John McCoy will be sentenced Aug. 14, the same
day he is scheduled to be sentenced on earlier convictions of bank
robbery and killing a federal witness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
