<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Pensions,0120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Raise Old-Age Pensions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet legislature on Tuesday raised the
minimum old-age pension to the equivalent of $112 monthly,
television news reported.
   Officials previously said many elderly Soviets received pensions
as low as $64 a month.
   The official Tass news agency said 30 million people will be
helped by the increases, including disabled workers and World War
II veterans.
   The higher payments will begin Oct. 1. The first months of the
increase will be financed by a $2 billion donation from the
Communist Party, its youth organization, trade unions and the state
peace fund.
   Tass said social insurance taxes subsequently will raise an
unspecified amount to cover the increases.
