<FIRST>r a AM-DC-10Crash-Engine     08-01 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Crash-Engine,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crashed Jet's Engine Returns to Manufacturer for Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY MAY-LEE CHAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What remains of the jet engine that is
believed have exploded and led to the crash of a DC-10 in Sioux
City was shipped Tuesday to the plant where the engine was
manufactured, investigators said.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators at the
Evendale, Ohio, General Electric plant plan to take the engine
apart and try to determine the sequence of events that led up to
the July 19 crash of United Airlines Flight 232, in which 111
people died.
   NTSB spokesman Alan Pollock said the disassembly process would
begin sometime in the next couple weeks.
   The tail-mounted No. 2 engine apparently exploded and flying
pieces severed all three of the airliner's hydraulic systems, which
allow pilots to control the aircraft's altitude and direction.
Without them, the pilot has little control over the airplane.
   Investigators want to determine if something within the engine
malfunctioned or if something entered it from outside, Pollock said.
   The flight crew said the jet lost all of its hydraulic fluid
shortly after the No. 2 engine failed. They struggled to guide the
plane to the Sioux City airport, but one wing dipped and touched
the ground just short of the runway and the jet cartwheeled,
breaking up and bursting into flames.
   The investigation at the cras site at Sioux Gateway Airport was
nearly complete, Pollock said.
   ``The field phase of the investigation will wind down by the end
of the week and disband,'' he said.
   He said one NTSB investigator would remain in Sioux City to
oversee the search for missing engine parts, particularly a fan
assembly from the No. 2 engine that is thought to have fallen in
corn and soybean fields.
   Some pieces of the jet had been recovered near Alta, about 60
miles east of Sioux City.
   Investigators also have reconstructed part of the jet's tail
section and were examining it to determine how pieces of the engine
penetrated the tail and hydraulic lines, Pollock said.
   Pollock said 12 NTSB teams were involved in the investigation.
</TEXT>
