<FIRST>r w AM-US-ChineseStudent     08-01 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Chinese Student,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0778 to include cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fugitive Leader Lionized in Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive leader of China's democracy
movement urged Congress on Tuesday to allow Chinese students to
remain in the United States as long as they feel endangered by
returning home.
   Wu'er Kaixi also told admiring members of the Congressional
Human Rights Caucus that ``if China persists in its brutal policy
it is a government which is neither stable nor has a future.''
   He said he supports economic sanctions and diplomatic isolation
against China that do not sacrifice U.S. interests ``nor the
sentiments of the Chinese people.''
   The 21-year-old Beijing Normal University student went
underground and fled China in the wake of the June 3-4 crackdown in
Beijing's Tiananmen Square that left hundreds, perhaps thousands,
dead. He has been named by China as one of the fugitives most
wanted as a leader of the pro-democracy movement.
   Guarded by two Capitol Police officers and speaking Mandarin
through an interpreter, he was treated as something of a hero by
members of the caucus.
   ``God bless you ... You've inspired the entire world,'' Rep.
Charles Bennett, D-Fla., told him.
   Wu'er is on a four-day visit to Washington that is to include
meetings with congressmen, unidentified White House officials and
appearances at seminars and a demonstration outside the Chinese
Embassy.
   He is accompanied by Liu Yan, a leader of hunger strikers in
Tiananmen Square and Shen Tong, a participant with Wuer Kaixi in a
dialogue with Chinese Premier Li Peng before the army's violent
crackdown.
   Wu'er said China has already arrested 120,000 pro-democracy
students in its attempt to stamp out the movement.
   ``One of the greatest worries'' of the more than 40,000 Chinese
studying in the United States is that on return they will be
``subjected to all sorts of harm'' in reprisal for support of the
democracy movement, he said.
   Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., co-chairman of the caucus, told him
Congress would do ``everything possible'' to enable Chinese
students to remain in the United States so long as they feel
endangered in their homeland.
   Legislation to allow the students to remain after their visas
expire passed the House on Monday, but has yet to pass the Senate.
</TEXT>
