<FIRST>r a AM-PersonalityStabbed     08-01 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Personality Stabbed,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Personality Stabbed To Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local television personality was found stabbed
to death at the home of a 35-year-old woman, who died of stab
wounds as she was being driven to a hospital, police said Tuesday.
   Larry Sturholm, 46, was a feature reporter for KIRO Television.
He was featured in ``Larry at Large'' reports, which were
light-hearted accounts of life as seen by Sturholm.
   Sturholm had resigned effective Monday and told friends he
intended to pursue interests in writing and video production, said
Kathryn Rich, assistant news director for KIRO.
   A third man injured in the Monday evening incident was admitted
to Harborview Medical Center and was in satisfactory condition.
Police and hospital officials declined to identify the man, who is
48.
   The injured man was being treated for stab wounds to the neck
and was under police guard, said King County police spokesman Cecil
Ray.
   The dead woman was identified as Debra Sweiger of Issaquah, said
King County Medical Investigator Vaughn Van Zant.
   A taped police message about the incident said it was believed
to be the result of a domestic disturbance. Police were
investigating the relationships among the three people.
   Ray said Sweiger had called a female business associate for help
during the stabbing. The associate sent her husband to Sweiger's
house and, when he arrived, Sweiger was outside and a male figure
was moving inside, Ray said.
   Seeing Sweiger's wounds, the man put her in his car and began
driving toward a hospital, Ray said. The man stopped at a house
along the way to call for help and Sweiger died at the residence,
Ray said.
   Officers went to her home and found the dead body of Sturholm
and the injured man in separate rooms.
   KIRO Senior Vice President Al Mladenich thought Sturholm may
have had a business relationship with Steiger, but said the station
was also attempting to piece together what happened.
   ``We're all shocked and saddened,'' Rich said. ``We feel a
tremendous loss. Everyone who worked with him just thought he was
wonderful.''
