<FIRST>r a AM-RockyFlats     08-01 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Impaneled to Hear Government's Case on Nuclear Weapons
Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special grand jury was impaneled Tuesday to hear
numerous allegations of safety violations at the Rocky Flats
nuclear weapons plant, including the illegal dumping of hazardous
wastes.
   Chief U.S. District Judge Sherman G. Finesilver told the 23
grand jurors their only task during the 18-month term would be ``to
determine what criminal acts, if any, were committed at Rocky Flats
nuclear weapons plant.''
   The plant, which manufactures plutonium detonators for nuclear
weapons, is located 16 miles northwest of Denver.
   About 75 FBI agents and special officers from the Environmental
Protection Agency raided the plant on June 6 after a search warrant
was issued on an affidavit containing more than 100 pages of
allegations.
   The affidavit accused Rocky Flats officials and employees of
illegally dumping hazardous wastes into two streams that flow into
water supplies serving four Denver suburbs, illegally operating an
incinerator in a building closed by Department of Energy
inspectors, and altering documents to cover up those alleged
activities.
   Government agents have recovered boxes of documents and numerous
samples of soil and other material at the plant, operated for the
Department of Energy by Rockwell International.
   Since the raid, Gov. Roy Romer and DOE officials reached an
agreement allowing the Colorado Health Department to monitor the
plant more closely than before.
   Finesilver told jurors they had the option to return indictments
or a written report. Twelve jurors must reach agreement on an
indictment before one can be issued, he said.
   Although prosecutors will present the case, ``You are not a
rubber stamp for activities of the U.S. attorney,'' Finesilver
said. ``You must exercise your own, individual judgment.''
   Finesilver also told them they could expect to work about one
week each month until the investigation is concluded.
   Working with U.S. Attorney Mike Norton on the case are Assistant
U.S. Attorney Ken Fimberg of Denver and Peter Murtha, a special
prosecutor in the environmental crime section of the Justice
Department in Washington.
</TEXT>
