<DOCNO> AP890801-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-Confidentiality     08-01 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Confidentiality,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA Panel Recommends Privacy for AIDS Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Bar Association panel recommended
Tuesday that public health officials rigorously protect the privacy
of AIDS patients, saying confidentiality ``is critical to the
success'' of efforts to stop the spread of the deadly disease.
   The organizations's AIDS coordinating committee said it's
18-month study found discrimination persists against people who
have AIDS or have been exposed to the human immunodeficiency virus
that is believed to cause the disease.
   The panel said the lack of laws ensuring confidentiality is
``keeping people who believe that they may have been exposed to the
virus from seeking testing and counseling services.''
   ``Confidentiality protections encourage individuals to come
forward for voluntary testing, counseling and research,'' the
committee said.
   The committee recommended federal, state and local laws barring
discrimination against those who suffer from AIDS, both to help
treat the victims and to help advance research for a cure.
   ``Since the AIDS epidemic began, people with AIDS and HIV
infection have experienced discrimination in ... employment,
housing, public accomodations and government services,'' the report
said.
   It added, ``discrimination impairs the country's ability to
limit the spread of the HIV virus by interfering with educational
testing, counseling and health care efforts.''
   Those who oppose confidentiality for AIDS patients argue people
may contract the contagious disease through unwitting contact with
AIDS victims. The debate has been the sharpest in public schools,
where residents of some communities have protested the presence in
the classroom of children who have contracted AIDS or been exposed
to HIV.
   The ABA report said that because AIDS is not spread through
casual contact, students who have been exposed ``should not be
separated'' from classmates, ``except in the rare instance when a
particular child presents a substantial risk of transmitting the
virus in a school setting.''
   The committee also recommended that its members provide more
free legal aid to people infected with HIV.
   The conclusions, which were released in a statement by the ABA,
are to be presented to the organization's annual meeting next week
in Honolulu, where members will decide whether to make the
recommendations formally on behalf of the entire association.
   AIDS is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune
system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and
infections. The incurable condition is believed caused by HIV and
is spread through contact with blood or with semen from infected
persons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
