<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Britain     08-01 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Britain,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Argentina Lifts Restrictions On British Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina lifted restrictions on
British imports Tuesday in what the foreign minister called a
gesture toward better relations between the two countries.
   The government also removed barriers to financing Argentine
exports to Britain.
   Trade with Britain will be treated in the same way as trade with
any other country, Foreign Minister Domingo Cavallo said.
   ``This is a gesture in the direction that President Carlos Menem
has signaled,'' Cavallo said.
   Diplomatic relations were severed in April 1982, when Argentina
invaded and occupied the Falkland Islands, a British colony since
1833. British forces recaptured the islands off Argentina's
southern coast in a 74-day war.
   Argentines call the islands the Malvinas and claim they
inherited them in 1810 after declaringindependence from Spain.
   Argentina never formally declared an end to hostilities. It has
refused to allow British planes or ships to use Argentine ports, or
to allow British companies to bid on Argentine public projects.
   Britain says it wants to normalize trade relations with
Argentina, negotiate a fishing agreement, re-establish air links
and reduce tension.
   Tuesday's trade development will be conveyed to Britain by the
Brazilian Embassy in London, Argentina's diplomatic representative
there.
   Menem said after taking office on July 8 that he wants to
normalize relations with Britain. Last month, Menem said Argentina
would formally declare an end to hostilities if Britain ended its
150-mile, militarily enforced ``protection zone'' around the
islands.
   ``If Mrs. Thatcher (British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher)
doesn't insist on the issue of sovereignty, we won't, either,''
Menem said shortly after taking office.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
