<FIRST>r a AM-SlainLawmaker     08-01 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Slain Lawmaker,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife of Slain Lawmaker Confesses Then Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estranged wife of a state lawmaker went to
police Tuesday and confessed to beating him to death with a hammer,
then killed herself in the police station's bathroom, authorities
said.
   The body of Rep. Roland Kotani, 35, was discovered in his rented
Honolulu duplex on Friday.
   The Honolulu Medical Examiner's Office said Kotani had been
struck over the head with a blunt object.
   Grace Sadako Imura-Kotani went to police Monday night to be
interviewed about her husband's death, but was not arrested, said
Maj. Robert Au of the police Criminal Investigation Division.
   ``During the interview she confessed to the murder of
Representative Kotani,'' Au said. ``She asked to use the restroom
and was directed to the women's room ... moments later, she was
dead of a self-inflicted gunshot wound.''
   Au said the slaying stemmed from a domestic dispute. The Kotanis
were married in 1979 and have a 3-year-old daughter, Mariko. They
separated in February.
   Kotani, a Democrat, was an assistant majority floor leader in
the state House of Representatives.
   He was appointed to the House in 1987 by Gov. John Waihee to
fill a vacancy created when Eloise Tungpalan was appointed to the
state Senate. He was elected in his own right last year, running
unopposed.
   Kotani went to the House after serving as an assistant to the
governor and lieutenant governor.
