<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-01 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Opposition Leader Held For Questioning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Dae-jung, head of South Korea's
leading opposition party, was detained on a court warrant Wednesday
for questioning in connection with a party lawmaker's illegal trip
to communist North Korea.
   Kim and senior party National Assemblyman Moon Tong-hwan were
taken from the headquarters of the Party for Peace and Democracy by
four agents of the the Agency for National Security Planning early
Wednesday.
   The warrant was issued last Thursday after Kim and Moon failed
to comply voluntarily to three summons issued by the agency to
answer questions about a trip north by Suh Kyung-won, 52, a party
lawmaker in jail on charges of espionage.
   Kim and Moon maintained they had nothing to add to the
investigation and charged the government with harasssment and
trying to destroy their party. Suh was expelled from the party
after his trip became public.
   Kim's aides said four agents came to party headquarters and
presented detention orders to Kim and Moon before taking them away.
The aides said the two, notified late Tuesday of the action, did
not resist.
   More than 100 lawmakers and party supporters gathered around Kim
shouting slogans as he and Moon were hustled into two cars.
   ``Disband the NSP!'' they shouted, fists jabbing the air. Kim
smiled and waved as he left in his private car, followed by agents
in other cars.
   Kim and Moon were taken to a downtown police station for
questioning, which party officials said was expected to last until
late Wednesday. The agency has occasionally borrowed interrogation
rooms in the Chungbu Police Station.
   Party spokesman Lee Sang-soo said ``the national security
agency's scheme to suppress and destroy the party has reached the
extreme'' with Kim's detention.
   The agency said it wanted to question Kim and Moon about Suh's
trip to visit North Korean leader Kim Il Sung in August 1988. It
said it wanted to know details of how Suh joined their party and
how he happened to run for the National Assembly on the party's
ticket.
   Suh turned himself into authorities June 25 and was formally
arrested three days later on charges of violating national security
laws for an unauthorized visit to a hostile, communist nation.
Party leaders said they encouraged Suh to turn himself in after the
party belatedly heard about the trip.
   Dozens of people have been questioned and half a dozen people
charged in connection with the Suh case.
</TEXT>
