<FIRST>u a AM-FiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0670 08-01 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildfires Char Timber, Range Land in Four States</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with fires in British Columbia,
small Idaho town evacuated. Picks up 10th graf, pvs, `Yellow Pine...';
SUBS last graf to UPDATE with another Southern California fire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cooler weather allowed firefighters to advance Tuesday on forest
blazes threatening three tiny Idaho towns, and soldiers in
Washington state began hasty training to join the battle against
wildfires in four Western states.
   Fire crews have ``just been holding their own so the lower
temperatures are really going to help things out,'' Boise National
Forest spokeswoman Lynette Davis said.
   But the weather was a mixed blessing. Fire bosses who monitored
up to 2,000 lightning strikes an hour in the fire areas early
Tuesday worried that continued strikes predicted overnight could
ignite a new round of blazes like those that have been burning
since the middle of last week.
   Since July 26, more that 175,000 acres of forest, brush and
grassland have burned in Idaho, California, Washington and Oregon,
according to the Boise Interagency Fire Center, the federal
wildfire command post.
   A blaze south of Kelowna, British Columbia, about 50 miles north
of the Washington border, had blackened more than 1,400 acres as it
burned out of control Tuesday. It was among more than 100 new fires
that broke out in British Columbia in a 24-hour period.
   Red-flag warnings for ``dry lightning'' _ strikes unaccompanied
by quenching rain _ were issued for Tuesday in northeast Oregon,
Idaho and western Montana, said fire center spokeswoman Debbie
Shivers.
   The Boise center was directing 20,000 firefighters Tuesday, and
1,200 troops at Ft. Lewis, Wash., began a crash course on using
hand and power tools to cut containment lines around wilderness
blazes. They were to begin heading for the fire lines as early as
Wednesday, said Capt. Martin Eckert, spokesman at Ft. Lewis.
   In Idaho, where 76,000 acres have been blackened, smoke from
fires miles away hung over Boise but no warnings were issued to
stay indoors.
   Hundreds of reinforcements, including National Guard troops and
crews from out of state, were ferried to help crews on the most
critical fire lines in the Payette and Boise national forests.
   Attacks were concentrated south of the small mining town of
Warren, 120 miles north of Boise, which was threatened by a
1,000-acre Whangdoodle Fire, and around Idaho City, a small town 25
miles northeast of Boise.
   Fire bosses began to evacuate Warren on Tuesday, displacing 16
of the town's 36 residents. The evacuees went to McCall, 30 miles
southwest, and the rest were told to be ready to move at a moment's
notice, officials said.
   Yellow Pine, a hamlet of perhaps two dozen permanent residents
near Warren, was cut off by fires burning across both roads into
town, but the settlement wasn't in immediate danger, authorities
said.
   Losses in Lowman, a town of 15 residents largely leveled over
the weekend, were estimated by the state Disaster Services Bureau
Tuesday at $10.3 million.
   Helicopters crisscrossed the Hell's Canyon area near the
Idaho-Oregon border looking for hikers who might be endangered by
the fires. Rangers ferried in by chopper brought maps to direct
about 40 hikers to the safest routes out of the backcountry.
   In Eastern Oregon, where 80,000 acres have burned, the cooler
weather helped slow one big blaze.
   Crews made progress cutting lines around a 10,300-acre fire near
the town of John Day, but firefighters working on blazes around
Baker and Enterprise made little headway.
   ``They'll work like mad today with fairly good condiions to make
as much progress as possible,'' said Suzanne Zachry, spokeswoman
for the Wallowa-Whitman National Forest near Baker. ``They've still
got a lot of work to do.''
   A fast-moving fire southwest of Unity doubled in size overnight,
and authorities evacuated two campgrounds on the south fork of
Burnt River.
   In Washington state, an 850-acre fire burning in the Cascade
range near the Canadian border was 84 percent contained Tuesday,
said Greg Thayer of the U.S. Forest Service.
   In Montana, erratic winds and temperatures in the 100s pushed a
fire in the Custer National Forest to more than 1,200 acres
Tuesday, said Jerry Chapman of the Bureau of Land Management. It
was the largest of several fires burning uncontrolled in the state.
   In California's Sierra Nevada foothills, firefighters on Tuesday
contained a blaze that burned 11,700 acres of brush and grassland
and destroyed seven homes. Arson was blamed for that and a
2,000-acre fire 25 miles away at Balch Camp, but there were no
arrests. Another fire roared through the steep canyons of the
Cleveland National Forest, about 90 miles southeast of Los Angeles,
and blackened 7,000 acres, officals said.
</TEXT>
