<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     08-01 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador-Designate to South Africa Says No New Sanctions Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's choice to be ambassador to
South Africa told a Senate committee Tuesday no new sanctions
against South Africa are needed.
   The nominee, career diplomat William Lacy Swing, appeared before
the Foreign relations Committee at the same time as House members
concerned about South Africa met to map strategy for possible
additional sanctions aimed at pressing the South African government
to dismantle its race policies.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill, in the committee chair, said the
committee hoped to act on the nomination by Friday.
   After the meeting of the House group, a congressional source who
spoke on condition that he not be identified said the group was
considering two lines of action: Further U.S. sanctions, or
cooperation with sanctions under the aegis of the United Nations as
proposed by Simon.
   Swing, formerly ambassador to Liberia, told the committee, ``Our
position is that we do not need further sanctions.''
   Asked about United Nations sanctions, he said, ``Were we to be
involved in mandatory U.N. sanctions, clearly we risk the
possibility that we would be hostage to a veto by someone who
didn't share (our) particular assessment of the situation on the
ground in South Africa.''
   At a House Banking international development subcommittee
meeting earlier, a Bush administration spokesman urged that South
Africa get more time to repay at least $8 billion of dollars of
foreign debt that falls due next June. Other witnesses urged that
no delay be allowed unless South African policies are changed.
   ``Some $2.6 billion in unpaid principal remained outstanding to
U.S. financial institutions at the end of March 1989,'' said R.
Richard Newcomb, director of the U.S. Treasurty's Office of Foreign
Aassets Control.
   ``Were this amount to be simply defaulted on by the South
African borrowers because U.S. lending institutions were prevented
by Congress from participating in further reschedulings, the
benefit to the South African economy is evident.''
</TEXT>
