<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Unemployment     08-01 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Unemployment,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unemployment Drops to Lowest Level in Seven Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate in
June fell to 2.2 percent, the lowest level in seven years, the
government announced Tuesday.
   The Statistics Bureau of the prime minister's office said the
number of jobholders grew by 1.33 million from a year earlier, the
largest gain in more than 15 years. It brought the total number of
employed to 62.39 million.
   It said there were 1.34 million Japanese without work in the
month, a decrease of 100,000 from a year earlier.
   In May, the unemployment rate was 2.4 percent.
   Japan's economy has continued to expand robustly and rising
domestic demand has spurred many manufacturers to boost production.
   Figures released by the Labor Ministry on Tuesday indicated
there were 134 job offers for every 100 people looking for work.
   Japan's jobless rate would be higher if it were calculated by
U.S. or European methods.
   In Japan, members of the armed forces and people working more
than one hour in the last week of the month _ when data are
tabulated _ are counted as employed. In the United States, military
personnel traditionally are not considered part of the labor force
and those working less than 15 hours a week are considered
unemployed.
   Japan has used its current method to calculate unemployment
since 1953.
</TEXT>
