<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0780 08-01 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostage Developments at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf in `U.S. Reaction' section to UPDATE with message
to Iran.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tuesday's hostage developments at a glance:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEADLINES AND DENIALS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The group holding American hostage Joseph Cicippio said it had
extended by 48 hours the deadline for his ``execution.'' The
Revolutionary Justice Organization issued a statement saying the
deadline of 6 p.m. Tuesday (11 a.m. EDT) was extended due to
``friendly appeals and sincere behests as well as some special
factors and the moving plea by Cicippio's wife.''
   The group had said Monday that Cicippio would be killed unless
Israel freed captured Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid. The statement issued
Tuesday said there would be no further postponement of the deadline.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, which on Monday said
it had hanged U.S. Lt. Col. William R. Higgins in retaliation for
Obeid's abduction, denied Tuesday that it had made telephone calls
threatening to kill Anglican church envoy Terry Waite, who
disappeared in January 1987.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOSTAGE RELATIVES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Cicippio's wife, Ilham, made her plea during a news conference
in Beirut. She urged her husband's kidnappers to give him a chance
``to prove to you that he is innocent of all guilt.'' Her husband,
who converted to Islam in 1985, was kidnapped Sept. 12, 1986, while
working for the American University in Beirut.
   In Cicippio's home town of Norristown, Pa., his relatives
reacted with caution to his two-day reprieve, and said they hoped
his captors would free him.
   In Washington, Higgins' wife, Robin, viewed the videotape of the
purported execution of her husband, and said it was impossible to
make a definite determination of whether he was dead or alive. She
called on the captors to ``give us proof.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. REACTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   President Bush met for a second day with senior advisers. One
administration source said military action was possible, but
another official said a hostage rescue or a military strike were
``not attractive options.''
   Officials said the United States sent a strongly worded message
to Iran on behalf of the hostages. The administration also appealed
to Saudi Arabia and other Arab governments as well as the Soviet
Union for help in winning the release of all American captives in
Lebanon. Bush telephoned the Pope and the prime minister of Turkey,
and a spokesman said Bush planned to ``talk to a lot of people,
involve a lot of people'' to help the hostages.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ISRAEL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Israel insisted it would not free Obeid despite the reported
killing of Higgins and the threats against other hostages. But
officials said Israel remained willing to exchange Obeid and other
Lebanese Shiite prisoners for Israeli soldiers and Western
hostages. The radical Shiite group Hezbollah, of which Obeid is a
spiritual leader, rejected the deal.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir expressed ``deep sorrow'' over
Higgins' reported death. A Foreign Ministry spokesman called on
``the American people not to allow this outrage to drive a wedge
between the United States and Israel.'' In Washington, debate
continued on Capitol Hill about the wisdom of the Israeli decision
to kidnap Obeid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
