<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-CandidodeCarvalho     08-01 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Candido de Carvalho,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilian Novelist Jose Candido de Carvalho Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Candido de Carvalho, author
of one of Brazil's top-selling novels and a member of the Brazilian
Academy of Letters, died of heart failure Tuesday. He was 74.
   Candido de Carvalho, who recently suffered from respiratory
problems, died at a hospital in neighboring Niteroi.
   The author was best known for his novel ``The Colonel and the
Werewolf,'' which was first published in 1964.
   It was reprinted in four editions and translated into many
languages. It also was made into a feature-length movie in Brazil.
   Born in the city of Campos on Aug. 15, 1914, Candido de Carvalho
studied law and later became a journalist and writer.
   In 1939 he finished his first novel, ``Look to the Sky,
Frederico.''
   After publishing ``The Colonel and the Werewolf,'' Candido de
Carvalho was voted into the Brazilian Pen Club. In 1974 he was
elected to the Brazilian Academy of Letters.
   Burial services are scheduled for Wednesday in Rio.
</TEXT>
