<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2350EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     08-01 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Topple Power Pylons, Attack on Refinery Thwarted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels blew up eight more power
pylons, making a total of 30 destroyed since last week and further
reducing service in Lima and other coastal and highland cities,
electric company officials said Tuesday.
   Last Wednesday rebels toppled 22 towers carrying electricity
from Peru's main hydroelectric facility high in the Andes mountains
to coastal cities, cutting power usage by 40 percent. The latest
attacks occurred Monday night.
   Jose Acevedo, spokesman for the state-owned ElectroPeru company,
said 200 workers aided by air force helicopters and personnel were
working to re-establish service.
   Police reported Tuesday that six guerrillas were captured and 29
escaped during a planned attack Sunday on La Pampilla oil refinery
10 miles north of Lima. They said the rebels apparently planned to
blow up oil tanks but security police spotted the guerrillas on a
nearby hill and police and marines were sent in by helicopter.
   After a brief gunfire exchange police seized six guerrillas and
identified them as members of the Maoist Shining Path movement,
officials reported.
   The Shining Path has been waging an insurgency since 1980. The
government says more than 15,000 people have perished in the
fighting.
   The pylon attacks are part of the rebels' strategy of isolating
Lima from the rest of Peru. Guerrills also have blown up railroad
tracks and attacked highways and bridges between the capital and
the agriculture and mining areas in the Andes mountains to the east.
   Power rationing has caused shortages of perishable food,
gasoline and potable water in Lima.
</TEXT>
