<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2300EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe     08-01 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twenty People Accounted for Most Renovation Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty people, mostly former officials or
prominent Republicans, were able to snag about a fifth of the
federal funds intended to renovate existing housing for the poor,
according to a report prepared for a Senate committee looking into
the scandals at the Housing and Urban Development Department.
   The 20 were paid more than $5.7 million in consultant fees by
developers who hired them to chase HUD grants, said the study
prepared by the agency's inspector general, Paul Adams.
   Adams' work, prepared at the request of Senate Banking Committee
Chairman Donald Riegle Jr., D-Mich., was to be presented at a
committee hearing on Wednesday. A copy was obtained in advance by
The Associated Press.
   While Adams has reported before on the use of consultants in
obtaining funds from HUD, and many names involved have been made
public previously, the current study is the first attempt to
determine the extent and expense of the practice.
   Of projects using consultants, 45 were put in states _ notably,
Colorado, Oklahoma, Nevada and Wyoming _ which would not have
qualified for the funds if HUD's eligibility formulas had been
used, the report said.
   Since October 1983, 51 projects with 7,268 apartments used
consultants, the report found. That accounts for about 20 percent
of all HUD's work in this area during that time.
   Joseph Strauss, a former assistant to then-HUD Secretary Samuel
Pierce Jr., made nearly $1.7 million _ the most of all the
consultants found by Adams' inquiry.
   Others earning high fees included former Interior Secretary
James Watt, who got $300,000; former HUD Secretary and now U.S.
Trade Representative Carla Hills, who received $138,445; and Paul
Manafort, a lobbyist and Republican political strategist, who got
$442,000.
   Because of the publicity about HUD, Adams said, five developers
reported not paying consultants' bills in full.
   One of those consultants was Fred Bush, ambassador-designate to
Luxembourg, who has had $45,000 in payments withheld since April.
Bush, who is no relation to the president but was the chief
fund-raiser for his 1988 campaign for the White House, was paid
$215,000 to help land HUD funds for developers who hired him.
   A related study by the General Accounting Office, prepared by
John M. Ols Jr., said developers were willing to pay high fees to
the consultants because the structure and oversight of the HUD
programs made them virtually no-lose propositions.
   ``In this manner developers were able to realize substantial
gains on their limited investments while undertaking very little
risk,'' Ols wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
