<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SenileMobster     08-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senile Mobster,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Drops Contempt Charges Against Bonanno Because of Senility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has dropped a criminal contempt
charge against Joseph Bonanno because the 85-year-old reputed
ex-mob boss was found to be senile, according to court papers filed
Tuesday.
   The charge stemmed from Bonanno's refusal to testify about the
ruling commission of organized crime in a federal case against
eight men accused of participating in commission rackets. All were
convicted at U.S. District Court in Manhattan in 1986.
   Bonanno served 14 months for civil contempt rather than testify.
Federal prosecutors brought the criminal contempt charge after the
trial ended.
   Bonanno described the commission's formation in his 1983
memoirs, ``A Man of Honor,'' and prosecutors at the commission
trial sought his testimony to help them establish the commission's
existence. He claimed he was too sick to testify.
   Bonanno, a resident of Tuscon, Ariz., was released Oct. 31,
1986, from federal prison in Springfield, Mo., when the government
rested its case in the commission trial and withdrew its subpoena
for his testimony.
   The criminal indictment, brought in November 1986, charged that
he ``willfully disobeyed the court's order to testify'' at a
deposition in Tuscon.
   U.S. District Judge Miriam Goldman Cedarbaum signed an order
dismissing the criminal charge after prosecutors said in court
papers that two psychiatrists concluded Bonanno suffers from
``senile dementia.''
   Bonanno's book said the commission was established in New York
in 1937 to keep peace among the five Cosa Nostra families operating
in the city. He said he retired in the 1960s.
</TEXT>
