<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Iraq-DesertFarming Adv08   08-01 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Desert Farming, Adv 08,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tue AMs, Aug. 8 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laid-Off Agronomists Successfully Farm Iraq's Desert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARBALA, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Abbass Hamadi and three co-workers
lost their jobs as government agronomists, they went off and did
something that could help Iraq for years to come. They farmed the
desert.
   ``This land is virgin, not barren,'' Hamadi said on his desert
farm where he grows high quality vegetables and fruit. ``It only
needs patience and it will yield.''
   The project got going two years ago, when the state-run poultry
unit where he worked was sold off under a government privatization
program and he and his three friends were laid off.
   He decided to fulfil a long-held dream of acquiring his own farm
and putting his agricultural skills to work. He and the others
leased land in the desert west of this Shiite Moslem holy city
about 65 miles south of Baghdad, Iraq's capital.
   They settled for parcels of desert west of the Euphrates River
because they could not afford to lease productive farmland in more
fertile areas.
   ``I never wavered when they offered me a plot in the desert,''
Hamadi said.
   Using fertilizers liberally to make the sandy, gypsum-filled
soil more productive, the desert farmers have been especially
successful in growing tomatoes, cucumbers, watermelons and potatoes.
   Desert farming had long been considered impractical because of
Iraq's searing summer temperatures, poor soil, the high cost of
transporting produce and the lack of surface water for irrigation.
   Hamadi said his biggest problem in trying to develop the 123
acres he leased from the government was finding water.
   He and his colleagues dug wells, going down as much as 100 feet
to reach an underground reservoir.
   It is one of many deep below the arid surface, fed by
underground channels that carry rainwater from the Najd plateau in
northern Saudi Arabia to the west.
   Now more than 140 farmers are planting about 17,300 acres of
land outside Karbala and a thriving settlement has grown up at the
edge of the desert.
   Hassoun Saleh, who heads the province's agricultural corps, said
the government is trying to encourage farmers to exploit the desert
by providing equipment for digging wells, sprinklers for
irrigation, fertilizers and seeds.
   ``When the farmers need help, we give them scientific
instructions on how to cultivate desert land,'' Saleh said. ``We
prepared all the facilities for making this project a success.''
   United Nations figures indicate that Iraq has more than 13.34
million acres of cultivable land out of a total area of 112.43
million acres.
   With extensive irrigation that could rise to 59.3 million acres,
government experts say.
   But only about 7.4 million acres are now being farmed.
   The irrigation systems used in the central plains north of
Baghdad are thousands of years old.
   Despite heavy government outlays on irrigation projects, the
amount of cropland varies considerably from year to year according
to the rainfall.
   Iraq, which is $60 billion to $70 billion in debt after an
8-year war with Iran, relies heavily on food imports that cost
close to $3 billion a year.
   The United States sells Iraq food valued at more than $1 billion
a year, mostly wheat, rice, corn, vegetable oil, livestock and
dairy produce.
   Australia and the 12-nation European Economic Community also
export farm produce to Iraq, and Cuba provides sugar.
   A decade ago, Iraq had ambitious plans to become self-sufficient
in food production during the 1990s. But officials now say that
productivity on farms has declined because of a labor shortage and
a need for more mechanization.
   About one-third of Iraq's work force are farmers, and
agriculture contributes 20 percent of the country's total output of
goods and services.
   Mendi Sagher, another agronomist who joined the desert project
in 1987, said he believes its success will encourage people to
start desert farming in other regions.
   ``I'm certain many others will follow our example. ... But it
does depend on the kind of facilities provided for the desert
farmers,'' he said.
   Sagher, who built his family a home on his desert farm, said his
tomato harvest this year matched top production levels in the
country's fertile zones.
   He added it should be even higher next year as the soil quality
on his plot improves.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, Aug. 8</NOTE>
