<FIRST>r f PM-HousingAffordability     08-01 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Affordability,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affordable Housing Declines, According to Realtors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An index measuring the ability of the typical
American family to buy a home fell in June to its lowest level in
three years, reflecting rising mortgage rates and higher home
prices, a real estate trade group said.
   The National Association of Realtors said Monday that for the
first time since March 1986, its housing affordability index showed
that a typical American family did not have enough money to buy a
median-priced home.
   The index dropped to 99.3 percent in June, down from 100.7
percent in May. That means that a family earning the national
median of $32,760 a year had 99.3 percent of the funds needed to
qualify for conventional financing covering 80 percent of the
purchase price of a home costing a median price of $93,200.
   The decline in affordability in June was blamed on an increase
in mortgage rates and a $600 increase in the median resale price of
a home. Mortgage rates at closing climbed to 10.59 percent in June,
up from a nationwide average of 10.46 percent in May. The
association uses a composite rate reflecting both fixed-rate and
adjustable-rate mortgages.
   Officials noted that, since June, mortgage rates have begun
declining in response to credit-easing moves on the part of the
Federal Reserve and home prices have begun moderating as well.
   ``Lower mortgage rates and price moderation in many areas will
help people who can make a down payment. But, in high-cost areas,
the entry-level buyer is still going to be priced out,'' said Ira
Gribin, president of the Realtors group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
