<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     08-01 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Reach Lowest Levels Since Last Autumn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction to the lowest levels since last
fall.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.65 percent, down from 8.09 percent
last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.35 percent, down from 7.73 percent last
week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.54
percent last Nov. 7 and six-month bills averaged 7.34 percent on
Sept. 19, 1988.
   The discount rates understate the actual return to investors _
7.91 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,806.60 and 7.74 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,628.40.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.86
percent last week, down from 7.96 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
