<HEAD>American Express To Sell Last of Fireman's Fund Common Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. will sell the last of its
common stock in Fireman's Fund Corp. back to the company for $342
million in securities, the companies said.
   American Express said Monday the transaction represented its
exit from the property and casualty insurance business, which it
regarded as too up-and-down and a poor fit with the rest of its
businesses. The financial services giant continues to sell life
insurance, a business it entered through Fireman's Fund.
   American Express bought Fireman's Fund for $350 million in
preferred stock in 1968 and began selling it piece by piece in
1985. The sale of the final 15 percent brings total proceeds of the
sale to $1.8 billion, the company said.
   Fireman's Fund is paying for the stock purchase by issuing a
special class of voting preferred stock to American Express. There
are no restrictions on American Express' ability to trade the
preferred shares, which are redeemable after seven years.
