<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerConfidence     08-01 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Confidence,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Confidence Still at High Level</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer confidence increased in July despite
indications of sluggish economic activity, a research group
reported.
   The Conference Board said Monday its consumer confidence index
rose 3.5 points during the month to 120.7.
   ``The continued high level of consumer confidence despite signs
that the economy may be slowing can be attributed to the strength
of the particular economic circumstances which affect daily life of
the average citizen,'' said Fabian Linden, executive director of
the board's consumer research center.
   ``Unemployment has been hovering around 5 percent and we are
generating about 200,000 new jobs a month,'' he said. ``Declining
interest rates and the inflation rate, which is fluctuating between
modest and barely visible, also contribute to the consumer's sense
of security.''
   Based on a monthly survey of about 5,000 households, the board
said consumers expressed considerable satisfaction with present
business conditions and slightly fewer people believe the current
climate is bad.
   The survey found 31.8 percent of those responding thought
business conditions were good, up from 28.3 percent in the survey a
month earlier. There was a drop of 2 percent in the number of
people who termed conditions as bad.
   People continued to be positive about the employment situation
and a third of all the survey respondents said jobs were plentiful.
In the July survey, 18.6 percent of those participating said that
more job opportunities will become available in the months ahead,
up from 17.9 percent in the June poll.
   The Conference Board is a nonprofit research organization
supported by companies, trade and professional groups, government
agencies, labor unions, schools, libraries and individuals.
   Its monthly survey of households is conducted by National Family
Opinion of Toledo, Ohio.
</TEXT>
