<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BoiseModernization     08-01 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boise Modernization,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>$450 Million Paper Machine Planned for Western Maine Mill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUMFORD, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boise Cascade Corp. has unveiled a plan to
install one of the world's largest paper machines at its mill in
this Androscoggin River town, a $450 million project that will
continue the mill's two-decade trend toward a smaller work force.
   The new machine, with an annual capacity of 318,000 tons, will
be the centerpiece of a $770 million modernization program designed
to turn one of the nation's oldest pulp and paper mills into one of
the largest and most productive manufacturers of coated papers for
catalogs and magazines, the Boise, Idaho-based company said Monday.
   Coated paper from the mill in western Maine is used in such
publications as Time, National Geographic, People and Vanity Fair
as well as such catalogs as L.L. Bean, Horchow and Macy's, Baxter
said.
   The company said it expects to begin installing the machine and
building related facilities in 1991, with a start-up of production
planned for late 1993.
   The new machine will lead to an unspecified reduction in the
1,600-member work force at the Rumford mill, according to Eric S.
Baxter, spokesman at the offices of Boise Cascade's coated paper
division in Portland.
   ``We'll be shutting down four very old machines to make way for
the new machine,'' said Baxter. He said there will be no layoffs
and all job losses will be carried out through attrition.
   The president of Local 900 of the United Paperworkers
International Union, which represents some 1,250 production workers
at Boise Cascade, declined comment on the merits of the project but
expressed surprise that it was announced at this time.
   ``They (management) told us about a month ago that it was being
put on hold for at least nine months to a year before it was going
to be announced. Now, they go ahead and announce it,'' Don Barker
said.
   Barker, whose union was involved in a violent strike at Boise
Cascade three years ago, noted that the mill had more than 3,000
workers before automation began to shrink the number of jobs.
   Built around the turn of the century at a bend in the
Androscoggin River, the mill has produced both coated and uncoated
papers. When the new machine is installed, production will rise to
753,000 tons a year and be made up entirely of coated papers, the
company said.
   The project hinges on obtaining state and federal environmental
permits to install and operate the machine.
   Other elements of Boise Cascade's modernization include:
   _ A $180 million power generation project to be completed next
year that will eliminate the need for 600,000 barrels of oil a year
and reduce particulate emissions by 50 percent.
   _ A $75 million pulp mill expansion project that will increase
pulp production capacity by 212 tons a day, or 25 percent.
   _ A $52 million complete rebuilding of one paper machine and a
$12 million enhancement of another machine.
</TEXT>
