<FIRST>r f PM-MisleadingMail     08-01 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Misleading Mail,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes to Clamp Down on Misleading Mail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved a bill to clamp down on
private businesses and others who attempt to mislead consumers by
designing their mailings to look like U.S. government documents.
   The bill, passed by voice vote Monday and sent to the Senate,
would require such mass-mail solicitations to have on the envelope
or wrapper: ``THIS IS NOT A GOVERNMENT DOCUMENT.''
   Rep. Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., said the bill was needed to
``protect the consumer, especially because many of these deceptive
mailings appear to be targeted at the elderly and other vulnerable
groups.''
   He cited the case of one group which has been attracting elderly
people to pay it a fee for helping them sign up for Social
Security, something that's done for free by government employees.
</TEXT>
