<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Wang Bjt   08-01 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Wang, Bjt,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Wang Reports $375 Million Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wang Laboratories Inc. is so troubled that
it would be put up for sale were it not for the objection of the
founding family, which controls the stock voting rights and is
struggling to turn the computer maker around, analysts say.
   The Lowell-based company reported a $375 million quarterly loss
Monday and announced it had suspended dividend payments. It also
said its financial condition put it in violation of a bank lending
agreement.
   In addition to the objection of the Wang family to a sale, the
company is burdened with lines of business that are not attractive
to potential buyers, analysts said. The family controls 80 percent
of the stock voting rights.
   Most of the quarterly loss stemmed from a $237 million pre-tax
charge to cover the cost of a restructuring that involved closing
factories, cutting jobs and lowering the book value of outdated
assets.
   But the company also lost money on its ongoing operations.
   ``A third of (the loss) is current operations and clearly they
have to reduce their expense structure further,'' said John W.
Adams, chairman of Adams, Harkness &amp; Hill in Boston. ``I'm sure
they're aware of it. The computer business has just gotten to be
more and more competitive.''
   The latest bad news pushed Wang's stock down 37{ cents to close
at $6.12{ a share on the American Stock Exchange.
   Wang stock has lost more than 80 percent of its value since
early 1984, when it traded above $35 a share.
   The most pressing crisis for Wang is that the loss in its fourth
fiscal quarter reduced its net worth below the level required by
its commercial banks under a $300 million revolving credit
agreement.
   Wang said it had received waivers from the banks through Aug. 10
and was continuing to negotiate new terms that would give it some
breathing room. The company said it hired Lodestar Group and
Salomon Brothers Inc. as financial advisers.
   Founded in 1951, Wang ranks 145th on Fortune magazine's list of
the 500 largest American industrial companies, but in recent years
the computer maker has shown a pronounced limp.
   After building a reputation in office word processors in the
1970s, Wang watched as sales slowly eroded due to powerful personal
computers that have taken their place. Its minicomputer business
likewise faltered as the popularity of workstations has risen.
   Wang is trying to make a comeback by focusing on four types of
customers: financial services, government, manufacturing and
professional services. Its most promising asset is Freestyle, a
technology that allows interaction with a personal computer through
an electronic pencil instead of a keyboard or ``mouse.''
   Wang also is promoting its imaging equipment, which allows
companies to electronically scan documents, photographs and other
material and enter it into a computer for storage and collation.
The materials may later be recalled on a computer screen in their
original form.
   Wang cut its work force by more than 10 percent to 28,300 in the
year ended June 30, while executives have taken pay cuts of 5
percent to 20 percent.
   More jobs will be shed in the coming months with the previously
announced decisions to close a 240-employee factory in Stirling,
Scotland, and reduce employment at its Juncos, Puerto Rico, plant
to 125 people from 500.
   On top of Wang's financial problems are the health problems of
An Wang, the company's 69-year-old founder and chairman, who
underwent surgery July 14 for cancer of the esophagus. He left the
hospital Thursday and doctors said he is progressing, according to
Wang spokesman Joseph Roy.
   ``He has a Freestyle at home and he's been in contact with us
quite frequently,'' Roy said.
   Wang's son, Frederick, is president of the company.
   For the quarter ended June 30, the net loss of $374.7 million
came on revenue of $783.7 million, compared with earnings of $13.4
million, or 8 cents a share, on $822.8 million in revenue for the
same period a year ago.
   The company reported a net loss of $424.3 million for all of it
its 1989 fiscal year as compared with net income of $92.7 million,
or 56 cents a share, on revenue of $3.07 billion in its fiscal 1988.
   The company said directors voted not to declare a quarterly
dividend for the first quarter of fiscal 1990, but will consider an
annual dividend policy as soon as operating performance allows.
</TEXT>
