<FIRST>r f PM-ExportSubsidies     08-01 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Export Subsidies,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says Export Program Meeting Goals Of Increased Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farm export subsidy program is meeting its
goals of increasing sales of agricultural products abroad and
pressuring U.S. competitors to negotiate in international trade
talks, government officials told Congress.
   The Agriculture Department and the General Accounting Office,
the investigative arm of Congress, delivered the favorable
assessments of the Export Enhancement Program to a House
Agriculture subcommittee Monday. The USDA, which just completed a
study of EEP, said fears the Bush administration might halt the
program were unfounded.
   ``We believe that EEP is an important trade policy tool,'' said
Richard T. Crowder, USDA undersecretary for international affairs
and commodity programs.
   GAO credited the subsidy program for increasing farm exports to
a number of countries, including the Soviet Union, China, Egypt,
Jordan and Iraq, and said abandoning EEP would ``weaken the U.S.
negotiating position'' with the European Community.
   Under EEP, private exporters can sell U.S. commodities at lower
prices to meet foreign competition and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   There have been $8.4 billion in farm sales through the program
since it was established by the 1985 farm law, and the subsidies
were valued at nearly $2.6 billion. About half of the $770 million
allocated for the program this year has been awarded, with most of
the subsidies going for wheat sales.
   In its study, USDA estimated that EEP subsidies caused wheat
exports to grow 10 percent to 30 percent more than what they would
have been without the program. The department concluded the program
operated at little or no cost to the government by moving more
grain into export markets, which in turn helps lower the cost of
federal price supports to farmers.
   White House budget officials directed USDA to review the program
last year to answer questions about its cost and whether it was
meeting its goals. Farm-state lawmakers expressed concern earlier
this year that EEP subsidy offers appeared to have been put on hold
during the review, although administration officials have said
there were no delays.
   At the hearing, members of the wheat, soybeans and feed grains
subcommittee criticized USDA's management of the subsidy program
and questioned why the agency had not used the program for soybean
oil sales to the Soviet Union.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., the subcommittee chairman, complained
that USDA had not finished a review of a Swiss-based company's
possible ties to a fugitive commodities trader. The company, Richco
Grain Ltd., received at least $65 million in subsidies through EEP.
   ``You have yet to tell us how the largest tax evader in the
history of the United States of America, one of them, was able to
participate in the Export Enhancement Program,'' said Glickman.
   Glickman contends the company is tied through a series of
subsidiary arrangements to Marc Rich, who fled to Switerland in
1983 before his indictment for criminal tax evasion, racketeering,
mail and wire fraud.
</TEXT>
