<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 0133EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FoodInspection     08-01 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Food Inspection,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Auditing Agency Raps Food Inspection System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has failed to
impose sufficient management controls over a new computer system
aimed at allowing spot-checks of certain meat and poultry
processing plants, the General Accounting Office said.
   In a report prepared for a House Government Operations
subcommittee, the congressional investigative arm found fault with
many aspects of the department's ``Performance Based Inspection
System.'' In general, it concluded the department's computer system
aimed at singling out plants for inspection on the basis of their
health risk had not lived up to its billing.
   The report, released Monday, concluded the Agriculture
Department's computerized inspection-scheduling system ``cannot be
relied upon to give the type of quality information needed as a
basis for making decisions'' on which plants should be scrutinized.
   ``The GAO report confirms the evidence from our April hearing
that PBIS does not adequately protect consumers from unsafe
processed meat and poultry,'' Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., chairman of
the human resources subcommittee, said in a statement.
   ``I am alarmed that since April, USDA has installed this flawed
system nationally and intends to spend more than $13 million on
PBIS by 1996,'' he said. ``Hopefully, USDA will heed GAO's advice
to stop wasting any more money on PBIS until the agency has
regained control over the program.''
   Mitchell Zeller, counsel to the subcommittee, said in an
interview that Congress enacted legislation in 1986 allowing the
Agriculture Department to go to a system of spot-checking certain
suspect meat and poultry inspection plants. In doing so, the agency
abandoned routine inspections of individual plants and began
reducing the number of inspectors from 2,300 to 1,100. The agency
said that would save the government $27 million a year.
   ``The theory was fine,'' Zeller said. ``But they've taken
control of inspections away from the inspectors and put too much
reliance on a computer system that doesn't work.''
   In his report to the House panel, James W. Harman, director of
food and agriculture issues at the GAO, said investigators ``found
various problems'' with the computerized inspection-scheduling
system and said they stemmed in large part from the agency's
``failure to apply management controls.''
   Agricultre Department officials had no immediate comment on the
GAO report. But in his report, Harman said he had discussed the
problem with agency officials.
   ``While generally agreeing with our assessment of PBIS,'' the
agency said the computerized system was its ``highest priority''
and said they would ``make a concerted effort to correct any
problems,'' he said.
</TEXT>
