<FIRST>r f PM-STP-Expansion Bjt   08-01 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-STP-Expansion, Bjt,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>STP Makes Move Into Auto Service Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alex. in in 5th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 30 years after it was created as
a special lubricant for auto engines, STP is being called upon to
help its parent company slip into the $25 billion-a-year automotive
services market.
   First Brands Corp. of Danbury says it will open up to 100
automotive service centers under the familiar red, white and blue
STP logo over the next three to five years. The company also
expects to see revenues from the new venture grow to $150 million a
year during that period.
   ``STP has connotative qualities of high performance, high
technology, durability and dependability ... all of which were
considered highly favorable in launching this brand into another
business,'' said Ronald A. Artzer, president of STP Consumer
Services Inc., a subsidiary of First Brands.
   The STP centers will offer oil changes, car washes, cooling
system maintenance and tune-ups. They will compete directly against
other established automotive service companies, such as Jiffy Lube
International Inc., Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. and Sears, Roebuck
and Co.
   ``The competition is getting a lot stiffer,'' said analyst
Franklin L. Morton, a vice president with Alex. Brown &amp; Sons Inc.
in Baltimore.
   ``The market is growing and so is the number of people entering
the market,'' Morton said, noting other newcomers include the Ford
Motor Co. and Avis Inc.
   Morton said a shakeout is inevitable due to the vast growth of
car service companies. He said a key to success will be careful
marketing.
   In another sign of the industry's growing competition, Pennzoil
Co. agreed last week to buy 80 percent of Jiffy Lube and take over
management of the chain, which has more than 1,000 franchised
outlets. The oil company is expected to strengthen the chain's
market position.
   The first STP center opened last month in Atlanta. Three more
are planned for Atlanta, and another is planned for Charolotte,
N.C., as First Brands tests its new concept. The cities were chosen
because they are in auto-racing country, where STP is well known
for its long affiliation with NASCAR racing and driver Richard
Petty.
   The business marks the second new subsidiary for First Brands,
which has been looking for ways to expand since it was created in
1986 through a leveraged buyout of Union Carbide Corp.'s home and
automotive divisions.
   The buyout, engineered by executivies of the former Carbide
divisions, created a $1.2 billion corporation with such well-known
products as Prestone antifreeze, Simoniz car wax and Glad plastic
bags, in addtion to STP. But the deal also left First Brand
executives with the challenge of finding new markets for their
well-established products.
   ``The company wanted some growth horizons. I won't say the
businesses we're in are mature, but they've been around awhile,''
Artzer said.
   A marketing study was done, and the results showed potential
growth for STP in automotive repair and maintenance. Artzer said
the study showed a particularly strong growth area in the quick
lube business, where consumers can get an oil change in a matter of
minutes.
   He noted that car manufacturers are suggesting more frequent oil
changes for small-engine cars. The study also showed that there are
not enough service centers to keep up with the demand for routine
maintenance. And people are keeping their cars longer due to the
costs of replacing them, he said.
   ``The dynamics are great,'' said Artzer, who was hired in
September because of his expertise in franchise marketing.
   STP will test two types of service centers. The Atlanta shops
will be ``STP Service Plus'' centers that will offer quick lubes,
car washes, cooling system maintenace and tune-ups. In Charlotte,
it will test ``STP Super Plus,'' which will offer all the same
services plus sell gasoline.
   To reduce the hassle of getting a car repaired, STP will keep
computer records of all work done for its customers. Customers will
be able to obtain maintenace records when they want to sell their
cars and also will receive notices reminding them when regular
maintenance is needed.
   Aside from serving the customer, the computer records will help
STP determine ``operational standards,'' Artzer said. In the 1990s,
this information will be used to sell STP franchises.
   First Brands has set no limit on the money that can be spent to
develop the business into a national chain, Artzer said.
   ``This is a business we want to have a major impact on First
Brands,'' he said.
</TEXT>
