<SECOND>BC-Earns-Natwest,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Posts Profit Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Westminster PLC, Britain's biggest bank,
on Tuesday reported a 58 percent drop in earnings for the first
half of 1989 due to a sharp increase in its loan-loss provision.
   The bank said after-tax profit for the six months ended June 30
totaled $314 million, or 20 cents a share, compared with $740
million, or 50 cents a share, in 1988.
   The latest period included an $8 million charge for the closure
of the bank's primary dealership in New York.
   Natwest also made provisions of $656 million to cover possible
losses on loans to Third World countries, compared with $10 million
in its loan-loss provision a year ago.
   Excluding that pre-tax profit would have risen 13 percent to a
record $1.56 billion, the bank said.
