<SECOND>BC-Montedison,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Chemical Group Announces Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montedison SpA, Italy's largest chemical
company, has offerd to buy all the remaining outstanding stock of
Himont Inc. of Wilmington, Del., and Erbamont N.V. of the
Netherlands, for about $1.06 billion.
   Montedison currently owns 81 percent of Himont and 72 percent of
Erbamont.
   It is offering $49 in cash and warrants for each of the 12.3
million shares of Himont it does not already own and $37 in cash
and warrants for each of the 12.4 million shares of Erbamont.
   In an announcement Monday, Montedison said it wanted to acquire
full control in the two subsidiries to compete more effecctively in
the increasingly global market.
   Analysts said it would be easier for Montedison to sell parts of
Himont and Erbamont through a restructuring without having to deal
with minority shareholders.
   Montedison said the two separate transactions were subject to
the approval of the respective boards of the two companies.
   Erbamon markets the anti-cancer drug Adriamycin.
