<FIRST>u f PM-Coke-Buffett 1stLd-Writethru   08-01 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coke-Buffett, 1st Ld-Writethru,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Stock Sharply Higher on Warren Buffett's Investment Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS chief financial officer's name to J. Verne McKenzie
in 9th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURAN NEERGAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Warren Buffett's intention to expand his
stake in Coca-Cola Co. has pushed the soft drink company's stock
sharply higher.
   Buffett, who has made a reputation and rishes as a savvy,
long-term investor, filed a statement with the Securities and
Exchange Commission Monday seeking clearance to purchase up to 15
percent of Coca-Cola's common stock.
   Earlier this year, Coca-Cola disclosed that Buffett had acquired
a 6.8 percent stake. He was elected to the company's board of
directors in July.
   Coca-Cola stock spurted $4.50 to $68 a share Monday on the New
York Stock Exchange even though a spokesman for Buffett said that
the filing was not a purchase announcement.
   An analyst said Buffett's plans could inspire other investors to
back Coke.
   ``This may make other investors more interested in Coca-Cola
because Warren Buffett has an extraordinary track record,'' said
analyst Emanuel Goldman, of Paine Webber Inc. in San Francisco.
``His even talking about 15 percent in Coca-Cola is a tremendous
endorsement of the company.''
   Randy Donaldson, a Coca-Cola spokesman, said the company was
``delighted when Mr. Buffett made his significant investment in the
Coca-Cola Co. and the relationship that has developed since that
investment has reinforced that initial positive view.''
   Buffett _ who has said he is a Cherry Coke drinker _ is chief
executive officer of the diversified Omaha, Neb.-based conglomerate
Berkshire Hathaway Inc. He and his wife control 45 percent of
Berkshire Hathaway stock.
   Berkshire Hathaway chief financial officer J. Verne McKenzie
said that Monday's filing was not an announcement of immediate
stock purchases.
   ``This does not say there are plans now to buy,'' McKenzie said,
noting that purchase plans would be made based on stock price and
market conditions. ``This gives us a flexibility to buy to match
our flexibility to sell.''
   McKenzie said the filing also addresses Buffett's clearance to
sell his Coca-Cola stock, but ``there are no plans to sell now.''
   When Coca-Cola disclosed in March that Buffett had acquired more
than 6 percent of the company, Buffett called the purchases
``simply a passive investment'' and said he is happy with the way
the company is being managed.
   McKenzie said there had been no change in Buffett's view of the
investment. Buffett was not available for comment Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
