<DOCNO> AP890801-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Kodak     08-01 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Kodak,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Blames Restructuring for Second Quarter, Half-Year Earnings
Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said Tuesday its profit
fell 85 percent in the second quarter, mainly because of one-time
charges to cover the cost of a corporate restructuring.
   Even without the special charges, though, net earnings would
have dropped 26 percent from last year's record. The company
attributed the weakness to higher costs, including interest
expenses, and the impact of the dollar's rise.
   ``While volume gains so far this year have been gratifying,
especially in the United States, our earnings have not kept pace,''
Chairman Colby Chandler said in a press release. ``Strong steps are
being taken to address the earnings shortfall.''
   Net earnings from the second quarter were $60 million, or 18
cents a share, down from a record $390 million, or $1.20 a share, a
year earlier. Revenue rose to a record $4.5 billion from $4.13
billion a year earlier.
   For the first half, earnings fell 60 percent to $260 million, or
80 cents a share, from $650 million, or $2 a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose to a record $8.4 billion from $7.46 billion a year
earlier.
   Earnings from operations were $276 million for the quarter,
compared with a restated $769 million for the second quarter of
1988. For the half-year, operating earnings dipped to $745 million
from last year's restated $1.24 billion.
   The company announced July 24 that it was taking a $225 million
charge against earnings for the second quarter of 1989 because of
consolidation of its photofinishing and consumer photography units
and associated write-offs of equipment, salaries and goodwill,
along with special separation payments to outgoing employees.
   ``For the balance of the year, we look for continued gains in
sales with earnings improved over the half year to approximately
the same level as the record earnings reported for the 1988 second
half,'' Chandler said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
