<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Brokers     08-01 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokers,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bear Stearns Fourth Quarter Income Jumps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bear Stearns Cos. Inc. said Tuesday its
fourth-quarter profit more than doubled from a year ago.
   Bear Stearns, parent of the investment firm, Bear, Stearns &amp;
Co., reported net income of $47.6 million, or 50 cents a share, up
from $20.8 million, or 19 cents a share, in the comparable 1988
period.
   Revenue totaled $629.7 million, a 30 percent increase over
$485.8 million a year ago.
   For the fiscal year ended June 30, the New York holding company
posted a 71 percent rise in net earnings to $172.4 million, or
$1.78 a share, from $100.7 million, or 96 cents a share, in the
previous year. Revenue jumped 25 percent to $2.4 billion from $1.9
billion in the last fiscal year.
   Alan C. Greenberg, chairman and chief executive, said the
company's earnings per share neared the previous record set in the
year ended April 30, 1987, six months before the stock market
collapse.
   ``We believe this is a strong endorsement of the many decisions
we made in October 1987 and we look forward to the new year with
continued optimism,'' Greenberg said.
   Although the company's earnings plunged dramatically after the
stock market crash of October 1987, it vowed not to cut back
businesses or lay off employees. The company said at the time it
would continue to tighten expenses and hire new employees.
</TEXT>
