<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     08-01 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0447</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed today after the release
of economic reports that reawakened fears of a possible recession
among some investors.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was off 2.28
points at 2,658.38 as of 11 a.m. EDT.
   Advancing issues and declining ones were almost evenly matched
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 640 higher, 641 lower and 509
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 78.30 million shares.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said today its
index of the economy slumped to 46 percent in July, its lowest
reading since an identical one in January 1983.
   Also pointing toward slow growth was a Commerce Department
report on a decline in construction spending.
   Before the reports' release the Dow Jones industrial average had
been up 13 points. Stock investors are jittery at these levels.
Monday's rally carried the Dow Jones average to within 60 points of
its record high, 2,722.42 on Aug. 25, 1987.
   ``The purchasing managers indeed took the starch out of it. ...
You have people looking at one word in the back of their mind, and
that is recession,'' said Thomas R. Walsh, senior vice president
and head of equity trading at Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc.
   On the other hand, Walter Murphy, a Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. analyst,
said he felt the economic reports were not a factor in the market's
retrenchment.
   ``The market is down because of its own internal technicals
rather than any fundamental external news,'' he said.
   Traders have been taking confidence from signs of declining
interest rates. Bond prices rallied on Monday and the price gains
continued early in today's trading.
   But the economic slowdown that helps the inflation-sensitive
bond market is not so good for the stock market because slow growth
could hurt corporate profits.
   Today the Commerce Department added to evidence that the economy
was sluggish by announcing that construction spending in June fell
0.8 percent, following a rise of 0.6 percent in May. The May
increase had originally been estimated at 1.3 percent.
   Among the early volume leaders on the NYSE, Texaco was up \ at
53], American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was down [ at 40{, Upjohn was
down 1[ at 34~, and Citicorp was down | at 33\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.11 to 192.30. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 0.01 to 3767.55.
   On Monday the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 25.42
points to 2,660.66.
</TEXT>
