<HEAD>Soybean Futures Up, Grain Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rose slightly in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade while corn and wheat
futures were narrowly mixed following a broad selloff in the
previous session.
   The soybean market advanced in line with modest gains in soybean
oil and soybean meal.
   On Monday, soybean prices for near-term delivery plunged below
$7.25 a bushel, a 16{-month low, following a wetter-than-expected
weekend in key Midwestern growing areas.
   A six- to 10-day National Weather Service forecast issued late
Monday predicted a return to mild, rainy conditions in the Midwest
next week, which was seen as bearish for the corn and soybean
markets.
   The Agriculture Department's weekly crop-progress report showed
continued improvement in crop conditions during the week ending
Sunday.
   The USDA rated 79 percent of the U.S. corn crop in fair to good
condition and 15 percent in excellent condition, up from 12 percent
in the previous week. The USDA said 84 percent of the soybean crop
was in fair to good shape and 9 percent was in excellent condition
compared with 7 percent in the previous week's survey.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.85{ a bushel; corn was
1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.21{ a bushel;
oats were 2{ cents to 4{ cents higher with September at $1.34 a
bushel; soybeans were } cent to 2{ cents higher with August at
$6.27 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were narrowly mixed while pork futures were lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .10 cent higher with August
at 72.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .05
cent higher with August at 83.55 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent
to .47 cent lower with August at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .42 cent to .97 cent lower with August at 24.65 cents
a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Monday while pork futures were
mostly lower.
</TEXT>
