<FIRST>r f BC-AutoIncentives     08-01 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Incentives,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Boosts Cash Incentives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. on Tuesday offered $1,000
factory-sponsored cash incentives on 21 Ford, Lincoln and Mercury
models and $300 to $750 on 13 others.
   As the Big Three carmakers near model changeover, they are
throwing cash at customers to help clear showrooms of light-selling
models as well as popular but more expensive cars, like the Probe
LX-GT, which carries a $500 cash-back offer or a discounted annual
percentage rate.
   Ford's discounted interest rates range from 2.9 percent on a
two-year loan to 10.9 percent for five years. The incentives run
indefinitely, Ford said.
   No. 1 General Motors Corp. announced new incentive programs for
four divisions in early July, including the tripling of cash
incentives on two Buick models. Most of the GM division incentives
run indefinitely.
   Chrysler Corp. has ongoing $1,000 cash rebate offers on all
Jeep-Eagle models.
   Ford Division Vice President and General Manager Thomas J.
Wagner said the higher cash rebates are more popular with customers
than discounted interest rates.
   The Lincoln-Mercury Division is offering at least $1,000 cash
back on all its models, including the ongoing $4,000 rebate on the
sporty XR4Ti, which is being phased out.
   Bulging inventories have barely been dented by the incentive
programs to date, and the companies have taken advantage of the
traditional shutdown for retooling to extend the involuntary
vacation for plant workers.
   The eight major domestic automakers sold 19 percent fewer cars
during the first six months of this year compared with the same
period in 1988, which was the second-best sales year in history.
More than 15.8 million cars and light trucks were sold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
