<DOCNO> AP890801-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Hunt-Bankruptcy     08-01 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hunt-Bankruptcy,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Creditors Win Victory in Hunt Bankruptcy Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Harold Abramson said
creditors in the bankruptcy case of William Herbert and Nancy Hunt
can submit suggestions on how the Hunts should repay their debts.
   The judge's decision Monday shifts leverage in the case from the
debtors to the creditors. Creditors previously had to base
negotiations on a plan developed by Herbert Hunt.
   Abramson said he will allow the suggestions because he did not
see a resolution coming from Herbert Hunt's proposed settlement.
   ``I find that the mere filing of competing plans will not impede
debtors' negotiations,'' said the judge, who ultimately will decide
how creditors are paid.
   The Internal Revenue Service and Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
of New York, two of the largest creditors in the Herbert Hunt
bankruptcy, said they will file a repayment plan by Friday.
   ``This is exactly what we have been asking for,'' said Grover
Hartt III, an attorney for the IRS.
   The IRS claims Herbert Hunt owes about $300 million in back
taxes while brother Nelson Bunker Hunt owes $700 million. The IRS
has agreed to settle both cases for about $350 million.
   Bunker and Herbert owned one-third of the world's supply of
silver bullion from a silver-shopping spree that began in 1973,
government attorneys claim.
   As the price tumbled to $10 an ounce from $50 an ounce, the
brothers found themselves with debts totaling as much as $2 billion
and creditors threatening the family's beloved Placid Oil Co.
   Barbara Houser, attorney for the Peruvian silver mining company
Minpeco S.A., which seeks $251 million, said she also has a plan
prepared.
   Abramson gave Bunker Hunt and his wife Caroline, until Aug. 31
to work out a repayment plan with their creditors.
   The judge said the Hunt cases are ``two of the most difficult
Chapter 11 cases a lawyer could envision.''
   Stephen A. McCartin, attorney for Herbert and Nancy Hunt said
that allowing creditors to submit repayment proposals will ``make
it more difficult to reach a consensual plan.''
   The IRS plan to be filed this week in the Herbert Hunt case will
recommend that the agency receive 70 percent of a liquidating
trust, or about $60 million. Under the plan, the IRS also would get
$90 million in a non-dischargeable claim that would be paid after
Herbert emerges from bankruptcy.
   The IRS is negotiating a similar settlement proposal with Bunker
and his wife, Caroline.
   The Hunt brothers, including Lamar Hunt, are in U.S. Tax Court
contesting the millions of dollars in taxes the IRS says it is owed
from the 1982 dissolution of a partnership set up to repay their
debts after the silver price collapse.
   The Hunts' non-jury, tax trial reconvenes in Washington, D.C.,
on Aug. 21.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890801-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FCCNominees-Indecency 2ndLd-Writethru f0Minn.(AP)(USDA)_Tuesdaycattle1
08-01 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FCC Nominees-Indecency, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0079,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Bush's Nominees For FCC</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 6 grafs with vote and new information. Picks up 6th
graf pvs, `Garbage is ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Commerce Committee today voted 15-2
to approve President Bush's three nominees for the Federal
Communications Commission and sent the appointments to the floor
for expected speedy confirmation.
   Committee Chairman Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., said he
expected the full Senate to vote on the nominations of Alfred C.
Sikes, Sherrie P. Marshall and Andrew C. Barrett before the
scheduled beginning of the congressional recess on Friday.
   Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., and Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.,
cast the dissenting votes.
   The vote came one day after a hearing that was dominated by the
issues of sex and violence on the airwaves.
   Gore said he voted against the nomination as a symbolic protest
of eight years of free-market deregulation of the communications
industry under the Reagan administration. He said he believed the
new nominees would continue the Reagan-era philosophy.
   Hollings, Gore and others hit hard on TV indecency, noting that
until Congress stepped in to ban all indecent TV programs in 1988,
the FCC had established a ``safe harbor'' for such shows from
midnight to 6 a.m. when children were presumed not to be watching.
   ``Garbage is garbage regardless of the time of day,'' Hollings
said.
   Barrett sparked a confrontation with Gore when he said that he
abhorred indecent programming, but that the FCC must recognize
``there is a market for indecency'' and that the agency's role is
to decide ``what the law will allow us to tolerate.''
   Americans, Gore responded, are ``sick and tired of what's going
on.''
   Sikes said he would vigorously attack obscene material on the
airwaves, but that the Supreme Court has proscribed much of
Congress' power in the area of free speech and indecency.
   The FCC last year tried to implement the 24-hour ban on indecent
programming, but broadcasters and civil rights groups challenged it
on constitutional grounds. A federal appeals court in January
stayed imposition of the law.
   Hollings and other committee members expressed hope that
relations between the FCC and Congress would improve after eight
years of battles with a commission headed by outgoing Chairman
Dennis R. Patrick and his predecessor, Mark S. Fowler.
   Because of his displeasure with Patrick's policies, Hollings had
refused for more than a year to hold hearings on other nominees to
fill two vacancies on the five-member FCC. Patrick will step down
when Sikes is confirmed.
   Sikes, a self-described moderate, is the assistant secretary of
Commerce for communications and information, a former broadcaster
and a longtime political ally of Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., a
member of the committee.
   Barrett is a member of the Illinois Commerce Commission, and
Marshall is a lawyer and former legislative aide to Patrick.
   The nominees face a host of important issues, such as the
government role in fostering international competitiveness in areas
such as high-definition television; further deregulation of the
telephone industry; re-regulating cable television; and assignment
of the airwaves to competing businesses such as cellular telephones
and direct broadcast satellites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890801-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     08-01 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0495</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were higher today after a brief
downturn, and the market appeared unsettled after its recent sharp
runup.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 8.91 points
at 2,669.57 as of noon EDT.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones about 5 to 4 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 741 higher, 602 lower and 510
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 111.42 million shares as of noon
on Wall Street, up from 73.15 million shares at the same time
Monday.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said today its
index of the economy slumped to 46 percent in July, its lowest
reading since an identical one in January 1983.
   Also pointing toward slow growth was a Commerce Department
report on a decline in construction spending.
   Before the reports' release the Dow Jones industrial average had
been up 13 points. It fell and was briefly down about 8 points,
then recovered.
   Stock investors are nervous that the market may have risen too
quickly and is due for a downturn. Monday's rally carried the Dow
Jones average to within 60 points of its record high, 2,722.42 on
Aug. 25, 1987.
   ``The purchasing managers indeed took the starch out of it. ...
You have people looking at one word in the back of their mind, and
that is recession,'' said Thomas R. Walsh, senior vice president
and head of equity trading at Nikko Securities Co. International
Inc.
   On the other hand, Walter Murphy, a Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. analyst,
said he felt the economic reports were not a factor in the market's
brief retrenchment.
   ``The market is down because of its own internal technicals
rather than any fundamental external news,'' he said.
   Traders have been taking confidence from signs of declining
interest rates. Bond prices rallied on Monday and the price gains
continued early in today's trading.
   But the economic slowdown that helps the inflation-sensitive
bond market is not so good for the stock market because slow growth
could hurt corporate profits.
   Today the Commerce Department added to evidence that the economy
was sluggish by announcing that construction spending in June fell
0.8 percent, following a rise of 0.6 percent in May. The May
increase had originally been estimated at 1.3 percent.
   Among the early volume leaders on the NYSE, Texaco was up ] at
53{, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was unchanged at 40|, Upjohn
was down 1[ at 34~, and Citicorp was down { at 33].
   Kodak was off ] to 47~ after reporting lower earnings.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.65 to 193.06. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.81 to 377.37.
   On Monday the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 25.42
points to 2,660.66.
</TEXT>
