<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Markets Close Mostly Higher; Near-Month Soybeans Fall Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices closed mostly higher in a
technical rebound Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade but
soybeans for August delivery plunged to a new 16{-month low,
reflecting a rise in supplies from South America.
   In addition to the increased movement of newly harvested
soybeans from Argentina and Brazil, soybean speculators saw an
important technical support swept away Monday when August soybeans
crashed below $6.25 a bushel.
   Monday's 24{-cent plunge in the August contract prompted selling
in an attempt among some traders to depress the market further, to
the next support level of $6 a bushel, said William Biedermann,
director of research with Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage based
in Crystal Lake, Ill.
   The moderate gains in most of the other grain and soybean
contracts were perceived as a technical correction in a bear market.
   With farmers believed to still be holding fairly large amounts
of corn and soybeans and the harvest season approaching, market
fundamentals look ``pretty bleak,'' Biedermann said.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 6{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.87\ a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to 4{ cents higher with September at $2.22\ a bushel;
oats were 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher with September at $1.33 a
bushel; soybeans were 10{ cents lower to 8 cents higher with August
at $6.14 a bushel, the lowest settlement of a nearby soybean
contract since March 16, 1988.
