<DOCNO> AP890801-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2049EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Carbide-PoisonPill     08-01 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carbide-Poison Pill,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carbide Implements Anti-Takeover Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months after a court settlement in
the Bhopal gas disaster fueled speculation about possible takeover
attempts, Union Carbide Corp. said Tuesday it has implemented
``poison pill'' measures to ward off unwanted suitors.
   Carbide spokesman David N. Kernis called the anti-takeover
measures routine and said officials at the Danbury, Conn.-based
company don't know of any possible takeover attempts and ``none has
been offered.''
   ``Nearly 1,000 companies have these things. We're sure from time
to time these things have come up (for review at Carbide). But,
obviously, this is our first one,'' Kernis said.
   The ``poison pill'' measures, announced last week, would allow
Carbide shareholders to acquire additional stock at a deep
discount, thereby making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive
for a potential acquirer.
   Analysts have said the corporation became a prime takeover
candidate in February, when the Supreme Court of India ordered the
multinational chemical giant to pay $470 million to settle claims
arising from the 1984 Bhopal disaster. But they were cautious in
evaluating Carbide's poison-pill plan.
   While immersed in the legal battle over Bhopal in 1985, Carbide
successfully fought off a $4.3 billion hostile takeover attempt by
GAF Corp. by repurchasing some of its common stock. Directors said
later they never considered a poison-pill defense.
   Harvey Stober, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said
Monday that Carbide is attractive because it has tremendous cash
flow, businesses that can be separated and sold off, and it has
``easily understood'' businesses. In addition, he said the
company's stock is currently undervalued, closing up \ of a point
Monday at $27.12{.
   Carbide last week reported second quarter earnings of $186
million, or $1.33 a share, on sales of $2.28 billion. The earnings
were down slighty from 1988 second quarter earnings of $187
million, or $1.39 a share, on revenue of $2.1 billion.
   Stober said corporate takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn has been
mentioned as one possible Carbide suitor. But Stober said he
believed the company when it said no takeover offers have been made.
   ``It's something that many companies have done. It's usually
done to get fair treatment under a hostile attempt and usually to
preclude the use of greenmail,'' he said. Greenmail is an
antitakeover maneuver in which the target company buys the raider's
stock at a price above that available to other stockholders.
   Leslie Ravitz, an analyst with Salomon Brothers Inc., said that
Carbide's action was typical of the chemical industry. He said it
would be misleading to interpret Carbide's plan as an indication
that it will soon become involved in an acquisition, noting that
the company has had no suitors in the many months that it has been
the subject of takeover talks.
   Ravitz agreed that Carbide is an attractive takeover target. But
so is ``virtually every company out there in the chemical
industry,'' he said, adding that the stock of most chemical
companies are currently undervalued.
   Ravitz said Carbide's poison-pill measures are good only as long
as the board of directors wants to keep them in place. He said if a
large enough cash offer is made, the directors would have to revoke
measures.
   ``It doesn't preclude a takeover. It just gives you a hurdle to
jump,'' he said.
   Under the Carbide plan, shareholders of record as of Aug. 31
will receive one right to purchase a share of common stock at a
discount for each outstanding share of stock they own. The rights
will expire on Aug. 31, 1999, unless redeemed by the company at a
cost of 1 cent per right.
   The rights are exercisable only within 10 days after a potential
buyer acquires 20 percent or more of Carbide common stock, or only
within 10 days of an announcement of a tender offer to acquire at
least 20 percent of Carbide stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890801-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-01 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0261</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices finished lower in active trading
today, buffeted by conflicting sentiments about the economy.
   Wall Street started the day higher, adding to the strong gains
of recent sessions, but later retreated in edgy, volatile activity.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said today its
index of the economy slumped to 46 percent in July, its lowest
reading since an identical one in January 1983.
   Also pointing toward slow growth was a Commerce Department
report on a decline in construction spending.
   The department said construction spending in June fell 0.8
percent, following a rise of 0.6 percent in May. The May increase
had originally been estimated at 1.3 percent.
   The reports' release pushed the Dow Jones industrial average
lower, and the blue-chip indicator swung widely up and down through
the rest of the trading session.
   Stock investors are nervous that the market may have risen too
quickly and is due for a downturn. Monday's rally carried the Dow
average to within 60 points of its record high, 2,722.42 on Aug.
25, 1987.
   Traders have been taking confidence from signs of declining
interest rates. But the economic slowdown that helps the
inflation-sensitive bond market is not so good for the stock market
because slow growth could hurt corporate profits.
   ``It's that balancing act,'' said Larry Wachtel, an analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``Of course we know the economy
has been softening, but bad news has been good news up to now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
