<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-01 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall as Hurricane Worries Abate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices dropped Tuesday, giving
back part of the previous session's gains as a hurricane in the
Gulf of Mexico swept ashore, enabling offshore oil producers to get
back to work.
   The contract for September delivery of West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, fell 28 cents to $18.03 per
42-gallon barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange after rising
38 cents in the previous session. Contracts for delivery in later
months posted similar losses.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
September contract of unleaded gasoline also tumbled, falling 1.27
cents to 51.43 cents a gallon after spurting 1.15 cents a gallon on
Monday. Later contract months posted smaller declines.
   The September contract for delivery of No.2 heating oil settled
0.11 cent lower at 49.20 cents a gallon after rising 0.49 cent on
Monday.
   ``It was the mirror image of yesterday in crude oil and
gasoline,'' said Bob Baker, who follows oil futures prices for the
investment firm Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   On Monday, prices had risen on fears that the storm would
severly disrupt production off the Texas and Louisiana coasts.
   But Baker said those fears proved largely unfounded on Tuesday
and the market concluded ``the hurricane was not going to be much
of a factor in reducing supplies.''
   Hurricane Chantal roared ashore at about 8 a.m. Tuesday on the
upper Texas Gulf Coast and within two hours, tides at Galveston
were reported near normal, enabling several oil drilling companies
to send employees back to work on oil drilling platforms and rigs
in the Gulf.
</TEXT>
