<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-01 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down in New York; Gold Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar tumbled in choppy U.S. trading
Tuesday, weighed down by additional evidence of sluggish economic
activity and expectations of further interest rate declines.
   Gold prices traded near recent levels. On the Commodity Exchange
in New York, gold for August delivery closed at $370.80 a troy
ounce, up 30 cents from Monday's settlement. The Republic National
Bank quoted bullion at $370.50 an ounce as of 4 p.m. in New York,
10 cents higher than Monday's late bid.
   After some initial strength in early New York dealings, the
dollar started to slide after release of a monthly business report
from the National Association of Purchasing Management showing
weakness in manufacturing.
   The Purchasing Managers' Index dropped to 46 percent in July
from 48.8 percent in June, falling to the lowest level since
January 1983.
   The news from the nation's purchasing agents, coupled with
report of a drop in construction spending, reinforced expectations
of further reductions in interest rates.
   Decreases in U.S. interest rates would cut returns on
dollar-denominated investments and lessen demand for dollars.
   Thomas Palladino, an assistant vice president at Amsterdam
Rotterdam Bank's New York office, said currency dealers have been
operating under the assumption that the Federal Reserve Board has
been nudging interest rates lower.
   A rumor swept through the market Tuesday that the central bank
was about to slash its discount rate, a move that would underscore
the Fed's desire for looser credit conditions to revive the
flagging economy.
   Although there wasn't any substance to the rumor, it intensified
the selling, which drove the dollar down toward thresholds
considered technically significant, Palladino said.
   The rumor may have been triggered by Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan's remarks to the Senate Banking Committee. He confirmed
that the central bank lowered interest rates another notch last
week as part of its continuing effort to keep the country out of
recession.
   Earlier, on currency markets abroad, the dollar headed higher in
subdued trading.
   Dealers in Europe reportedly were preoccupied with adjusting
their dollar holdings ahead of Friday's release of U.S.
unemployment figures for July, a potentially market-moving report.
   Sterling stumbled after rebounding recently from a slump. The
pound fell to $1.6550 from $1.6665 late Monday. In New York,
sterling fetched $1.6648 vs. $1.6655 on Monday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 1.75 yen to close at 136.65 yen.
Later, in London, the dollar traded at 136.80 yen. In New York the
dollar closed at 135.80 yen, down from 137 yen on Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8505 West German marks, down from 1.8650; 1.5895
Swiss francs, down from 1.6080; 1.1747 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1811; 6.266 French francs, down from 6.3135; and 1,330.05 Italian
lire, down from 1,341.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late Monday's
levels included: 1.8660 West German marks, up from 1.8655; 1.6075
Swiss francs, up from 1.6065; 6.3135 French francs, down from
6.3155; 2.1060 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1030; 1,342.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,340.03; and 1.1743 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1809.
   Gold prices barely budged.
   Gold finished in London at a bid of $368.25 a troy ounce late
Tuesday, unchanged from late Monday.
   The precious metals market in Zurich was closed for a national
holiday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.62 an ounce to close at
$371.26.
   Silver was trading in London at $5.23 an ounce, up sharply from
Monday's $5.13. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $5.252 a troy ounce, down from Monday's settlement
of $5.269.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
