<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-01 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Retreat As Chantal Threat Eases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices eased Tuesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as the hurricane threat to Gulf Coast oil and natural-gas
operations lessened and traders turned their attention to weekly
supply statistics.
   The market expected the American Petroleum Institute report to
show increases of 1 million to 2 million barrels across the board.
The report, released after the close, showed crude oil stocks up
882,000 barrels, gasoline stocks up 4.6 million barrels and
distillate stocks up about 2.1 million barrels.
   The report also showed a rise in refinery runs, contrary to
expectations.
   On other markets, coffee futures surged; near-month soybean
futures continued to slide but most grain contracts advanced; pork
bellies led the livestock and meat markets lower; and precious
metals were mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 19 cents to 29 cents
lower with the contract for delivery in September at $18.03 a
barrel; heating oil was .11 cent lower to .04 cent higher with
September at 49.20 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .80 cent
to 1.27 cents lower with September at 51.43 cents a gallon.
   The market gave back most of Monday's gains, which were
triggered by fears of damage to Gulf Coast oil refineries and
offshore platforms by Hurricane Chantal.
   ``Today they were selling on the fact that it was not nearly as
bad a hurricane as they were expecting,'' said Ray Mazzeo, energy
futures specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The hurricane lashed the Gulf Coast with heavy rain and wind up
to 80 mph but was downgraded to a tropical storm about 2{ hours
after moving ashore near High Island, Texas, midway between
Galveston and Port Arthur.
   Some offshore oil and gas operations were shut down Monday
afternoon, but they were back in operation late Tuesday.
   Analysts said the only danger to refineries appeared to be the
possibility that the heavy rains could cause some flooding of pumps
located near the ground.
   Coffee futures prices surged on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange in a reversal of the recent trend.
   Some analysts called the rally a technical correction while
others cited Folger Coffee Co.'s announcement of a
20-cents-per-pound cut in wholesale prices of ground roast coffee.
   Folger said the price cut reflected the sharp drop in green
coffee prices following the International Coffee Organization's
July 3 suspension of export quotas.
   Coffee settled 2.02 cents to 3.38 cents higher with September at
82.37 cents a pound.
   Most grain futures advanced in a technical rebound on the
Chicago Board of Trade but soybeans for August delivery plunged to
a new 16{-month low of $6.13{ a bushel, reflecting a rise in
supplies from South America and growing confidence that U.S.
supplies would last until harvest time.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 6} cents higher with September at
$3.87{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 4{ cents higher with
September at $2.22{ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 3{ cents higher
with September at $1.33 a bushel; soybeans were 11 cents lower to 8
cents higher with August at $6.13{ a bushel, the lowest settlement
of a nearby soybean contract since March 16, 1988.
   Pork belly futures prices dropped sharply on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. The near-month contract fell below 25 cents a
pound, reflecting the continuing weak demand for bacon and the
near-record supply of bellies in cold storage.
   Weak cash markets also weighed on the pork and cattle markets.
   Live cattle settled .08 cent to .50 cent lower with August at
72.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .32 cent lower
with August at 83.45 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent to .65
cent lower with August at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .25 cent to 1.35 cents lower with August at 24.82 cents a
pound.
   Gold futures were little changed on New York's Commodity
Exchange while silver finished slightly lower after posting strong
gains in the previous session.
   Gold settled 80 cents lower to 30 cents higher with August at
$370.80 a troy ounce; silver was 1.7 cents to 2 cents lower with
September at $5.293 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
