<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SteelTalks     08-01 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Talks,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armco, USW Settle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Steelworkers on Tuesday announced a
tentative four-year agreement with Armco Inc. that will restore up
to $1 an hour in past reductions to 4,700 union members and further
boost wages up to $1.50 per hour.
   The union's chief negotiator said he expected the offer to be
ratified in a referendum this month by mail. Union negotiators,
voting Monday shortly before the midnight expiration of their old
contract, unanimously recommended membership ratification.
   Armco is the last of five major steelmakers to settle with the
USW during the current round of negotiating. The settlement follows
a pattern set by Bethlehem Steel Corp.
   Armco is offering each worker an immediate $500 signing bonus
and a share of profits.
   Union members at the Baltimore and Kansas City, Mo., plants
would get back wage sacrifices that averaged $1 per hour to be
followed by wage increases averaging 35 cents per hour Aug. 1,
1991, and 40 cents a year later.
   Workers at Armco's Ashland, Ky., plant would no longer
contribute 65 cents per hour to help finance a continuous caster
and would receive $1,000 on Aug. 1, 1990, as an early repayment of
their investments in the $22.5 million caster. More would be repaid
later.
   The Ashland plant employees would also get consecutive annual
raises of 75 cents, 50 cents and 25 cents beginning Jan. 1, 1991.
   The offer also includes cost of living raises effective Aug. 1,
1992, and the restoration of vacations, holidays, premium pay and
shift differentials Jan. 1, 1990.
   Ballots are to be counted Aug. 28 in Pittsburgh.
   Independent unions represent Armco workers in Butler;
Zanesville, Ohio; and Middletown, Ohio. Contracts at Butler and
Zanesville expire at the end of August. Middletown's contract runs
through March 1990, said Armco spokesman Ted Taylor in Parsippany,
N.J.
</TEXT>
