<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Dial-A-Porn     08-01 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dial-A-Porn,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Company to Block `Adult' Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts users of so-called ``dial-a-porn''
telephone services must request special access to them from the
phone company under a state ruling announced Tuesday.
   ``Our intent is to ensure that customers have the greatest
degree of control possible over the types of information that they
and their children can access,'' said Department of Public
Utilities Chairman Bernice K. McIntyre.
   The department directed New England Telephone to separate state
lines with ``adult'' services on to a 940 exchange. New England
Telephone will automatically block the service to all Massachusetts
customers.
   People who want to call in-state pornographic message services
will have to write the telephone company and request access to the
adult line, the directive states.
   The automatic blocking applies only to adult message services in
Massachusetts. ``We can't regulate interstate calls,'' McIntyre
said.
   But New England Telephone will offer customers the option to
block interstate information services, including out-of-state
pornographic lines, on a 900 exchange. Customers will also have the
option to block multi-party chat lines on 550 and other
pre-recorded information lines on 976.
   New England Telephone will determine which services qualify for
the adult line, McIntyre said.
   The telephone company defines anything that contains sexually
suggestive descriptions or innuendo as adult matter, said Clare
Silvestri, a telephone company spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
