<DOCNO> AP890801-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2153EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Bridgestone-Firestone     08-01 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridgestone-Firestone,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridgestone Consolidates Tire Headquarters In Akron</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Bridgestone Corp., which acquired
Firestone Tire &amp; Rubber Co. for $2.6 billion last year, said
Tuesday the combined business will be headquartered in Akron, where
Firestone was founded 89 years ago.
   Firestone's corporate headquarters is in Chicago and Bridgestone
(USA) Inc. is based in Nashville, Tenn. Firestone, formed in Akron
in 1900, moved its headquarters from Akron to Chicago two years ago.
   Three-hundred Firestone employees now in Chicago will be invited
to relocate to Akron, as will about 200 who work at Bridgestone
(USA) offices in Nashville, said Bridgestone spokesman Dennis Allen.
   Akira Yeiri, Bridgestone president, said in a statement that the
consolidation will enable a unified presentation to tire customers.
   ``The past year since the merger of Bridgestone and Firestone
has been spent reviewing our worldwide organization and
operations,'' Yeiri said. ``We are confident that this
consolidation will allow our operations to respond more efficiently
to the challenges and opportunities in the 1990s and beyond.''
   Although Bridgestone corporate offices will move from Tennessee,
the consolidation does not affect its tire manufacturing plant in
LaVergne, Tenn., which employs about 1,800 workers, and plans for a
$50 million radial truck tire plant in Warren County, Tenn., Allen
said.
   Bridgestone (Canada), in Mississauga, Ont., will also report to
the new headquarters.
   John J. Nevin, Firestone chairman and chief executive officer,
has been named chairman of the board of directors of
Bridgestone-Firestone. Allen said Nevin has plans to retire Jan. 1,
1990, and intends to remain in Chicago.
   The Tokyo-based Bridgestone completed its acquisition of
Firestone in April of last year by paying $80 per share for all
Firestone stock. Firestone became Bridgestone's wholly owned
subsidiary.
</TEXT>
