<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-MCorp     08-01 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-MCorp,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCorp Says Its Five Remaining Banks Earned $1.5 Million In Second
Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: MCorp, no period, is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp, the bank holding company stripped of most
of its banks by federal regulators, said Tuesday it earned $1.5
million in the second quarter, its first full quarter of operation
after the reorganization.
   The company, which has filed for Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy
protection, was left with five banks after the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. seized 20 MBanks in Texas on March 28. The rescue
is expected to be the second most expensive thrift bailout in the
nation's history.
   Those five banks earned $1.5 million, or 3 cents per share, in
the three month ended June 30, the company said.
   In the first three months this year, the same five banks had a
loss of $34 million, MCorp said, releasing the numbers for the
first time Tuesday.
   The losses during that period reflected a ``very harsh''
examination by federal regulators, who forced the company to write
down assets more severely that bank officials thought necessary,
MCorp spokesman Joe Stroop said.
   ``We took a big hit in the first quarter that in our view should
not occur again,'' he said.
   Deposits at the five banks fell from $2.75 billion at year's end
to $2.62 billion on March 31 and $2.5 billion on June 30.
   Assets dropped from $3.5 billion at the end of 1988 to $3.1
billion on March 31 and $3.06 billion on June 30. Non-performing
assets were $167 million in the second quarter, up from $147
million in the first quarter and $130 million at the beginning of
the year.
   MCorp's five banks are in Brownsville, Corpus Christi, El Paso,
New Braunfels and Waco. The company includes a statewide trust and
investment subsidiary.
   After operating the 20 MBanks as Deposit Insurance Bridge Bank
since the takeover, the FDIC sold the bank to Banc One Corp. of
Ohio. The resulting Bank One Texas has assets of about $13 billion,
although that could drop to about $10 billion after bad assets are
pruned.
   The FDIC has estimated the bailout could end up costing as much
as $2.3 billion, ranking second only to last year's rescue of First
RepublicBank Corp., with an estimated cost of $3 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
