<FIRST>u f AM-Simmons-Lockheed 1stLd-Writethru f0240 08-01 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Simmons-Lockheed, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0240,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texan Harold Simmons Ups Stake in Lockheed Corp.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Earlier this ...,' to DELETE reference to B-2
designation, which applies to a different plane made by another company.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas billionaire Harold C. Simmons said
Tuesday he had increased his stake in defense contractor Lockheed
Corp. to 9.46 percent.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, a group
of Simmons-controlled concerns headed by Valhi Corp. stated they
now hold more than 6 million shares, or 9.46 percent, of Lockheed's
common stock.
   That's an increase from an 8.03 percent stake reported July 17
by Simmons, one of Lockheed's largest individual shareholders.
   The latest SEC filing did not state why Simmons had increased
his holdings, indicating the reason had not changed since a June 12
filing.
   In that filing, when he acquired 6.25 percent of Lockheed,
Simmons said he was buying the defense contractor's shares ``for
purposes of investment and in order to acquire a significant equity
interest in the company.''
   Equity is the ownership interest shareholders possess in a
corporation.
   In the June filing, Simmons denied having immediate plans to
take over the company by stock ownership or other means _ although
he didn't discount such a move in the future.
   Earlier this year, Simmons, a Dallas billionaire with holdings
in the chemical, timber and sugar industries, revealed he had a 5.3
percent stake in Lockheed, the Calabasas, Calif.-based maker of the
stealth jet fighter.
   That disclosure prompted Lockheed to create an employee stock
ownership plan (ESOP) that in effect blocked any takeover attempt
under Delaware law. Lockheed is incorporated in Delaware.
   The day after Lockheed created the ESOP, Simmons, whose worth is
estimated by Fortune magazine at $1.5 billion, reduced his holdings
from 5.3 percent to 4.2 percent.
   According to the latest SEC filing, Valhi Inc. controls 3.4
million, or 5.49 percent, of Lockheed. Valhi also controls NL
Industries Inc., which holds 1.29 million Lockheed shares, or 2.04
percent, and NL Chemicals, which holds 1.22 million, or 1.93
percent.
   NL Industries and NL Chemicals have purchased more than 909,000
Lockheed shares since July 17 for between $47.50 and $49, according
to the SEC filing.
</TEXT>
