<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 1958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PrimeComputer     08-01 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Makes New Offer for Prime's Minicomputer Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. of Tustin, Calif., offered
Tuesday to buy Prime Computer Inc.'s minicomputer business for $525
million in cash, replacing its previous offer of a mixture of cash
and securities.
   The new, all-cash offer expires Aug. 9, the date of Prime's
annual meeting, which has been delayed twice because of a takeover
battle with MAI.
   MAI previously offered $450 million in cash, plus debentures
with a 15{ percent interest rate and a face value of $150 million,
for the minicomputer division.
   MAI's offer conflicts with an agreement by Prime's board of
directors to sell the entire company to J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., a New
York venture capital firm, for about $1.2 billion.
   Prime, based in suburban Natick, makes minicomputers and
computer-aided design and manufacturing systems. It has 11,200
employees and had revenues of $1.6 billion last year. The
minicomputer business accounted for about one-third of those
revenues.
   Prime spokesman Joseph Gavaghan said the company's board would
meet to review the new offer.
   Analysts have said the Whitney merger could be endangered by
Prime's continuing flow of red ink, including a $19 million loss in
the quarter that ended June 30. Two banks asked Whitney to obtain
additional financing for the deal in the wake of that loss.
   MAI, controlled by New York investor Bennett S. LeBow, launched
a hostile bid last November to buy all of Prime for about $970
million. But it gave up that offer in the wake of Prime's agreement
to merge with J.H. Whitney in a deal negotiated by Prime management.
   Prime shares closed down 50 cents Tuesday at $15.75 in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
