<FIRST>r f BC-FNN-Wheeler     08-01 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FNN-Wheeler,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheeler Named to Head Financial News Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial News Network Inc. said Tuesday that
Michael Wheeler, who formerly was in charge of its business and
financial news programming, has been named president of the cable
network company.
   As president, Wheeler will also have responsibility for the
company's sports information service called FNN:Score and its stock
market quotes and information service called FNN: Data Broadcasting.
   He succeeds David Meister, who has been in charge of FNN since
December 1986 and assumed the title of FNN president in early 1988.
   Financial News Network has been expanding its business and
financial news service over the past few months, dropping a home
shopping service that once ran in the overnight hours on the
channel and trimming the time allotted for sports programming.
   Those changes were made as established cable networks such as
Cable News Network beefed up their business news coverage and a new
cable network, called the Consumer News and Business Channel, was
launched with backing from the National Broadcasting Co., which
operates the NBC Television Network.
   FNN officials said their network lost 2 million cable
subscribers when CNBC made its debut in mid-April but that they
have since recaptured about 750,000 of them and added nearly 2
million more as part of the network's normal growth.
   FNN currently is on cable systems with about 33 million
subscribers, while CNBC is on systems with about 13 million
subscribers.
   Wheeler, 38, has been with FNN for more than two years. He
previously worked for CBS Inc., Meredith Corp., Warner Amex
Satellite Entertainment Co. and the Showtime Networks.
   Meister, 49, has been given new responsibilities for strategic
planning at Infotechnology Inc., which owns a controlling stake in
FNN. He retains his title as executive vice president at
Infotechnology, and remains on its board.
   ``This move is clearly a reflection of the progress of FNN,''
Meister said in a telephone interview.
   In a separate announcement, Infotechnology said it had divided
its operations into four new operating groups: technical products
and services; information and news products; marketing services;
and media networks.
   ``These changes in Infotech's operations are a key part of our
business plan, as we look forward to completing our translation
from a business development company into an operating company,''
said John F. Berentson, Infotechnology's chief operating officer.
   FNN's Wheeler will head the media networks group, which includes
Infotechnology's interests in FNN, an FNN business radio network
and The Learning Channel, another cable TV network.
   Joseph K. Taussig was named to head the information and news
products group, which includes Infotechnology's interest in United
Press International.
   Infotechnology acquired WNW Group in March. WNW Group's
principal assets were a proxy to vote substantially all of the
stock owned by New UPI Inc., the parent of United Press
International, and an irrevocable option to acquire shares that
would result in the ownership of 99 percent of New UPI.
   James R. Pompa will head the technical products and services
group and Alan Vera will head the marketing services group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
