<FIRST>r f AM-WarnerBankruptcy 2ndLd-Writethru f0219 08-01 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner Bankruptcy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0219,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trustee: Warner Trying to Settle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `Warner, reached ... is offering,' with 3 new
grafs to UPDATE with Warner comment to a newspaper; picks up 10th graf
pvs, ``There is ...''.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trustee for a Florida federal bankruptcy
court says millionaire businessman Marvin Warner is trying to
strike a deal with creditors to prevent the seizure and sale of
Warner's assets.
   But trustee Daniel L. Bakst, a West Palm Beach, Fla., lawyer,
said he will not let the 11th-hour settlement efforts interfere
with his assignment to track down Warner's assets for distribution
to creditors.
   ``Mr. Warner wants to stop me,'' Bakst said in an interview with
The Cincinnati Post published Tuesday. ``Just because Warner is
flopping around trying to make deals doesn't mean I can't do my
job. We are going forward.''
   Warner, 70, who owned the failed Home State Savings Bank of
Cincinnati, had filed in October 1987 a petition for protection
from his creditors under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act.
Warner, who now lives in Ocala, Fla., and filed the petition in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Jacksonville, Fla., sought protection from
creditors seeking more than $4 billion from him.
   Home State's March 1985 collapse precipitated a crisis among
Ohio thrifts. Warner's creditors include the state of Ohio, which
obtained a March 1987 court order that Warner pay back to the state
$22 million needed to guarantee Home State deposits.
   Warner, a former U.S. ambassador to Switzerland, was convicted
on Ohio felony charges in Home State's collapse, but was acquitted
of federal charges in a separate trial. He is appealing the Ohio
convictions.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge George Proctor on Friday authorized
appointment of Bakst as trustee. On Monday, Proctor signed an order
that converted Warner's Chapter 11 reorganization to a Chapter 7
proceeding. Bakst is to conduct a meeting of lawyers for Warner and
the creditors Aug. 24 in Jacksonville.
   Warner, reached by phone at his Ocala home Tuesday, declined
comment. However, he told a newspaper in his Florida home town that
he is not trying to impede any court proceeding.
   ``During all of this litigation I have never impeded any of the
proper procedures in any way,'' Warner told the Ocala Star-Banner.
He declined to comment further.
   One of Warner's lawyers, Andrew Hall of Miami, Fla., confirmed
Tuesday that Warner is trying to settle the case. Hall said he did
not know the amount of money Warner is offering.
   ``There is a very substantial offer being made,'' Hall said. ``I
understand they're working on it. If they work this out, it's all
over.''
   Hall said any settlement would have to be approved by the judge
and then would be subject to acceptance by his creditors.
   Lawrence Kane Jr. of Cincinnati, Ohio's special prosecutor in
the Home State case, declined comment on any settlement
possibilities. Proctor ruled in August 1988 that Warner's
bankruptcy reorganization would not allow him to avoid paying
restitution to Ohio. Kane said that judgment would not be affected
by any Warner settlement.
   ``There is no one who can compromise that judgment,'' Kane said.
``That debt is still outstanding, and we intend to collect it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
