<DOCNO> AP890801-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HomeShopping-GTE 1stLd-Writethru f0222 08-01 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Shopping-GTE, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0222,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Blames Home Shopping Newtwork for Own Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The case ...,' to UPDATE with deliberations
continuing Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Shopping Network's $1.5 billion
lawsuit accusing GTE Corp. of failing to provide adequate equipment
to handle a large volume of calls went to a jury Tuesday.
   In closing arguments, a GTE attorney blamed HSN's telephone
problems on the video retailer's failure to inform GTE officials in
advance of plans to enter 11 new markets in 1986.
   The case went to the six-member jury after a six-week trial
before Pinellas Circuit Judge Howard Rives. After about two hours,
the panel was excused, with deliberations to continue Wednesday
morning.
   Home Shopping attorneys said in final arguments Monday that GTE
told ``little white lies'' to the network to cover up the
communications company's failure to provide for the volume of calls
in 1986 and 1987.
   But GTE attorney Roy Reardon said Tuesday that HSN said in a
Dec. 2, 1986, letter that the telephone company had been
``responsive to all our previous needs'' and was lookimg forward
``to continuing this highly successful relationship.''
   Ten months later, HSN filed suit claiming it lost millions of
calls and some $500 million in potential sales because the GTE
telephone network equipment was ineffective.
   Named as defendants were the Stamford, Conn.-based parent
company, its Florida subsidiary and GTE Communications. GTE has
filed a slander and libel counterclaim that blamed HSN's decline in
the electronics market and stock market on mismanagement.
   Reardon said HSN's purchase of 11 UHF stations in new markets,
combined with its entrance in the cable television market, caused
the number of subscribers to soar from 9 million to 46.5 million in
one year.
   He said GTE knew about the cable arrangements. A $1 million
stock option offered to cable companies enhanced their interest in
HSN, he said, and 70 cable outlets were obtained.
   But even when HSN made its initial public stock offering on May
13, 1986, the company failed to mention plans to purchase the UHF
stations as a second operational network, Reardon argued.
   He said an HSN official warned in September 1986 that the
network didn't have enough people to answer the growing number of
calls, but board chairman Roy Speer ``didn't want to hear they
needed more operators.''
   Competition from similar retailers also has led to HSN's decline
in sales, Reardon said.
   Responding to HSN charges GTE didn't mention the overload
problem to protect its business, Reardon said HSN was aware of
alternative services before it contracted with GTE in 1985.
   When club members rose to 126,000 in November 1985, he said, HSN
signed contracts to purchase three OMNI automatic call distribution
systems from GTE.
   The first was installed in the middle of Februrary 1986, and HSN
launched its UHF network with the second OMNI on March 1, about 10
weeks before going public.
</TEXT>
