<FILEID>AP-NR-08-01-89 2130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     08-01 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Lower in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dropped in early trading against
the Japanese yen Wednesday, while share prices were marginally
lower.
   The dollar opened at 135.58 yen, down 1.07 yen from Tuesday's
close of 136.65 yen. The dollar closed at 135.93 yen in New York
overnight, down from Monday's finish of 136.94 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's drop followed the release
Tuesday of the monthly report of the National Association of
Purchasing Management, which showed weakness in U.S. manufacturing.
   The report showed that the Purchasing Managers' Index fell from
48.8 percent in June to 46 percent last month, the lowest level
since January 1983.
   ``The latest report indicated that the American economy is
surely entering a slowdown,'' said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   The dealer, who spoke anonymously, said the market was moving in
anticipation of a further U.S. interest rate decline.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 55.41 points Tuesday, shed another 20.72 points,
or 0.05 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to
34,877.74 points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
